<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> `Frostcast' Drives Grain, Soybean / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Grain and soybean futures advanced Wednesday on  
the Chicago Board of Trade after a private forecaster predicted an 
early freeze in the Midwest this fall. 
</P>
<P>
	The gains came on the strength of a late rally after  
Freese/Notis released the early frost forecast, according to 
traders. 
</P>
<P>
	The price rises were modest on a quiet trading day, however.  
Many investors expressed skepticism in the reliability of the 
long-range forecast or said a frost might actually be beneficial by 
drying out a corn crop expected to be early. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for December delivery rose 2 cents to $2.86 1/2 per bushel;  
December corn rose 3 1/4 to $2.19 3/4 per bushel; December oats rose 1 1/2 
cents to $1.15 1/4 per bushel; and November soybeans rose 8 1/2 cents to 
$4.75 1/2 per bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Beef futures advanced on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange, while  
pork futures were mixed. 
</P>
<P>
	October live cattle rose .55 cent to 65.45 cents per pound;  
October feeder cattle rose .68 cent to 78.55 cents per pound; 
October lean hogs rose .33 cent to 46.20 cents per pound, while 
pork bellies fell 1.50 cents to 59.30 cents per pound. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
