<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dye's Arm Regains Nerve Function </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FLAGSTAFF, Ariz. (AP) -- Ernest Dye has regained some nerve  
function in his right arm, but the doctors who saved it still don't 
know if the Arizona Cardinals offensive tackle will enjoy full use 
of the limb again. 
</P>
<P>
	``We continue to be hopeful that he will have more function in  
the future,'' vascular surgeon Jerry Mohr said Wednesday. ``The arm 
is viable. Time will be the test.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dye's arm was nearly severed on Aug. 16, when a car driven by  
teammate Lester Holmes skidded off Interstate 17 about 25 miles 
south of Flagstaff and rolled over, pinning Dye to the ground. 
</P>
<P>
	Holmes, a starting offensive guard, gashed his forehead in the  
crash and is not expected to return to action until the regular 
season, and defensive lineman Carl Simpson bruised his hip. 
</P>
<P>
	Both escaped the catastrophic injuries that may have ended the  
career of Dye, a first-round draft choice in 1993. 
</P>
<P>
	The Cardinals declined comment on Dye's football future, and  
team spokesman Paul Jensen said that was secondary to his health 
problems. 
</P>
<P>
	``Ernest's welfare should remain the sole focus of attention.  
The Cardinals join their fans in offering their prayers for his 
recovery,'' Jensen said. 
</P>
<P>
	Feeling will not return to the arm for months, Mohr told  
reporters at Flagstaff Medical Center. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a very contaminated wound that was cleaned out  
vigorously,'' he said. ``Antibiotics and time along with dressing 
changes (will be critical).'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dye underwent a nine-hour operation immediately after the  
accident to repair a bone in his arm and restore blood flow. 
</P>
<P>
	In a seven-hour operation Sunday at the Flagstaff hospital, Mohr  
and orthopedic surgeon Philip Mack performed a second surgery to 
repair the median and ulnar nerves, which control hand and 
lower-arm function. 
</P>
<P>
	In order to do that, the doctors had to graft nerves in Dye's  
lower legs to the damaged nerves in his arm. That enabled them to 
bridge the severed nerves and restore some function in the arm. 
</P>
<P>
	Mohr said blood and air seeped into Dye's chest cavity after the  
second surgery. It wasn't known how serious that complication might 
be, but the doctors said his overall health seemed to be improving. 
</P>
<P>
	Dye will be hospitalized in Flagstaff, where the team holds its  
training camp, for at least two more weeks. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
