<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Battered Braves Keep on Winning </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- John Smoltz is starting to feel like it's 1991  
all over again. 
</P>
<P>
	The Atlanta Braves no longer have the look of a dominating team.  
Cancer took away their top hitter, while injuries sidelined their 
best reliever and All-Star catcher. 
</P>
<P>
	Those who remain would have been perfect extras for ``MASH,''  
filling the hospital beds behind Hawkeye and Trapper John. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, despite an epidemic of injuries, the Braves are rolling  
along with the best mark in the major leagues (79-49), intent on 
keeping alive their record streak of playoff appearances. 
</P>
<P>
	In a decade of excellence, this might be their most impressive  
performance since the one that got it all started -- the 
worst-to-first of '91. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're just scratching and clawing,'' said Smoltz, who allowed  
only four hits in eight innings Tuesday night as the Braves won 
their sixth in a row, 6-4 over the Cincinnati Reds. ``We don't have 
a team like 1991, but that's the kind of mentality we have. We need 
everybody to win.'' 
</P>
<P>
	They don't have everybody. The medical report includes Smoltz  
(tender elbow), Greg Maddux (chipped bone in his pitching hand), 
Rudy Seanez (stress fracture in his pitching elbow), Kevin Millwood 
(sore back) and Brian Jordan (aching wrist). 
</P>
<P>
	And those are the lucky ones. Andres Galarraga, Kerry  
Ligtenberg, Javy Lopez and Odalis Perez are done for the year, the 
first two without ever playing a game. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've had our share of injuries, but you can't worry about  
it,'' Bret Boone said. ``Of course, if we had Andres Galarraga, 
Kerry Ligtenberg, Javy Lopez and Odalis Perez, we'd be a better 
team. But you can't control those things.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Braves, 1 1/2 games ahead of the New York Mets in the NL East,  
got an indication of what type of season it would be before it 
began. 
</P>
<P>
	Galarraga, who hit .305 with 44 homers and 121 RBIs last season,  
was diagnosed with cancer in his back just before the start of 
spring training. While expected to make a full recovery, the Big 
Cat had to sit out the year to undergo treatment. 
</P>
<P>
	Then, in the early days of spring training, Ligtenberg felt a  
twinge in his right elbow. Doctors discovered a partially torn 
ligament, meaning the Braves would have to replace the pitcher who 
became the first rookie in 12 years to save 30 games. 
</P>
<P>
	Moving on without their best hitter and top reliever, the Braves  
moved Ryan Klesko to first and 24-year-old John Rocker into the 
closer's role. Klesko was hitting .305 with 18 homers and 68 RBIs, 
while Rocker has 27 saves and seems assured of surpassing 
Ligtenberg's numbers. 
</P>
<P>
	But there would be more holes to fill.  
</P>
<P>
	Lopez, a two-time All-Star catcher who had 34 homers and 106  
RBIs in 1998, hobbled for a couple of weeks on a sore right knee 
before succumbing to season-ending surgery in late July. The Braves 
promptly traded for Greg Myers. 
</P>
<P>
	The same day Lopez's season ended, the Braves learned the  
21-year-old Perez, their fifth starter, would need surgery to 
repair a torn medial collateral ligament in his left elbow. Like 
Ligtenberg, he'll be out at least 12 months. 
</P>
<P>
	So, at the July 31 trade deadline, Atlanta acquired left-hander  
Terry Mulholland from the Chicago Cubs. He has been a valuable 
addition both starting and relieving. 
</P>
<P>
	Smoltz went more than two months without a win -- a streak that  
ended Tuesday night -- and twice went to the DL with lingering 
problems in his right elbow, which has undergone two operations 
since 1994. He is now trying to cope by altering his pitching 
motion. 
</P>
<P>
	Maddux (16-6) chipped a bone in his right wrist diving for a  
pop-up last Saturday. The four-time Cy Young winner will likely 
miss his next start, at St. Louis on Friday night, but the injury 
is not believed to be serious. 
</P>
<P>
	Batting in the cleanup spot formerly occupied by Galarraga,  
Jordan has 100 RBIs for the first time in his career even though 
he's been plagued with various maladies. At one point, his entire 
right side was hurting. For now, his right wrist aches every time 
he swings. 
</P>
<P>
	``It hurts,'' Jordan said, ``but that's a pain I've got to deal  
with.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Seanez wasn't as fortunate. A valuable middle reliever (56  
games, 6-1, 3.35 ERA, three saves), he felt a strange pain in his 
elbow last week, underwent a bone scan and learned that he has a 
stress fracture. 
</P>
<P>
	Seanez was placed on the DL for the seventh time in his career,  
but he expects to return after resting a couple of weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think we've proven we can win with whoever is on the field,  
whoever is on the mound,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	David Cortes, called up to replace Seanez, had 22 saves at  
Triple-A Richmond, but has been troubled by injuries in his career. 
</P>
<P>
	He'll fit right in with this team.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
