<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> A-10 Bomb Search Renewed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- The Air Force renewed the search Wednesday for the  
four bombs from the suicide crash of an A-10 warplane two years ago 
after a hiker spotted an object wedged between the rocks high in 
the Rockies. 
</P>
<P>
	The cylindrical object with a tailfin was spotted about eight  
miles south of where Capt. Craig Button's plane went down. 
</P>
<P>
	``The way she described it, it is worth to go up and look at  
it,'' said Capt. Robyn Chumley, a spokeswoman for Langley Air Force 
Base in Virginia. 
</P>
<P>
	The hiker led an Air Force officer, a civilian engineer and a  
forest ranger on the search. 
</P>
<P>
	Button's attack jet, carrying four 500-pound bombs from  
Davis-Monthan Air Force Base in Tucson, Ariz., broke formation 
during a training mission with two other planes on April 2, 1997. 
For three hours, Button flew an erratic 500-mile course that ended 
when he crashed into the 13,000-foot Gold Dust Peak near Eagle, 
Colo. 
</P>
<P>
	Air Force investigators concluded he committed suicide. The  
wreckage was found after an 18-day search. But there was no trace 
of the bombs, despite a 72-day search. 
</P>
<P>
	The unidentified hiker discovered the object in the fall, but  
snow and the threat of avalanches prevented officials from heading 
up Whitney Mountain until this week. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
