<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 3 Students at 1 School Kill Selves </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ANTIOCH, Calif. (AP) -- A 16-year-old boy became the third  
student in four months from one high school to kill himself with a 
gun, although school officials said there's no reason to think the 
deaths are linked. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're grieving,'' Principal Dee Hopfenspirger said Wednesday.  
``We're very concerned. We're very concerned about our students and 
why they would hurt themselves.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The first suicide at Deer Valley High School was in May. The  
second was two weeks ago. The latest death was Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Crisis counselors were at the school this week to help students  
deal with the anguish of losing so many classmates in such a short 
period of time. 
</P>
<P>
	``Sometimes with suicide there's what's called a contagion  
effect, where one suicide produces a copycat effect,'' said John 
Bateson, executive director of a crisis center. 
</P>
<P>
	The nation's teen suicide rate has tripled in 20 years and is  
the third-leading cause of death for that age group, following 
accidents and homicides, according to the federal Centers for 
Disease Control and Prevention. 
</P>
<P>
	In May, an Associated Press review found that more than a third  
of California's 999 school districts had no counselors and no 
psychologists on staff to spot or help troubled children in the 
1997-1998 school year. An additional 70 districts had fewer than 
one full-time counselor or psychologist, the AP reported. 
</P>
<P>
	California schools are far from the only ones dealing with teen  
suicide. 
</P>
<P>
	In Monticello, Ga., a 16-year-old Jasper County High School  
sophomore fatally shot herself in the school's parking lot just 
after classes began Wednesday, authorities said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
