<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Editorial Roundup  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Here are excerpts from recent editorials in newspapers in the  
United States and abroad: 

</P>
<P>
	Aug. 23  
</P>
<P>
	The State, Columbia, S.C., on presidential candidate John  
McCain: 
</P>
<P>
	Presidential candidate John McCain, a U.S. senator from Arizona,  
wasn't even in the Iowa straw poll ... but as far as we're 
concerned, he emerged stronger than anyone who was. 
</P>
<P>
	First, McCain won points for character for speaking the truth  
about Iowa's role in the presidential contest. He refused to 
participate in the nonbinding vote, which represents only a small, 
self-selected and unrepresentative group of Iowa Republicans. He 
correctly called it a ``sham and a joke'' because the tiny group of 
participants could be easily targeted and influenced by candidates 
with the most money -- Texas Gov. George W. Bush and Forbes magazine 
publisher Steve Forbes. ... 
</P>
<P>
	One thing is certain: The Republicans this year have no shortage  
of good candidates. Not only are McCain, Bush and Forbes credible, 
but former Transportation Secretary Elizabeth Dole and conservative 
Gary Bauer help ensure a multiplicity of viewpoints. If candidates 
stick to issues, this could be the most worthwhile contest for the 
Republican presidential nomination in years. 

</P>
<P>
	Aug. 24  
</P>
<P>
	NewsPress, Stillwater, Okla., on Iowa straw poll:  
</P>
<P>
	Say what you will of the Iowa straw poll, there is a lesson to  
be learned from it for Oklahoma: do not follow the recommendation 
of Lance Ward, secretary of the state Election Board. Ward 
recommends abolishing the state's presidential primary and 
replacing it with the caucus system. Bad idea. 
</P>
<P>
	It's true, the Iowa straw poll was a non-binding political event  
(the caucuses won't be held until early next year). That, however, 
didn't keep it from almost immediately ending the presidential 
ambitions of Lamar Alexander and sending others (like Dan Quayle) 
into a nose dive. While the ``real'' elections will come later, the 
straw poll demonstrated why presidential primaries are better than 
the caucus system. ... 
</P>
<P>
	Do we want the presidential winnowing process decided by who can  
afford to bus the most people to an event, pay them to vote, hire 
celebrities to entertain them, and provide them with the most 
comfortable surroundings? ... 

</P>
<P>
	Aug. 24  
</P>
<P>
	St. Petersburg (Fla.) Times, on Texas Gov. George W. Bush:  
</P>
<P>
	In the absence of a shred of evidence that Texas Gov. George W.  
Bush ever used cocaine, Bush would have had every right to stick to 
his original pledge not to answer questions on the subject. ... 
</P>
<P>
	However, character is a relevant issue in presidential campaigns  
-- and the debris of the Clinton presidency will make questions of 
character more important than usual in 2000. ... 
</P>
<P>
	In any case, the public generally is more realistic, and less  
hypocritical, than politicians or the press about such issues. ... 
</P>
<P>
	Voters and reporters might have reasonable questions about how  
Gov. Bush's personal history jibes with his support for tough drug 
laws in Texas. ... 
</P>
<P>
	They might also wonder how the candidate with the best staff  
money can buy could stumble so badly over simple questions about 
cocaine. The stumbles raise larger questions about whether Gov. 
Bush has the maturity, judgment and temperament to be president. 
Voters will make that decision based on what is in his heart and 
between his ears -- not what might have gone up his nose long ago. 

</P>
<P>
	Aug. 19  
</P>
<P>
	The Monitor, McAllen, Texas, on a Hillary Clinton visit:  
</P>
<P>
	She came. She saw. She took the money and ran.  
</P>
<P>
	Hillary Rodham Clinton breezed into McAllen Wednesday morning,  
to share breakfast with Rio Grande Valley supporters and to pass a 
plate of her own -- a collection plate. Only supporters willing to 
pay $1,000 per plate were invited to the breakfast. ... 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton's visit here and other Texas cities was strictly to  
raise money for a Senate race she hasn't entered officially. She 
had no time for the public, much of which has stood behind her for 
nearly a decade, throughout her and her husband's various personal, 
political and legal peccadilloes. No comments as she stepped off 
the plane, no waves from the motorcade, no words of thanks as she 
left. ... 
</P>
<P>
	The everyday people who have defended her all these years, in  
the Valley and elsewhere, deserve more than a fleeting glimpse from 
afar. Clinton could have -- and should have -- taken a couple of 
minutes to make a public statement. The fact that she did not deem 
the people worthy of such attention makes one wonder if she would 
use a seat in Congress to serve the people, or only to serve 
herself. 

</P>
<P>
	 *MORE  
</P>
<P>
 *BC-Editorial Rdp, 1st add,0743 
</P>
<P>
 *UNDATED: serve herself.    	

</P>
<P>
	Aug. 25  
</P>
<P>
	The New York Times, on Federal Reserve:  
</P>
<P>
	The Federal Reserve Board is acting cautiously in trying to slow  
the American economy and head off a resurgence of inflation. 
Investors appear to be confident that such a gradual approach will 
have a minimal impact on the economy. In the near term, they are 
probably right. ... 
</P>
<P>
	The Fed is acting responsibly in trying to slow the economy  
gradually. President Clinton and Congress should cooperate by 
pursuing a lean fiscal policy. In particular, as Mr. Greenspan has 
asked, they should avoid tax cuts that would unnecessarily 
stimulate the economy and increase the chances that the Fed will 
have to raise interest rates again. 

</P>
<P>
	Aug. 22  
</P>
<P>
	San Antonio Express-News, on children's health bill:  
</P>
<P>
	The Clinton administration is sending auditors to every state to  
investigate whether they have improperly excluded people 
particularly children from health care, either from Medicaid, the 
health-care program for the poor, or from the federal Children's 
Health Insurance Program, created by Congress in 1997 to cover 
other uninsured children. 
</P>
<P>
	While CHIP won't start in Texas until next spring, the state has  
1.4 million children without health insurance. Experts told The 
Dallas Morning News that nearly 600,000 poor Texas children 
eligible for Medicaid are not enrolled. 
</P>
<P>
	... Physicians in Bexar County, where there are 104,000  
Medicaid-eligible children, long have complained that the 
application for Medicaid is so complicated that many families do 
not fill it out. ... 
</P>
<P>
	Architects of Texas CHIP are promising an application form that  
is simpler than that for the Medicaid plan. ... 
</P>
<P>
	No child, no matter his or her circumstances, should be denied  
adequate health care. The Medicaid audit is necessary nit-picking. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, Texas should design a user-friendly CHIP to cover the  
rest of its uninsured future taxpayers. 

</P>
<P>
	Aug. 23  
</P>
<P>
	Star Tribune of Minneapolis, on mystery object in sky:  
</P>
<P>
	... It is the nature of science ... to solve mysteries, and the  
nature of technological advance to build our capacity for 
classifying the universe, bit by bit, into increasingly neater 
piles. 
</P>
<P>
	But now and then comes a reminder that we haven't got it all  
mapped and sorted yet. ... One of these arrived last week in news 
accounts of an odd little light in the northern constellation 
Serpens, which some of the world's best astronomers have been 
squinting at for three years now. Despite their best efforts, its 
identity remains uncertain; it may be a completely new type of 
celestial body. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysis of its light has more or less established that it is  
neither star nor galaxy. Some scientists think these readings kind 
of, sort of, resemble those of quasars -- those odd energy centers 
that inhabit black holes -- but others disagree. ... 
</P>
<P>
	(The mystery object) doesn't fade or grow brighter. It doesn't  
collapse or explode. It sits still ... complicating the efforts of 
astronomers to reckon even whether it is in our galactic 
neighborhood or far, far away. 
</P>
<P>
	On its own, the object is an intriguing puzzle. In the context  
of advancing astronomical technology, it is the likely harbinger of 
many more mysteries to come as our instruments grow more powerful 
and our techniques more sophisticated. As the century nears an end, 
we humans seem poised not so much on the verge of explaining all we 
can behold, but of beholding a universe whose diversity well 
exceeds our current understanding. ... 

</P>
<P>
	Aug. 21  
</P>
<P>
	The (Cleveland) Plain Dealer, on fugitive investor:  
</P>
<P>
	One would think that Martin R. Frankel, the fugitive U.S.  
investor who fled to Europe after allegedly stealing up to $300 
million from insurance companies, would be cowering in a hotel, 
afraid that room service might come courtesy of the FBI. 
</P>
<P>
	But thanks to creaking intercontinental bureaucracies, Frankel  
has been handed a fugitive's greatest gift -- time. 
</P>
<P>
	He has spent it moving through France, Spain and Italy, staying  
well ahead of la policia even though his poster has been faxed to 
170 countries belonging to Interpol, the international police 
organization. 
</P>
<P>
	No doubt about it, a little international cooperation among law  
enforcement could have cut Frankel's Roman holiday short and 
brought him back to face a U.S. judge. 

</P>
<P>
	 *MORE  
</P>
<P>
 *BC-Editorial Rdp, 2nd add,0016 
</P>
<P>
 *UNDATED: U.S. judge.    	

</P>
<P>
	Aug. 21  
</P>
<P>
	Asahi Shimbun, Tokyo, on earthquake in Turkey:  
</P>
<P>
	It is said that the probability of rescuing anyone alive in such  
circumstances suddenly drops 72 hours after disaster has struck. 
Relief work requires promptness more than anything else. The relief 
team (from Japan) achieved success partly because it promptly left 
Japan as soon as it learned of the earthquake. 
</P>
<P>
	However, promptness alone does not assure success in relief  
work. Other indispensable measures after initial emergency work 
include medium-term assistance for the treatment of injured 
persons, prevention of epidemics and assistance to citizens so they 
can get on with their daily lives. 
</P>
<P>
	... As shown by the Great Hanshin Earthquake, there is no quick  
fix to rebuilding devastated areas and getting survivors back on 
their feet. The Turkish economy is faltering because of the 
economic crisis in Russia, a key trading partner. The earthquake 
just adds to the country's woes. The survivors will find it very 
hard to rebuild their lives. ... 

</P>
<P>
	Aug. 24  
</P>
<P>
	Le Matin, Lausanne, Switzerland, on earthquake in Turkey:  
</P>
<P>
	Turkey is part of the developing world. It isn't rich enough to  
face alone the massive destruction of the Izmit region, the 
country's industrial heart. 
</P>
<P>
	Without massive aid, it will be unable to rebuild not just its  
factories, but also its infrastructure -- roads, bridges, water and 
electricity systems. 
</P>
<P>
	The wounds that World War II inflicted on Europe and Japan were  
healed thanks to that American balm, the Marshall Plan. ... 
</P>
<P>
	Ankara also would like to turn disaster into victory. It is  
counting on the wave of solidarity that followed the earthquake 
when even traditional enemies, such as Greece and Iraq, rushed to 
its bedside. 
</P>
<P>
	But the gap between this spontaneous help and Turkey's needs is  
enormous. 
</P>
<P>
	Sums are needed that Western countries can't even give, because  
Ankara is not alone in seeking money. 
</P>
<P>
	The countries hit by last year's Hurricane Mitch or by the Asian  
and Russian financial crises, to name but a few, are all waiting 
for these funds which will allow them to move forward. 

</P>
<P>
	Aug. 24  
</P>
<P>
	The Daily Telegraph, London, on Slobodan Milosevic:  
</P>
<P>
	Since Slobodan Milosevic turned himself from Communist  
apparatchik into nationalist leader 12 years ago, he has ruthlessly 
exploited the Serbs' exaggerated sense of victimhood. The desire to 
get their own back on their supposed tormenters has led to the 
horror of ethnic cleansing in Croatia, Bosnia-Hercegovina and 
Kosovo. But the strategy that lay behind it, the creation of a 
Greater Serbia, has dismally failed. 
</P>
<P>
	Far from strengthening their presence, the Serbs have fled  
Croatia en masse and are doing the same in Kosovo. Their status as 
perennial victims confirmed, they are now demanding the 
establishment of exclusively Serbian cantons in the province as the 
only way to protect them from Albanian revenge. They should be 
firmly rebuffed. 
</P>
<P>
	One of the principles for which NATO intervened in Bosnia and  
Kosovo was to re-establish a multi-ethnic polity whose members 
could move freely without fear of intimidation. That this ideal has 
yet to be realised points not to its invalidity, but to a lack of 
will in its implementation. In Bosnia, the alliance has been 
notoriously hesitant in enforcing the provisions of Dayton 
regarding resettlement. In Kosovo, it is manifestly unable, without 
police assistance, to guard the Serbs against Albanian attacks. 
</P>
<P>
	The answer in the second case is not to set up cantons, which  
would be a significant step towards partition, but rapidly to build 
up a domestic police force. The sooner local representatives assume 
responsibility for law and order, the better. 

</P>
<P>
	Aug. 21  
</P>
<P>
	The Nation, Bangkok, Thailand, on China and Taiwan:  
</P>
<P>
	It is not surprising at all that Taiwanese President Lee  
Teng-hui has supported the island's participation in a missile 
defense umbrella called Theater Missile Defense (TMD). ... The way 
Beijing chose to respond to its renegade province's growing 
assertiveness has not been constructive at best. When China talks 
about using force, together with leaks of military exercises, the 
whole region shivers. And that is not good for China. ... 
</P>
<P>
	Certainly the talk of war by China and its controlled media have  
helped fan the fire of Taiwanese patriotism and toughen its defense 
posture. Increased arms acquisition will come in the near future. 
Lee is a shrewd politician who knows exactly what the Kuomintang 
Party needs to win the next presidential election and how to keep 
China at bay. ... 
</P>
<P>
	China's growing frustration with Taiwan and continued  
intimidation only plays into the hands of TMD supporters both on 
the island and Japan, especially among conservative groups. ... 

</P>
<P>
	Aug. 24  
</P>
<P>
	La Repubblica, Rome, on Russian politics:  
</P>
<P>
	The alliance between Moscow Mayor Yuri Luzhkov and ex-premier  
Yevgeny Primakov is one of the most interesting developments in 
Russia's politics. The alliance seems very strong ... and it 
appears likely to get a majority in the Duma and (to elect) one of 
its candidates to the presidency of the federation. 
</P>
<P>
	It is certain, however, that in the upcoming months the  
confrontation between this party and President Boris Yeltsin's 
allies will be violent, and it will be filled with low blows from 
both sides. 
</P>
<P>
	The main actors on the political scene are what they are: but  
nobody has so far spoken out against democracy, and hopefully a new 
generation of politicians will come out after the year 2000 to 
clean up the worst aspects of Russian politics. ... 

</P>
<P>
	Aug. 23  
</P>
<P>
	The Straits Times, Singapore, on Kashmir:  
</P>
<P>
	After last month's clashes over Kashmir that left 1,000 dead,  
there were hopes that India and Pakistan would have been 
sufficiently worn out not to have stomach for another call to 
action stations. Dream on. Five days before their common 52nd 
anniversary of independence two Sundays ago, a Pakistani 
reconnaissance plane was shot down with the loss of 16 lives. ... 
In the circumstances, it would take only the intervention of the 
United States to get the two sides to talk terms. The U.S., which 
effectively stopped the latest Kashmir skirmish, has said it would 
not mediate unless requested to by both countries. This is being 
unusually coy. 
  	   	
</P>
