<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Figure Skating Championship Moved </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LAUSANNE, Switzerland (AP) -- The international figure skating  
federation has moved next year's world championship from Brisbane, 
Australia, to the French city of Nice, an official confirmed today. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can confirm that, for technical and organizational reasons,  
the ISU council has decided to move the championships from 
Australia to Nice,'' said Aline Bussat, spokeswoman for the 
International Skating Union. 
</P>
<P>
	She declined to give details of those reasons or to say when the  
decision was made. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, Brisbane championship officials headed to Lausanne  
today for talks reportedly aimed at stopping the ISU from moving 
the March world championships to Nice because it would offer better 
television revenues. 
</P>
<P>
	Local officials said such a switch would be a financial disaster  
for Australia's Ice Skating federation. After winning the bid in 
June 1997, the Australian federation is heavily committed to 
hosting the championships at Brisbane's 12,000-seat Convention 
Center from March 18-25. 
</P>
<P>
	They said they would consider legal action if the event is  
shifted. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990825.0033 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-25 01:10:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Paterno, Lions Ready for Opener </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	STATE COLLEGE, Pa. (AP) -- Penn State had plenty of reasons to  
turn down the offer to play in the Pigskin Classic. 
</P>
<P>
	The third-ranked Nittany Lions already face one tough  
non-conference opponent, No. 12 Miami in the Orange Bowl. Their Big 
Ten schedule, meanwhile, is geared for a title run: They meet both 
No. 8 Michigan and No. 9 Ohio State in Beaver Stadium, and they 
don't face No. 10 Wisconsin at all. 
</P>
<P>
	So why risk it? Why sign up for a game against No. 4 Arizona?  
</P>
<P>
	Simple. This Penn State team can win this game -- and a lot more  
this year -- and denials aside, Joe Paterno knows it. 
</P>
<P>
	Penn State's coach insists that he didn't want to play it, that  
his team voted for the early test. 
</P>
<P>
	But he's been known to test his teams in these made-for-TV  
openers. The Lions were underdog winners over No. 7 Southern Cal in 
1997, and they beat Georgia Tech in 1991, the year after the Yellow 
Jackets finished No. 2. They once even took on a No. 1, Nebraska, 
although they were routed. 
</P>
<P>
	``In most cases, you feel like you've got a pretty good football  
team,'' Paterno said Tuesday. ``This particular year, I think we're 
a good football team.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Then, dispelling any notion that he has abandoned his tradition  
of bad-mouthing his new team before the season, he added, ``Whether 
we're as good as people think we are, I doubt it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Practice hasn't changed the quarterback situation, he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Last year's starter, Kevin Thompson, will get the nod Saturday.  
Rashard Casey -- the speedy backup recruited by Arizona a few years 
ago -- might play a little, but don't expect him to split time 
evenly with Thompson, as Arizona's Ortege Jenkins and Keith Smith 
do. 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere on offense, training camp took its toll. Cordell  
Mitchell, the probable starting tailback, pulled a hamstring and 
missed five days of drills. He started seven games in 1998 before 
being sidelined by a nerve problem in his shoulder. As he did late 
last season, Eric McCoo might start in his place Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Making matters worse in the backfield, Aaron Harris' bad luck  
continued. The fullback needed a good August workout after 
struggling in 1998 with knee trouble, but he pulled a groin muscle 
and missed a week. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've been bumped up quite a bit,'' Paterno said.  
</P>
<P>
	But if the past is any measure, he won't regret the decision to  
play Arizona. 
</P>
<P>
	``Really, there are very few negatives,'' he said. ``When you  
have a chance to prepare for a team as good as Arizona, you 
probably get a little more out of summer conditioning and preseason 
practice. Win or lose, you are probably a better football team when 
you start the next week.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Then again, he has seen it torpedo a team's confidence. After  
Nebraska thrashed Penn State -- the defending national champ -- in 
1983, the Lions lost the next three and finished 8-4-1. 
</P>
<P>
	``We overestimated ourselves in '83,'' Paterno admits. ``We  
weren't even in the same league. We were not ready to take on a 
team that was on a mission like that Nebraska team.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He would be shocked to see that happen in 1999. Both teams  
expect standout seasons. But while some consider a tough preseason 
game a step toward a national title for a Top 10 team, Paterno has 
let his team know that it usually doesn't work that way. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're a great first opponent,'' McCoo said earlier this  
month, ``but it doesn't predict what's going to happen down the 
road.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
