<DOCNO> APW19990825.0035 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-25 13:30:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pentagon Defends Missile Decision </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A senior Pentagon official who wants more  
tests of an Army anti-missile system before further development is 
done said Wednesday he supports the Defense Department's decision 
to skip further tests on the old design of the interceptor. 
</P>
<P>
	However, Philip Coyle, the department's director of operational  
test and evaluation, said a ``next generation'' of the anti-missile 
missile should receive more testing before further development or 
production. 
</P>
<P>
	``I recommend a strong ground-testing program, as well as  
long-range flight-testing,'' Coyle wrote in a memo released by the 
Pentagon. He suggested his position had been misinterpreted as 
criticism of the Pentagon decision to move to the next phase in the 
program. 
</P>
<P>
	The Pentagon announced last week that it would skip another test  
of an experimental anti-missile missile and to move to the next 
stage in the interceptor's development. 
</P>
<P>
	After six initial failures were followed by two recent  
successes, the Pentagon said it was satisfied little would be 
accomplished by additional tests of the experimental version of its 
Theater High Altitude Area Defense system, known as THAAD. 
</P>
<P>
	Coyle, commenting in the current issue of Defense Week, a trade  
publication, had said the two successful tests, carried out at the 
Army's White Sands Missile Range in New Mexico, differed from 
conditions of a real attack. He said they had been ``shaped and 
closely scripted.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He recommended more tests at a different, larger test range,  
specifically the Kwajalein Missile Range in the Marshall Islands. 
</P>
<P>
	Coyle said in his memo to his Pentagon supervisors, released  
Wednesday by his office, that he did not mean to register 
opposition to the decision to stop testing the particular missile, 
or to criticize the tests. 
</P>
<P>
	``The THAAD tests to date at White Sands Missile Range have been  
conducted carefully and professionally. These tests were important, 
necessary, and valuable, and were not `cooked' or `rigged.' The 
test limitations were unavoidable given range safety considerations 
and the maturity of the THAAD program,'' Coyle wrote. 
</P>
<P>
	However, he stuck to his recommendation that tests on a next  
generation of the missile, to be built by Lockheed Martin Corp., be 
conducted at the Kwajalein site before the Pentagon commits to 
further development of the missile or production. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
