<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Giants' DE Has Fun Playing Jets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- While many people are making a big deal out  
of the annual Giants-Jets preseason game for the so-called bragging 
rights of New York, two-time Pro Bowler Michael Strahan isn't. 
</P>
<P>
	The Giants' defensive end just hopes to improve his game a  
little on Saturday night at Giants Stadium, and laugh a lot, 
especially at Jets receiver Wayne Chrebet. 
</P>
<P>
	The two are close friends, and this is one of those games where  
there is going to be some good-natured trash talking. There might 
even be a hit or two. 
</P>
<P>
	Strahan and Chrebet reminisced about last year's big hit in a  
telephone call they had Tuesday, Strahan said. 
</P>
<P>
	Chrebet, who is 5-foot-10 and 185 pounds, tried to crack-block  
Strahan. Instead, the 6-5, 275 pounder threw him to the ground. 
</P>
<P>
	``I thought you were my friend. I'm a little disappointed in  
you,'' Strahan said in recalling the conversion. ``He said his 
stomach hurt because I did that to him. 
</P>
<P>
	``I said my stomach hurt, too, 'cause I was laughing so hard  
when you went down like that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The kidding doesn't stop on the telephone. Chrebet was quoted in  
one of the New York tabloids as saying he was going to be looking 
for Strahan to see if he got soft after his recent signing of a 
four-year, $32 million contract. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm going after him to see if he's as soft as `Chrebet Crunch'  
after sitting in milk for a half-hour,'' Strahan said, referring to 
a cereal named after the Jets' receiver. 
</P>
<P>
	With the Jets and Giants scheduled to play a regular-season game  
on Dec. 5, Strahan said neither team is going to show much in the 
preseason. 
</P>
<P>
	When asked what the regular-season game would be like if it was  
important to both teams, Strahan's eyes seemed to light up. After a 
couple of seconds, he made a sound that was a little like a short 
laugh. 
</P>
<P>
	``It would be the most trash talking I have ever heard on a  
football field in seven years,'' Strahan said. ``I would be lying 
if I didn't say I would be talking some of it myself. 
</P>
<P>
	``That would be one of the best things for the city, for the  
organization and I know one of the best things for the players to 
have a meaningful game against the Jets in December. That's pretty 
much like a dream.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Until that happens, this weekend's meeting will just be another  
Jets-Giants game, a learning experience for the players and a 
chance to make a big deal out of nothing for the fans and media. 
</P>
<P>
	For Chrebet and Strahan, it offers each a chance to yap back and  
forth after each play. 
</P>
<P>
	And it also offers them a chance to embarrass the other before  
the game. 
</P>
<P>
	Strahan could not resist talking about Chrebet's golf game on  
Wednesday. The two played before training camp opened with David 
Bryan, the keyboard player for Bon Jovi. Strahan remembered one of 
Chrebet's shots. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were down at the Shore and we thought he hit the siding on  
the house,'' Strahan said. ``Then we walked over, this woman opened 
her door and handed him his ball back. He put it right through the 
kitchen window.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The story doesn't end there.  
</P>
<P>
	Strahan said Bryan telephoned Chrebet the next week.  
</P>
<P>
	``He had his wife yelling in the background like she was the  
woman, yelling: `You broke my window. I want my money.' It was 
funny. I tell you what: he is such a nice classy good guy, you 
can't help but love him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And when Chrebet comes near him Saturday?  
</P>
<P>
	``I am going to try to get one little shot in,'' Strahan said.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
