<HEADLINE> Japanese Stocks Rise Slightly / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- The dollar fell against the yen Thursday morning,  
while Tokyo share prices rose slightly following another record 
close on Wall Street. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 111.06 yen at late morning, down 0.26 yen from  
late Wednesday in Tokyo and also below its late New York level of 
111.14 yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average gained 33.09  
points, or 0.19 percent, to 17,888.25 at the end of the morning 
session. On Wednesday, the average closed down 240.25 points, or 
1.33 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency dealings, the dollar initially was slightly higher  
from its New York level after a rally in U.S. Treasury bonds and 
the robust showing Wednesday on Wall Street attracted investor 
interest in the greenback. 
</P>
<P>
	But the dollar edged lower as enthusiasm among overseas  
investment funds for Japanese stocks emerged, thus curbing the 
dollar's rise. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was traded at 115.86 yen, down  
from 116.84 yen late Wednesday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	On the stock market, share prices posted slight gains on buying  
of some high technology issues, including Sony and Fujitsu. 
</P>
<P>
	High-tech issues led the market in early morning trading  
following strong gains by similar issues on the New York Stock 
Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	In New York on Wednesday, the Dow Jones industrial average  
finished at a record high 11,326.04 points, up 42.74, or 0.4 
percent. U.S. stocks shot up as investors expressed confidence that 
the American economy can continue to grow without high inflation. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section was up 0.92 points, or 0.06 percent, to 1,495.72. The 
TOPIX closed down 12.27 points, or 0.81 percent, the day before. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark 10-year Japanese government bond fell  
to 1.9550 percent from Wednesday's finish of 1.9950 percent, 
driving its price up to 99.53 yen from 99.20 yen. 
  	   	
</P>
