<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Eureka, Calif. Say No to Wal-Mart </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EUREKA, Calif. (AP) -- Many see the old polluted train yard as  
this fading timber town's final chance to stay true to its seaport 
roots and build a commercial port that could breathe life into its 
struggling economy. 
</P>
<P>
	Wal-Mart sees it as abandoned property ideal for a discount  
store. 
</P>
<P>
	The retail giant has spent tens of thousands of dollars on  
feel-good advertising and phone calls to sell its plan to 
residents, but the voters of Eureka this week said no. 
</P>
<P>
	Even though the town's economy, built on timber and fishing  
industries, has stagnated in recent years, and Wal-Mart would bring 
much-needed jobs and tax revenue, the train yard remains the last 
undeveloped waterfront area that would let the city build a 
deep-water, commercial port, said Patty Berg, a Eureka resident who 
led the fight against Wal-Mart. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think what our community said is we can't be bought and we  
control our future,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	In a special election Tuesday, they voted 4,015 to 2,605 to  
reject Wal-Mart's plan to rezone the 32-acre plot. 
</P>
<P>
	The site has sat idle for nearly 20 years since Union Pacific  
Railroad shut down its engine turnaround area. The ground was badly 
polluted by an engine repair shop. Any buyer would be obligated to 
clean it up. The city can't afford to. 
</P>
<P>
	Wal-Mart spokeswoman Daphne Davis said the company will step  
back and evaluate its options. 
</P>
<P>
	It could ask the government to rezone the land -- the special  
election had bypassed the usual channels. The city planning 
commission would need to approve the change, then the City Council 
and finally the California Coastal Commission. 
</P>
<P>
	After the vote, however, Davis spoke in the past tense.  
</P>
<P>
	``(The tract's) been sitting there for 20 years and it's in need  
of major cleanup and we were willing to do it. We were ready to get 
started right away. It would've been a good thing,'' she said. 
``We're obviously disappointed.'' 




  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
