<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pentagon Defends Missile Decision </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A senior Pentagon analyst says he wasn't  
criticizing the Army's testing procedures when he called two 
successful tests of an anti-missile missile ``tightly scripted'' 
events and not ``operationally realistic.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Philip Coyle, the Defense Department's director of operational  
test and evaluation, said he still stands by his recommendation for 
more testing before the Pentagon commits itself to a specific 
missile model in its $15 billion Theater High Altitude Area Defense 
program, or THAAD. 
</P>
<P>
	The Pentagon announced last week that, with two successful tests  
under its belt after six failures, it was skipping a planned third 
test and moving to the next stage in development. 
</P>
<P>
	Coyle, the Pentagon's top testing official, was quoted in  
Defense Week, a trade publication, as listing shortcomings of the 
tests at the White Sands Missile Range in New Mexico. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, in a memo released by the Pentagon, Coyle wrote  
that he didn't want his position to be misunderstood. 
</P>
<P>
	``The THAAD tests to date at White Sands Missile Range have been  
conducted carefully and professionally,'' he wrote. ``These tests 
were important, necessary, and valuable, and were not 'cooked' or 
'rigged.' The test limitations were unavoidable given range safety 
considerations and the maturity of the THAAD program.'' 
</P>
<P>
	THAAD is the centerpiece of the Defense Department's effort to  
provide missile protection abroad for U.S. and allied troops and 
their staging areas. 
</P>
<P>
	With a range of 800 miles, it is expected to complement the  
shorter-range Patriot 3 missile, the latest version of the missile 
used against Iraqi Scud missiles in the 1991 Persian Gulf War. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
