<HEADLINE> Karpov Sues Over Chess Tournament </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LAS VEGAS (AP) -- World chess champion Anatoly Karpov has filed a  
breach of contract suit against an international chess federation, 
seeking more than $1 million in compensation. 
</P>
<P>
	Karpov, angry over the championship tournament now under way at  
Caesars Palace hotel-casino, filed his petition on Aug. 19 in the 
Court of Arbitration for Sport in Lausanne, Switzerland, his 
spokesman Shiloh Quinn said. 
</P>
<P>
	Quinn said reigning champion Karpov was not given a fair  
opportunity to defend his championship. 
</P>
<P>
	He said officials from Federation Internationale de Echecs never  
consulted with Karpov about the dates of the tournament and his 
role in the event. The suit asks that the court require the winner 
of the tournament to play Karpov in a championship match. 
</P>
<P>
	Karpov won the world title in January 1998 for a period that he  
says should have lasted two years. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
