<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Grizzlies Await Word From Francis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	VANCOUVER, British Columbia (AP) -- Stu Jackson doesn't know what  
announcement brooding draft pick Steve Francis has to make on 
Friday, nor does the Vancouver Grizzlies general manager really 
care. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm going to wait, but I'm not going to wait with baited  
breath,'' Jackson said Wednesday. ``I don't know what he's going to 
announce. But I'll tell you this, any announcement that he has 
isn't going to lever us one way or the other. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're going to do what's in the best interest of our club when  
we feel we have to do it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Speculation of Francis' uncertain future with the Grizzlies took  
another turn this week when the New York-based Edelman Public 
Relations firm said Francis scheduled a press conference for noon 
Friday in his hometown of Takoma Park, Md. 
</P>
<P>
	Edelman representative Peter Land would only say that the  
subject of the press conference was ``basketball-related.'' Francis 
and his agent, Jeff Fried, have been unavailable for comment. 
</P>
<P>
	Francis, selected second in the NBA draft, has made clear his  
reservations about playing for the Grizzlies. On draft night, 
Francis made no attempt to hide his displeasure at being picked by 
Vancouver. He later explained his initial reluctance was because he 
didn't want to move so far away from his home and his grandmother 
who has raised him since the death of his mother. 
</P>
<P>
	Jackson acknowledged that there were personal issues raised by  
Francis during contract talks. And, Jackson admitted that he has 
made numerous attempts to deal Francis to another team. 
</P>
<P>
	Failing a trade, however, Jackson doesn't know what else he can  
do to convince Francis to play for the Grizzlies this season. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked if he would allow Francis to sit out the year and re-enter  
the draft, Jackson said, ``That's an option of ours. ... I can't 
say that I would do that. I just don't know. We're not at that 
point right now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Under the rookie salary cap, Francis is due a three-year  
contract worth about $9 million. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have done everything we possibly can,'' Jackson said.  
``It's not just myself, it's the entire organization that has bent 
over backwards to try to address every issue that Steve has. 
</P>
<P>
	``All we're trying to do is hand him over $9 million and make  
him a very well-known basketball player.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Although not at the point of exasperation, Jackson said he never  
expected to have this much trouble signing the player. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think anyone could expect the amount of issues that  
we've dealt with here internally at this point,'' he said. ``I just 
don't think anybody could have expected that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Francis is the only one of the top six draft choices not to sign  
a contract. 
</P>
<P>
	Rick Pernell, director of the Takoma Park Recreation Center and  
friend of Francis, said he was ``in the dark'' about what Francis 
was going to announce Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Pernell added that Francis has been working out daily and intent  
on playing in Vancouver. 
</P>
<P>
	``Steve's a ballplayer and he wants to play ball,'' Pernell  
said. ``As for his feelings, as far as I'm aware, he doesn't mind 
playing in Canada. ... He's focused on getting his mind ready to be 
that far away from home.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
