<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Steel Sculpture Installed on Mall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A 10-ton, 40-foot abstract sculpture made of  
steel construction beams painted industrial orange went up 
Wednesday on the Mall between the Capitol and the Washington 
Monument. 
</P>
<P>
	The sculpture consists of two beams that were welded together in  
the shape of a V and suspended to swivel in the breeze. 
</P>
<P>
	American sculptor Mark di Suvero, 66, was on hand to see that  
two big truck-mounted cranes -- the tools of his trade -- put his 
piece ``Are Years What? (for Marianne Moore)'' properly in place. 
</P>
<P>
	The cryptic title echoes a poem written by Moore, who died in  
1972. 
</P>
<P>
	Di Suvero's style dates back to ``constructivists'' in the early  
years of the Soviet revolution, who were impressed by both Pablo 
Picasso and the stark strength of modern building materials. 
</P>
<P>
	The 60-foot by 70-foot plot where the construction will stand  
belongs to the Sculpture Garden of the Hirshhorn Museum, part of 
the Smithsonian Institution. The museum acquired the work with the 
help of the Institute of Scrap Recycling Industries. Di Suvero 
finds most of his materials in scrap yards. 
</P>
<P>
	Another of his works in the same characteristic style already  
stands in the new sculpture garden of the National Gallery of Art 
on the opposite side of the Mall. 
</P>
<P>
	Di Suvero has made an international reputation with his works of  
industrial metal, bolted or welded together. His last big exhibit, 
in Paris two years ago, spread his sculptures over 10 prominent 
sites across the city. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990825.0068 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-25 14:31:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
