<DOCNO> APW19990825.0069 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-25 10:23:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Study To Compare Two Operations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- Doctors looking for the best way to prevent  
a stroke in people who recently suffered a minor one due to a 
clogged neck artery are starting a large study comparing a highly 
effective operation with a new, less invasive method. 
</P>
<P>
	New Jersey Medical School in Newark, part of the University of  
Medicine and Dentistry of New Jersey, will run the five-year 
international study, funded by a $22.3 million grant from the 
National Institute of Neurological Disorders and Stroke. 
</P>
<P>
	It's the biggest grant the university has ever received, and one  
of the bigger projects ever undertaken by the institute, one of the 
National Institutes of Health. 
</P>
<P>
	``In many strokes, there is a significant amount of recovery  
after two to three months (but patients) do have a very significant 
increased risk of another stroke, and second strokes can be more 
severe,'' said Dr. John R. Marler, the institute's associate 
director for clinical trials. 
</P>
<P>
	``So it certainly is worthwhile in the hundreds of thousands of  
patients who have a stroke with good recovery to do everything 
possible to prevent another stroke.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The institute notes that older people have a higher risk of  
stroke than the general population, and that risk increases with 
age. For every decade after 55, the risk of stroke doubles. 
Two-thirds of all strokes occur in people over 65. 
</P>
<P>
	During a stroke, brain tissue dies from lack of oxygen when  
blood flow to the brain is insufficient -- due to a clot blocking a 
blood vessel or a vessel bursting. Some scientists call strokes 
``brain attacks.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Depending on the amount and location of brain tissue killed, a  
stroke can cause permanent paralysis on one side, vision and 
hearing problems, difficulty speaking or thinking, and other 
symptoms. Each year, strokes kill about 150,000 Americans and 
disable half of the other 500,000 people who suffer one. Stroke is 
the most common cause of adult disability. 
</P>
<P>
	A ``ministroke'' can cause similar symptoms and disrupt brain  
function temporarily, but patients are usually virtually normal 
quickly. 
</P>
<P>
	``One of the most common causes of stroke is plaque in the neck  
artery,'' where fatty deposits tend to build up in the turbulent 
area where the artery splits into two branches, said the study's 
principal investigator, Dr. Robert W. Hobson II, director of the 
New Jersey medical school's division of vascular surgery. 
</P>
<P>
	Hobson said the study will include about 2,500 patients aged 40  
or older who, within the previous six months, suffered a ministroke 
associated with plaque deposits narrowing the carotid, or neck, 
arteries. Those arteries feed oxygenated blood to the brain. 
</P>
<P>
	Half the patients will undergo the ``gold standard'' surgery for  
preventing another stroke: carotid endarterectomy. A surgeon cuts 
into the neck, clamps off the artery around the plaque, then 
scrapes out the fat with tiny surgical spatulas and stitches the 
artery and neck incision shut. 
</P>
<P>
	The other patients will get a recently developed procedure  
called carotid angioplasty with stenting. A special catheter with a 
balloon is threaded from the groin up into the neck and, with 
guidance from X-rays, pushed into the clogged section. The balloon 
is inflated, flattening the plaque; after the balloon is removed, 
another catheter carrying a small, metal tube called a stent is 
pushed into that spot to keep the artery open. 
</P>
<P>
	``A lot of patients are asking for the less invasive procedure  
because they don't want the anesthesia, they don't want an incision 
in their neck,'' required for endarterectomy, Hobson said. 
</P>
<P>
	The older operation is considered extremely safe and effective  
and patients often recover in a day. An earlier study by the 
institute found endarterectomy cut the risk of having a second 
stroke or dying within a year to 9 percent, from the 27 percent for 
patients who received ``best medical care'' for the condition, 
Hobson said. 
</P>
<P>
	A selection committee at the medical school will pick 50 to 60  
sites around the country and will eventually add some sites in 
Canada and Europe. Patient recruitment is expected to begin by 
spring, Hobson said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The benefit (of this trial) may well be a better  
recommendation to the individual patient as to how their plaque 
should best be treated,'' with endarterectomy or angioplasty, he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Marler said that if the newer procedure proves more effective  
than endarterectomy, ``It could certainly prevent thousands, 
perhaps tens of thousands of strokes per year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He noted the study is one of a half-dozen funded by the  
institute investigating ways to prevent both second strokes and 
initial ones. They include trials giving people special vitamin 
supplements, comparing use of aspirin with the blood-thinner 
Coumadin, giving women estrogen supplements to prevent second 
strokes and one comparing aspirin's effect on African-Americans 
with that of another blood-thinner called ticlopidine found to be 
especially effective for that group. 
</P>
<P>
	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	EDITOR'S NOTE: For more information or to sign up for the study,  
patients may call the medical school's Center for Vascular Disease 
at 1-800-VASC-DOC. For information about stroke prevention, visit 
the institute's Web site at www.ninds.nih.gov 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
