<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Four Jailed in Soccer Blackout Scam </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Four men were jailed Wednesday for plotting to  
cause a blackout during a Premier League soccer game as part of a 
betting scheme devised by gambling syndicates in Asia. 
</P>
<P>
	The men were convicted of conspiracy to cause public nuisance by  
attempting to knock out floodlights during a match between Charlton 
Athletic and Liverpool at the Valley stadium in February. 
</P>
<P>
	Malaysians Chee Kew Ong and Eng Hwa Lim were each sentenced to  
four years at Middlesex Crown Court. 
</P>
<P>
	Roger Firth, a security guard at Charlton's field, was sentenced  
to 18 months after he admitted accepting a bribe to let the men 
into the stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	Wai Yuen Liu who was born in Hong Kong but lives in London, was  
sentenced to 30 months. He was the only one to plead innocent. 
</P>
<P>
	When Liu, Ong and Lim were arrested Feb. 10 at the Valley  
stadium, they were in possession of an electrical device designed 
to make the floodlights fail during the match scheduled for Feb. 
13. 
</P>
<P>
	Ong had boasted that the group caused blackouts which forced two  
Premier League games to be cut short in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	The men wanted to black out the games while the score was in  
their favor. A man sitting in the stands was able to trigger a 
short circuit using a simple remote control device and the cuts had 
to be cut short. 
</P>
<P>
	The first match was at Upton Park in November 1997 where West  
Ham hosted Crystal Palace. The lights went out 20 minutes into the 
second half just after West Ham had drawn level. 
</P>
<P>
	The second was a month later at Selhurst Park where Wimbledon  
played at home to Arsenal and again the lights went out shortly 
after half time when the scores were tied. 
</P>
<P>
	Betting syndicates stood to make a lot of money if a game was  
cut short when scores were favorable. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
