<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Profits Fall at Swissair Parent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ZURICH, Switzerland (AP) -- Swissair parent SAirGroup said  
Wednesday its net profit for the first half of this year fell 31.5 
percent as competition kept fares low and the war in Kosovo 
affected flight schedules. 
</P>
<P>
	The company, which also owns the regional airline Crossair, said  
it earned the equivalent of $58 million, down from from $84.7 
million in the same period last year. 
</P>
<P>
	In a statement, chief executive Philippe Bruggisser said 1999 as  
a whole will be difficult and that SAir won't be able to match its 
full-year results for last year, when it posted a net profit of 
$247 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Downward pressure on fares and restrictions and delays resulting  
from the Kosovo conflict were among the factors behind the profit 
drop, SAirGroup said. 
</P>
<P>
	It estimated that delays resulting from European airspace  
restrictions cost the group's airline operations between 
$3.3million and $4 million per month so far this year. 
</P>
<P>
	The group's cargo division also had a difficult first half,  
``facing both substantial yield declines and a steep falloff in 
traffic from the United States and on Europe-to-Asia routes.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
