<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Films Hurt US Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- When the import-battered U.S. steel industry  
was forced to lay off 10,000 workers last year, the government 
responded with a $1.5 billion loan program, a White House ``action 
plan'' and the threat of punitive tariffs against foreign steel 
makers. 
</P>
<P>
	But when the U.S. film industry saw 20,000 jobs leave the  
country, primarily because film and television producers were 
seeking lower-cost locations, no one in Congress or the 
administration rushed to the rescue. 
</P>
<P>
	``Folks may look at this and say, 'That's just a Hollywood  
issue.' But it's not,'' says Rep. Jerry Weller, R-Ill., who is 
taking the lead on Capitol Hill to help persuade American producers 
to stay home. ``It affects working people all over.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In 1990, overseas productions made up 14 percent of all U.S.  
film and TV projects. But by 1998, they comprised 27 percent, 
according to a study last month commissioned by two major Hollywood 
unions, the Directors Guild of America and the Screen Actors Guild. 
</P>
<P>
	That has meant a fivefold increase in lost wages, spending and  
taxes from those runaway productions to more than $10 billion in 
1998. 
</P>
<P>
	And the study said that for grips, best boys, extras, caterers,  
sound technicians and other movie-related workers, the picture is 
only getting worse. 
</P>
<P>
	The vast majority of the business is going to Canada, which  
offers tax credits to studios for wage costs, a very favorable 
currency exchange rate and much-improved quality in its crews and 
locations. All that combines for a 25 percent reduction in cost by 
choosing to film in Canada, the study concluded -- a sometimes 
irresistible lure for film producers trying to find ways to hold 
down expenses on multimillion-dollar productions. 
</P>
<P>
	The California legislature is among state governments that have  
taken notice of the film flight, passing two bills that would 
provide tax credits for certain productions that use California 
labor. 
</P>
<P>
	Runaway productions also are a concern for states such as Texas,  
North Carolina, Washington and Illinois, which often get 
smaller-budget projects that are more likely to leave the country. 
</P>
<P>
	Ron Ver Kuilen, managing director of the Illinois Film Office,  
estimates the list of all the projects written with Illinois 
locations that were filmed elsewhere added up to $52 million in 
lost direct spending last year. 
</P>
<P>
	One of those was ``Blues Brothers 2000,'' the sequel to the  
original film that put Chicago and its south suburbs on the 
moviemaking map. Adding insult to injury, after crews shot only a 
few location scenes in the Windy City, officials from the Toronto 
film office called their counterparts there for advice on how to 
make their city appear more Chicago-like. 
</P>
<P>
	``We may not have gotten most of them anyway,'' Ver Kuilen said  
of that and other films. ``But 20 years ago, nobody even thought of 
going to Canada. Now, it's their first thought.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Weller and the coalition of the unions and state film  
offices are faced with several obstacles as they try to lure the 
studios back home by making the United States a more attractive 
location. 
</P>
<P>
	First, there still is little awareness in Congress and in the  
Clinton administration that a significant problem exists that 
affects more than just California. 
</P>
<P>
	Also, there is no consensus yet among those working on the issue  
on what to do about it. 
</P>
<P>
	Weller began by proposing, along with Reps. Mark Foley, R-Fla.,  
and Xavier Becerra, D-Calif., an amendment to the Republicans' 
recently passed tax bill that would have provided a 20 percent tax 
credit for film-related wages, tax-free film production bonds and 
low-interest loans. As planned, he promptly withdrew the probably 
overgenerous measure, only meaning to raise the issue's profile. 
</P>
<P>
	Weller also is urging the administration to put the issue on the  
table at the next World Trade Organization talks, set for Seattle 
in November. He would like to see the U.S. trade representative 
address with Canada its requirement that up to 60 percent of the 
content shown on its stations be Canadian. 
</P>
<P>
	Weller says that although the policy is meant to protect  
Canadian culture, it instead is being used as an economic tool to 
give an unfair advantage to Canadian markets over American ones. 
</P>
<P>
	``If they want it to go the way of the TVs and other electronics  
products, then so be it. We will be a minority participant in the 
making of this product too,'' Ver Kuilen said. ``The trend is 
ominous for what has always been a U.S. industry.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
