<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Mostly Lower on Fed News </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The dollar rose against most major currencies on  
Wednesday, fueled by expectations that investors will buy dollars 
to purchase U.S. bonds and stocks now that many believe the Federal 
Reserve is done raising interest rates this year. 
</P>
<P>
	In late New York trading, the euro was quoted at $1.0425, down  
from $1.0529 late Tuesday. The dollar also was quoted at 111.14 
Japanese yen, up from 110.80. 
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesday, the Fed raised short-term interest rates for the  
second time this summer in an effort to cool the economy by making 
it more difficult for Americans to borrow money. 
</P>
<P>
	Many investors expect that the Fed will not raise rates again  
this year. That boosted bonds and stocks -- the Dow Jones industrial 
average set another record high --on Wednesday, and helped lift the 
dollar. 
</P>
<P>
	Higher rates make returns more attractive on investments  
denominated in dollars. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Fed's message has been interpreted that no further rate  
hikes will be needed for the rest of the year,'' said Kevin Harris, 
international economist at MCM Currencywatch in New York. ``It is 
now seen as safe to buy back into U.S. assets'' and investors will 
use dollars to fund their purchases. 
</P>
<P>
	The gains on Wall Street helped pull the dollar from its lows  
against the yen in overnight trading. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar moved as high as 112.40 yen soon after Haruhiko  
Kuroda, Japan's vice finance minister for international affairs, 
said the ministry is ready to take action against rapid moves in 
foreign exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	But once traders realized that the Bank of Japan hadn't stepped  
in to buy dollars and sell the strong yen, the U.S. currency 
slumped. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar also was quoted at 1.5366 Swiss francs, up from  
1.5201, and 1.4940 Canadian dollars, up from 1.4925. The British 
pound fell to $1.5853 from $1.5941. 
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no  
longer traded separately and are tied to the euro by a fixed rate. 
Based on Wednesday's euro rate, the dollar was worth: 1.8762 German 
marks, up from 1.8575; 6.2922 French francs, up from 6.2297; and 
1,857 Italian lire, up from 1,839. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
