<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-25 15:50:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Phasing Out of Gas Additive Urged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A report by environmental officials from eight  
Northeast states called Wednesday for a controversial 
methanol-based gasoline additive to be largely phased out within 
three years because it pollutes waterways. 
</P>
<P>
	But the report also cautioned that replacing MTBE as an additive  
could become tricky and pose still other health risks by increasing 
the amount of toxic chemicals going into the air from motor 
vehicles. The additive has been key to reducing air pollution but 
poses other environmental concerns. 
</P>
<P>
	This ``tension between public health and environmental resource  
protection'' poses unique challenges to state and federal 
regulators, said the study to be released Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	A copy was obtained Wednesday by The Associated Press.  
</P>
<P>
	Still, the study agreed with a blue-ribbon federal panel's  
findings last month that MTBE raises enough environmental concerns 
about water pollution that its use should be severely limited. 
</P>
<P>
	The report by the Northeast States for Coordinated Air Use  
Management was expected to add to pressure in Congress and at the 
federal Environmental Protection Agency to curtail use of the 
additive. 
</P>
<P>
	If federal action curtailing MTBE is not taken, ``a regional  
solution will be pursued in the Northeast'' to reduce the amount of 
it used in the eight states -- Connecticut, Maine, Massachusetts, 
New Hampshire, New Jersey, New York, Rhode Island and Vermont -- the 
report said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Northeast governors requested the study last November, but  
it gained new significance after the federal blue-ribbon commission 
issued its conclusions last month. 
</P>
<P>
	EPA Administrator Carol Browner has said she now wants to reduce  
MTBE use as quickly as possible as long as substitutes do not 
sacrifice air quality gains already made. 
</P>
<P>
	The methanol-based additive -- methyl tertiary butyl ether -- is  
in about one-third of the gasoline sold nationwide and in about 
three-fourths of the gasoline sold in the Northeast. It 
significantly reduces air pollution from automobiles, especially 
toxic tailpipe emissions. 
</P>
<P>
	But the federal panel said it also contaminates groundwater,  
lakes and streams due to spillage and leaks from underground 
storage tanks. 
</P>
<P>
	The Northeast governors will use the NESCAUM report to develop a  
regional strategy for dealing with MTBE, said Jason Grumet, the 
organization's executive director. 
</P>
<P>
	The report recommended that the Northeast governors press  
Washington officials to give states increased authority to regulate 
MTBE and for Congress to eliminate the requirement that gasoline 
contain a certain level of oxygenate. MTBE is an oxygenate that 
allows gasoline to burn cleaner. 
</P>
<P>
	The regional study made no recommendation how MTBE could best be  
replaced. 
</P>
<P>
	One substitute would be another additive, corn-based ethanol,  
which is used in the Midwest. The study said 800 million gallons of 
ethanol would be required to replace all the MTBE now in use in the 
Northeast region. Wide use of ethanol would be complicated by 
supply, distribution and cost problems, it said. 
</P>
<P>
	The most economic near-term substitute for MTBE in the  
Northeast, the study said, may be to have refiners increase the 
levels of aromatic compounds such as benzene, toluene and xylene in 
gasoline. But the report cautioned that these compounds are toxic, 
add to air pollution and ``adversely affect public health.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
