<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-25 08:10:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Thousands Rally for East Timor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DILI, Indonesia (AP) -- Up to 10,000 jubilant supporters of  
independence for East Timor defied threats and choked the streets 
of the normally sleepy provincial capital Wednesday, convinced they 
will win a historic U.N.-supervised referendum by a landslide next 
week. 
</P>
<P>
	Hundreds of people rode on trucks, buses and motorcycles in a  
noisy and smoky parade along Dili's palm-lined, ramshackle streets. 
</P>
<P>
	``Today is a golden day for us, ahead is freedom and  
independence,'' said Zoana Victor, a 38-year-old resistance 
supporter who was jailed by Indonesia in the 1970s. 
</P>
<P>
	Many waved the blue, green, and white independence flags that  
were banned until recently. Others carried portraits of imprisoned 
independence leader Jose Alexandre ``Xanana'' Gusmao. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the most impressive display of the separatist movement's  
popular strength to date, far outmatching earlier and more subdued 
rallies by anti-independence campaigners. 
</P>
<P>
	Also Wednesday, Gusmao unveiled a wide-ranging program designed  
to ensure national reconciliation and economic growth following the 
ballot. 
</P>
<P>
	``Regardless of past positions, all citizens are called upon to  
embrace the need for harmony, and to show forgiveness and tolerance 
toward their brothers for the sake of our national interests,'' he 
said in a statement released in Jakarta. 
</P>
<P>
	Gusmao, who is under house arrest in the Indonesian capital, has  
frequently predicted an overwhelming victory by the 
pro-independence side in the U.N.-sponsored referendum on Aug. 30. 
</P>
<P>
	Indonesia invaded the former Portuguese colony in 1975, and  
ruled with an iron hand until the ouster last year of the longtime 
dictator Suharto. Like many Indonesians, Suharto uses only one 
name. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier this year, the government reversed Suharto's policy of  
forcibly integrating the half-island territory into Indonesia. 
Instead, it said, the East Timorese would be allowed to decide 
their fate through the ballot box. 
</P>
<P>
	The vote will give East Timorese the choice between remaining  
part of Indonesia as a self-governing province and breaking away 
completely. 
</P>
<P>
	The transitional government would offer to integrate  
anti-independence supporters and other East Timorese citizens who 
worked for the Indonesian authorities into the new administration 
and police force, Gusmao's statement said. 
</P>
<P>
	Gusmao's optimism regarding the outcome of the plebiscite was  
echoed in Dili. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are sure 90 percent of East Timor's people will vote for  
independence,'' said Manuel Carrascalao, a longtime 
pro-independence politician. 
</P>
<P>
	Wednesday's crowd turned out despite what activists say is a  
campaign of violence and intimidation against civilians and U.N. 
staff by militia groups accused of trying to derail the ballot so 
they can stay part of Indonesia. 
</P>
<P>
	Riot police broke up a brief clash between pro- and  
anti-independence groups after both sides threw rocks. One man was 
injured before officers closed off a street adjacent to a militia 
building. 
</P>
<P>
	The celebration was also marred by a traffic accident in which  
three people died. Three others were injured in the collision 
between a truck and a car in the motorcade. 
</P>
<P>
	Members of Indonesia's armed forces, accused for decades of  
human rights abuses in their quest to crush separatist guerrillas, 
watched passively as the raucous procession moved slowly by their 
barracks. A police helicopter hovered overhead. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier, thousands rallied outside the seafront headquarters of  
the Council for Timorese National Resistance. They sang and danced, 
and chanted ``Long live East Timor,'' and ``Long live Xanana.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In his statement, Gusmao proclaimed a general amnesty ``for all  
political crimes committed until now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We have fought against an oppressive system that has  
antagonized us,'' he said. ``At no point have we fought against the 
people of Indonesia.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gusmao said the transitional government would maintain close  
ties with ``a democratic and multi-party Indonesia'' and would keep 
in use its currency, the rupiah. 
</P>
<P>
	He said East Timor would develop a market economy free of the  
endemic corruption that characterized Indonesia's administration. 
He also pledged to promote foreign investment and protect property 
rights. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990825.0090 </DOCNO>
