<HEADLINE> Advance To Dominate Fashion Press </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Advance Publications will dominate the  
fashion press with its planned purchase of a Walt Disney Co. 
publishing unit that includes Women's Wear Daily, W and Jane 
magazines. 
</P>
<P>
	The sale price was not disclosed Tuesday, but previous reports  
put the value of the deal at about $650 million. The companies said 
they expect the deal to close by the end of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	With its earnings and stock price slumping, Disney has been  
trying to refocus on its movie studio and theme parks. 
</P>
<P>
	``Despite Fairchild's strengths, Disney is focused on the  
long-term growth of our core brands and entertainment assets,'' 
said Michael Eisner, Disney chairman and chief executive officer. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the deal, Disney will sell its Fairchild Publications unit  
to Advance, the parent company of Conde Nast, but will be allowed 
to publish some material online from W, Jane and Women's Wear 
Daily. 
</P>
<P>
	Conde Nast's publications include: Vogue, Glamour, Mademoiselle,  
GQ and The New Yorker. 
</P>
<P>
	Disney acquired Fairchild in 1995 in its purchase of Capital  
Cities-ABC, but wanted to sell it two years ago as it sold other 
publications, including the Kansas City Star and Fort Worth 
Star-Telegram and the trade publisher Chilton. 
</P>
<P>
	S.I. Newhouse Jr., chairman of Advance, reportedly had been in a  
bidding war with rival Hearst Magazines for Fairchild. The deal 
merges two of the fashion world's most powerful publishers, 
potentially allowing Advance to offer advertisers package rates for 
buying space in several magazines at the same time. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, Disney announced today that it has bought a majority  
interest in toysmart.com, an online educational toy seller. 
</P>
<P>
	Disney's Buena Vista Internet Group will own an estimated 60  
percent stake in the Waltham, Mass.-based toy retailer, said Chuck 
Davis, president of electronic commerce for Disney's Internet 
group. 
</P>
<P>
	Terms of the deal were not disclosed, but analysts said the deal  
includes $20 million in cash and $25 million worth of free 
marketing. 
</P>
<P>
	Disney will integrate privately-held toysmart.com with its  
Family.com Web site, Davis said. Family.com has articles and advice 
on parenthood and draws about 3 million visitors a month. 
</P>
<P>
	Educational toys make up about 38 percent of the $23 billion toy  
market, said David Lord, toysmart.com's chief executive. 
</P>
<P>
	The market for the educational toys sold by toysmart.com is  
worth between $5 billion and $8 billion, said Ken Cassar, an 
analyst with Jupiter Communications in New York. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
