<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Disney Grabs Online Toy Business </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Disney has gained a better foothold in the  
online toy business with its purchase of a majority stake in 
Toysmart.com, a deal analysts said Wednesday will position the 
companies as leaders in educational toys. 
</P>
<P>
	The companies would not disclose the purchase price, but an  
analyst said Disney paid $20 million for its 60 percent interest in 
the toy company and agreed to provide $25 million in Web and other 
media marketing for Toysmart on Disney properties. 
</P>
<P>
	Toysmart specializes in what company President David Lord calls  
``good toys'' intended to teach and inspire children. Its products 
include games and puzzles, painting kits and a solar-powered 
windmill model. 
</P>
<P>
	Unlike the general toy business dominated by well-known  
retailers such as Toys ``R'' Us, Wal-Mart and the Internet company 
eToys, the market for educational toys is fragmented among smaller 
outfits. 
</P>
<P>
	Ken Cassar, an analyst with Jupiter Communications in New York,  
estimates the educational toys market is worth between $5 billion 
and $8 billion -- or roughly about a quarter to a third of the $23 
billion overall toy market. 
</P>
<P>
	Disney's clout and reach will help Toysmart, which is just  
beginning a big national marketing push, to ``bring the message to 
consumers that we're a credible alternative to other competitors in 
the online toy market,'' Lord said. ``We're going to champion good 
toys, and we're going to shout it from the top of every mountain.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The deal gives Disney a new, ready-made Internet toy presence  
beyond its online Disney store, where consumers can buy such items 
as Mickey Mouse tool kits and Cinderella play sets. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's nothing bad in it for Disney,'' said Carrie Ardito, a  
research associate at Forrester Research. ``It's relatively cheap 
and only extends their reach to more people. It's even better for 
Toysmart. It's a relatively unknown retailer catapulted into one of 
the most dominant marketers online.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The two companies' Web sites will share links, with Disney's  
Family.com site promoting Toysmart products and Toysmart's site 
gaining access to editorial content from Disney. 
</P>
<P>
	Disney will control three of the five seats on Toysmart's board  
of directors, but Toysmart will retain control of its site and what 
products are sold there, the companies said. 
</P>
<P>
	Chuck Davis, president of electronic commerce for Disney's Buena  
Vista Internet Group, said Disney wants to keep a ``little 
church-and-state separation'' so Toysmart will be free to pick the 
toys it wants. 
</P>
<P>
	Toysmart already sells some Disney toys and probably will add  
more as it expands its catalog from about 20,000 items to 75,000 by 
this November, Lord said. New items will include baby toys and 
children's furniture, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Davis said Disney toys likely would account for no more than 1  
percent of Toysmart's items. 




  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
