<CATEGORY> regional </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Wealthy Immigrants Sue INS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Affluent immigrants who hoped to attain  
permanent residency in the United States through investments sued 
the Immigration and Nationalization Service Tuesday claiming its 
rules were secretly and illegally changed. 
</P>
<P>
	INS officials said the dispute is about proving each immigrant  
invested $500,000 in a U.S. company as required. They said the 208 
immigrants in the lawsuit, about one-third living in California, 
have a quarrel with their investment company, not the government. 
</P>
<P>
	The 143-page suit filed in U.S. District Court in San Francisco  
is the latest and largest of six similar cases involving the United 
States' immigrant investor program. 
</P>
<P>
	Congress created the program in 1990 to attract foreign  
investment. Through it, immigrants can get a two-year conditional 
visa in exchange for investing a minimum $500,000 in U.S. companies 
to create at least 10 jobs each. If the financial obligation is met 
during the temporary stay, the immigrant obtains permanent 
residency. 
</P>
<P>
	The case involves immigrants who funneled their investments  
through AIS, a company based in Greenbelt, Md., which bundled more 
than $100 million from immigrants for investments in companies 
across the country. 
</P>
<P>
	Although AIS is not directly involved in the lawsuit, the case  
revolves around the financial arrangements the immigrants made with 
AIS. 
</P>
<P>
	Immigrants typically contributed a fraction of the amount  
required in cash, perhaps $125,000, and committed through a 
promissory note to pay the rest by the end of their two-year visa. 
</P>
<P>
	But as INS reviewed the mushrooming number of deals in late  
1997, outside experts and the agency's lawyers concluded that the 
immigrants associated with AIS and similar companies never paid as 
much as required. 
</P>
<P>
	``Basically, what they were trying to do was create some voodoo  
economics to give the appearance of making the investments when 
those investments were not being made,'' said Russ Bergeron, an INS 
spokesman. 
</P>
<P>
	AIS was criticized by both the INS and the immigrants.  
</P>
<P>
	William Cook, who was general counsel to the INS when the  
program was adopted and is now a lawyer representing AIS, defended 
the financial arrangements as acceptable in thousands of earlier 
immigration cases. 
</P>
<P>
	``They (INS officials) simply made the changes in secret and  
started to apply them retroactively,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The immigrants contend the extra INS scrutiny and requests for  
documentation effectively changed the rules secretly because they 
were not published in the Federal Register. 
</P>
<P>
	Even if new rules are approved to prevent deals that AIS  
arranged, the changes can't be applied retroactively to people who 
already invested their money and are living in the country, the 
suit contends. 
</P>
<P>
	``This lawsuit is our attempt to rein in a lawless agency,''  
said Ira Kurzban, a Miami lawyer who filed the case with Marc Van 
Der Hout of San Francisco. 
</P>
<P>
	The INS granted conditional visas to immigrants after examining  
their financial plans, which included promissory notes. But the 
immigrants claim not all applicants were treated equally. 
</P>
<P>
	Yi Yuan Chiang of San Francisco is one of 26 partners in C&AMP;W  
Hotel Ltd. Partnership, a Maryland group that assisted the 
expansion of K-Bob Steakhouse restaurants in Texas and New Mexico. 
Although 21 of the partners are already permanent residents, he is 
not because of the dispute about the $1 million investment he says 
he made. 
</P>
<P>
	INS officials declined comment on specifics of the lawsuit. But  
they criticized the arrangements of AIS and similar investment 
firms for failing to document that the money went to the companies 
intended. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
