<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Calif. Gov., Tribes Discuss Casinos </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- Gov. Gray Davis met with  
representatives of 25 California tribes Wednesday to discuss a 
possible interim agreement that would keep tribal casinos open 
until voters weigh in on the subject again. 
</P>
<P>
	The meeting came two days after the state Supreme Court struck  
down a voter-approved initiative that sought to expand legalized 
gambling at tribal casinos. 
</P>
<P>
	The tribes have until early October to reach an agreement with  
Davis to avoid having thousands of video slot machines shut down by 
federal authorities. 
</P>
<P>
	On Monday the justices ruled that Proposition 5 is invalid  
because it would let tribes operate video slot machines and other 
Nevada-style games banned by the state constitution. 
</P>
<P>
	Davis' discussions Wednesday included the possibility of an  
agreement that would give legal standing to tribes now operating 
casinos until a constitutional amendment that would permit the 
gambling goes to voters, Davis spokesman Michael Bustamante said. 
</P>
<P>
	Davis and tribal officials also discussed proposed language for  
a constitutional amendment that would be more restrictive than 
Proposition 5, Bustamante said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Proposition 5 allowed for a significant expansion of gaming,''  
Bustamante said. ``Perhaps a modest expansion of gaming might be in 
order.'' 
</P>
<P>
	An initiative tribes are now circulating for the March ballot  
proposes an amendment less restrictive than the one Davis discussed 
Wednesday. It would establish the same liberal rules allowing 
Nevada-style gambling at Indian-run casinos that Proposition 5 
would have created. 
</P>
<P>
	Mark Macarro, chairman for the Pechanga Indian Reservation in  
Temecula, south of Riverside in Southern California, said his tribe 
will consider both proposals. 
</P>
<P>
	``Any option that preserves our ability to continue on a  
status-quo basis has to be considered,'' Macarro said. ``We need to 
preserve the level of employment we have now and the level of 
tribal services we have right now.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
