<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Centenarian Celebrates Activism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Born just before the start of the 20th century,  
Georgianna Turner is as fabulously feisty as ever on the eve of the 
21st. 
</P>
<P>
	In between came a journey by ship north from her home in Jamaica  
and four decades of fighting to improve the once-dangerous corner 
of Brooklyn where she made her home. 
</P>
<P>
	Elegant in a long purple dress, her bobbed gray hair  
meticulously coiffed, Mrs. Turner recently celebrated a well-lived 
century with memories, music and friends. 
</P>
<P>
	``My secret to long life? Love,'' she said softly. ``Love  
everybody. Try to help the less fortunate. ... Try to help the 
children.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For a century, Mrs. Turner has lived by those words. Friends and  
neighbors on her block in the Fort Greene neighborhood cherish her 
stubborn devotion to the neighborhood, her strong spirit and her 
habit of looking out for those who need a hand. 
</P>
<P>
	She spent decades to make life in Fort Greene a little better  
and ignored those who thought the neighborhood wasn't worth 
fighting for. 
</P>
<P>
	For hours every night, she would sit at the window of her old  
brownstone home watching the street, calling police to report drug 
dealers and others who menaced passersby. Vandals knocked in her 
door and windows, but she kept on. 
</P>
<P>
	``I wanted to make it into a decent community, with decent  
people and a clean community,'' she recalled. ``I think everybody 
respects me in the neighborhood, because I worked very hard, put my 
life in danger.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Before ``quality of life'' became a political catch phrase, Mrs.  
Turner made countless phone calls to city agencies and lawmakers 
and spent hours at block meetings working to keep trucks out of the 
neighborhood, loiterers off the street and police officers walking 
their beats. 
</P>
<P>
	She visited neighbors who appeared to be in trouble, offering to  
help however she could. 
</P>
<P>
	``The whole neighborhood was awful,'' she said. ``The garbage  
wasn't picked up, the police were lazy. I got them working.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Her efforts paid off. Fort Greene is now cleaner and safer than  
ever. Property values are up and people are moving in. 
</P>
<P>
	About 75 friends gathered Aug. 18 to honor Mrs. Turner and share  
memories of her impressive life. She leaned on a cane as she 
walked, but she stood straight and appeared strong despite breaking 
a hip last year. 
</P>
<P>
	``Georgianna Turner gives old age new meaning,'' said her  
grand-niece, Michelle Hodges, 49. ``Turning 100 is a marvel, but to 
still have an able mind and body, a sense of humor and a 
willingness to learn new things, as Aunt Georgie does, is truly 
remarkable.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Turner, who worked as a dressmaker and a beautician until  
retiring in 1961, outlived three husbands and never had children. 
But there was no shortage of well-wishers to celebrate at her new 
home in an assisted-living center. 
</P>
<P>
	She was overcome with emotion and dabbed at her eyes with a  
handkerchief, but happily accepted kisses and birthday wishes from 
dozens of friends and relatives. 
</P>
<P>
	Hairstylist Sylvia Williams recalled the first time the  
well-turned-out Mrs. Turner walked into her salon. 
</P>
<P>
	``I said, `So this is the famous Mrs. Turner,''' she remembered.  
``To see somebody at her age doing those kinds of things, it makes 
you embarrassed that you're not doing more things.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Others remembered Mrs. Turner's devotion to her Catholic church,  
her penchant for wide-brimmed hats and her always-elegant 
appearance. 
</P>
<P>
	``She always looked so beautiful, with her pretty, big hats,  
we'd always chat on our way in or out of church,'' Margaret Vincent 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Turner, born in 1899, the youngest and now only surviving  
of 16 children, left her native Jamaica with a sister and a niece 
in 1915 for a five-day ship journey to Ellis Island. In 1958, she 
moved into her brownstone on South Oxford Street in Fort Greene. 
</P>
<P>
	She left her home recently, only because it had become too  
difficult to get around on her own. 
</P>
<P>
	What makes Mrs. Turner proudest in a century of living?  
</P>
<P>
	After all these years, she sighed, ``Just lasting.''  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
