<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 3 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Wednesday, Aug. 25, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Airline Workers Held in Drug Probe  
</P>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- Dozens of American Airlines employees and contract  
workers were arrested and charged today in a drug ring that 
investigators said smuggled cocaine and marijuana into the United 
States by hiding the stuff in food carts, garbage bags and carry-on 
luggage. Fifty-eight people were named in multiple indictments 
resulting from Operation Sky Chef and Operation Ramp Rat, including 
30 American employees. By early afternoon, at least 48 people had 
been arrested at their homes and a few caught at the airport. The 
people indicted were mainly ramp workers and baggage handlers. 

</P>
<P>
	White House Renews Tax Cut Attack  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Renewing its attack on the Republican tax cut  
plan, the White House contended today the proposal would result in 
nearly $100 billion in cuts to essential federal programs over the 
next five years, with Medicare and farm programs among the hardest 
hit. House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill, and Senate Majority 
Leader Trent Lott, wrote to Clinton last week that the estimated 
budget surplus is more than enough to cut taxes, save Social 
Security and Medicare and ensure adequate levels of government 
spending. 

</P>
<P>
	Turkey Leader Attacks Media  
</P>
<P>
	ISTANBUL, Turkey (AP) -- Stung by criticism of his government's  
response to last week's earthquake, Turkey's Prime Minister Bulent 
Ecevit lashed out at ``demoralizing'' media coverage today and 
called for national unity in the face of the catastrophe. The 
government also blamed fluctuations in the death toll on local 
officials in the town of Izmit, saying they had inflated their body 
count to get more quake aid. The mayor of Izmit said it was simple 
human error with no ulterior motive. The death toll jumped 
yesterday to more than 18,000, but the government today changed it 
back to 12,514. 

</P>
<P>
	Bosnia Commander Arrested in Austria  
</P>
<P>
	THE HAGUE, Netherlands (AP) -- Acting on a tip from the U.N. war  
crimes tribunal, Austrian police arrested the top Bosnian Serb 
military commander today as he visited Vienna -- unaware that he had 
been secretly indicted for crimes against humanity. The arrest of 
Gen. Momir Talic, the Bosnian Serbs' military chief of staff, 
sparked an immediate outcry from Serbs. U.S. diplomats warned 
American citizens to avoid traveling in the Serb-held part of 
Bosnia for fear of retribution. 

</P>
<P>
	Tropical Storm Heads Toward U.S.  
</P>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- A hurricane watch was posted today for the Bahamas  
because of Tropical Storm Dennis and forecasters warned that the 
storm could affect the southeastern United States this weekend. The 
hurricane watch covers the Turks, Caicos and other Bahama islands -- 
including Bimini, just 55 miles from Florida. ``Residents along the 
entire southeastern United States coast should closely monitor the 
progress of this system,'' said hurricane specialist Jack Beven of 
the hurricane center. 

</P>
<P>
	Mozart-Smart Theory Challenged  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A Mozart sonata may lift the soul, but it won't  
make listeners any smarter, according to two studies that challenge 
previous research about the effect of music on intelligence. The 
latest results call into question 1993 research that showed college 
students temporarily gained up to nine IQ points after listening to 
Mozart. ``Listening to classical music is probably good for kids -- 
good for reasons other than it's going to make them smarter,'' said 
Harvard Medical School researcher Christopher Chabris, who analyzed 
16 previous studies and published his findings in tomorrow's issue 
of the journal Nature. 

</P>
<P>
	Durable Goods Orders Up 3.3 Percent  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Orders for big-ticket manufactured goods  
vaulted ahead in July, and sales of existing homes, though pinched 
by rising mortgage rates, still managed to post the third best 
month ever. Economists said the two reports, released today, 
reflect a still-booming economy. The Commerce Department reported 
that orders for durable goods rose 3.3 percent last month to a 
seasonally adjusted $204 billion. The National Association of 
Realtors reported that sales of existing single-family homes 
declined 3.9 percent in July. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Drops 19; Nasdaq Rises 39  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Just before 3 p.m. EDT, the Dow industrials were  
down 19.95 points at 11,263.35. Declining issues on the New York 
Stock Exchange led advancers 1,520-1,399. The Nasdaq was up 39.29 
at 2,791.66. 

</P>
<P>
	Marion Jones Hurt in 200 Semifinals  
</P>
<P>
	SEVILLE, Spain (AP) -- Sprinter Marion Jones, bidding for three  
gold medals at the World Championships, pulled up with an injury 
during the semifinals of the 200 meters today and was carried off 
on a stretcher. Jones, who won the 100 meters on Sunday, clutched 
her lower back about halfway through the race and fell to the track 
in agony. Jones was the heavy favorite in the event in her try for 
a 100-200 double. Jones has said she will attempt to win five gold 
medals at next year's Sydney Olympics. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by DAVID GOODMAN  
  	   	
</P>
