<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bankrupt Pager Company Pulls Plug </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) -- Greenville-based Conxus Communications has  
sent a message to more than 80,000 paging customers they didn't 
want to get: Your service is being cut off. 
</P>
<P>
	The company, in bankruptcy since May, told customers that as of  
5 p.m. EDT Friday their cutting edge, voice-mail pagers will go 
dead. 
</P>
<P>
	The Pocketalk service was available in Dallas, Fort Worth,  
Texas, San Francisco, Los Angeles, Boston, Philadelphia, New York, 
Washington, Atlanta, Houston, Chicago and parts of south Florida. 
</P>
<P>
	No other companies have voice paging services that work with the  
Motorola system Conxus used, Motorola spokesman Ken Countess said. 
</P>
<P>
	Phones at Conxus' headquarters were answered Wednesday by an  
automated system with no opportunity to leave a message. Callers to 
Conxus' customer-service line got only the message, ``Conxus 
Communications, the network provider for Pocketalk and Pocketext, 
will cease operations effective Friday, Aug. 27, at 5 p.m. We 
regret this outcome.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Customers were told to seek help from the retailers where they  
bought the pagers that generally cost less than $50, with six-month 
service contracts from $9.95 to $19.95 a month. 
</P>
<P>
	Pocketalk stumbled from the start, said Kevin Condon, an  
industry analyst at Warburg Dillon Read in New York. ``We never 
thought there would be much of a market for voice paging. ... The 
guy sitting next to you can hear what the message is,'' Condon 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	There were also too many other competing technologies, said  
analyst Bruce Kasrel at Forrester Research in Cambridge, Mass. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is the kind of stuff that fails all the time,'' Kasrel  
said. ``People will put in the drawer with the Newton'' handheld 
computer.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Conxus was founded by Cecil Duffie and Bill deKay, former  
executives of Greenville-based Dial Page Inc. Duffie is the Conxus' 
vice chairman and chief executive and deKay its president. 
</P>
<P>
	DeKay also was a board member of the American Mobile  
Telecommunications Association in Washington, D.C. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is not a fly-by-night group that tried to take advantage  
of any situation,'' association President Alan Shark said. DeKay 
``worked 18 hours a day trying to keep that company going.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That's little solace to people like Dennis Daily, one of the  
company's Los Angeles customers. The recently laid-off longtime UPI 
radio employee told the Los Angeles Times he sent out more than 200 
resumes listing his Pocketalk phone number for potential employers 
to call. 
</P>
<P>
	``I labored over that resume, and now I have no idea what my 888  
number is going to say come the end of Friday,'' he said. ``Is it 
going to make me look like I can't pay my bills?'' 



</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
