<HEADLINE> Entertainment Highlights in History  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Entertainment highlights during the week of Aug. 29-Sept. 4:  
</P>
<P>
	60 years ago: ``The Women,'' directed by George Cukor, premiered  
in Hollywood. The film starred Norma Shearer, Joan Crawford, 
Rosalind Russell and Joan Fontaine. 
</P>
<P>
	55 years ago: Frank Capra's ``Arsenic and Old Lace'' starred  
Cary Grant, Raymond Massey and Peter Lorre. 
</P>
<P>
	50 years ago: James Cagney, Virginia Mayo and Edmond O'Brien  
starred in ``White Heat,'' directed by Raoul Walsh. 
</P>
<P>
	40 years ago: A New York radio station banned the song ``Mack  
the Knife'' in response to a wave of stabbings. 
</P>
<P>
	30 years ago: Chicago Transit Authority, Janis Joplin, Led  
Zeppelin and Santana performed at the Texas International Pop 
Festival in Dallas. 
</P>
<P>
	20 years ago: INXS performed its first concert in Toukley,  
Australia. 
</P>
<P>
	15 years ago: ``Purple Rain,'' the movie starring Prince, went  
into general release in Britain. 
</P>
<P>
	10 years ago: The Rolling Stones opened a 29-city Steel Wheels  
tour with concerts at Veterans Stadium in Philadelphia. 
</P>
<P>
	Five years ago: Singer Willie Nelson performed at the federal  
prison in McKean, Pa. ``Let's get this jail moving,'' Nelson told 
prisoners. They shouted back, ``We love you, Willie!'' 
</P>
<P>
	One year ago: The Venice Film Festival paid tribute to actress  
Sophia Loren. Her husband, producer Carlo Ponti, accepted a 
lifetime achievement award for Loren, who was kept away from the 
festivities by illness. 

</P>
<P>
	Spoken 10 years ago:  
</P>
<P>
	``The Who and the Rolling Stones figure, `I want another wing on  
my villa,' so they go and tour. We go on the road because the guys 
just like to play.'' -- Lead singer Grace Slick of the Jefferson 
Starship. 

</P>
<P>
	``We've ended up friends, which is great for us. That's a real  
triumph. It was not a happy ending in 1982, but it feels great 
now.'' -- Singer Roger Daltrey, as The Who wound up its 25th 
anniversary tour. 

</P>
<P>
	Spoken five years ago:  
</P>
<P>
	``It's positive. It's not about karate kicks. It's not about  
shooting off 5,000 bullets out of a gun. It's about people. It's 
about love. It's about joy.'' -- Actress Della Reese, describing her 
television series, ``Touched by an Angel.'' 

</P>
<P>
	``After a while in L.A., you're not going to be funny anymore.  
It just ebbs away, because the environment is very unfunny. In New 
York, you breed it, it's in the air. The garbage men have it, the 
mailmen have it, everybody has it.'' -- Comedian Jerry Seinfeld. 

</P>
<P>
	Spoken one year ago:  
</P>
<P>
	``This whole past year, my house has become a real Hollywood  
Babylon, Studio 54 type of place. So at any given moment, you may 
have found Leif Garrett or Corey Feldman singing the theme from 
`Grease.''' -- Rocker Marilyn Manson. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
