<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Campbell Soup Revamping Labels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAMDEN, N.J. (AP) -- At Campbell Soup Co., what goes on a can is  
almost as important as the soup inside, so the food maker has spent 
two years revamping its red-and-white label. 
</P>
<P>
	Since 1898, Campbell has made only 14 minor changes to the  
red-and-white label on its condensed soup line. The last change was 
made for select varieties in 1994 to mark the company's 125th 
anniversary. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, the company is making what it says is the most significant  
change in its history to the label popularized by pop artist Andy 
Warhol in the 60s. It will include all 70 varieties in Campbell's 
core business of condensed soups. 
</P>
<P>
	The Camden-based food maker will formally unveil the redesigned  
label today in Pittsburgh, where a symbolic replica of the last can 
of condensed tomato soup bearing the old label will be inducted 
into the Andy Warhol Museum. 
</P>
<P>
	``The design is much loved and very familiar to Americans, but  
we felt there was a wonderful opportunity to update it and refresh 
it,'' said Lisa Zakrajsek, vice president of the company's U.S. 
Soup division. 
</P>
<P>
	The new label has a photograph of a bowl of soup at the center,  
a recipe on the back and a colored banner to distinguish the soup 
category. The Campbell name is smaller on the new label and a gold 
medallion that had been in the center of the can is higher. While 
still red-and-white, the label now has a slightly brighter shade of 
red. 
</P>
<P>
	Zakrajsek said a team of designers and managers began working  
two years ago ``Project Renaissance.'' They presented about 20 to 
30 different labels to consumer focus groups before making a final 
selection and fine-tuning it, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We think it's a beautiful label,'' she said.  
</P>
<P>
	The red-and-white Campbell label made its debut in 1898, a year  
after the company began producing condensed soups in Camden. In 
1900, the company added a graphic touting its Gold Medallion award 
for excellence. Slight changes in lettering were also made in 1905 
and 1993 
</P>
<P>
	Warhol made the Campbell cans world famous with more than 100  
portraits and paintings showing the red-and-white label. Warhol, 
who died in 1987, began painting the soup cans in 1962. 
</P>
<P>
	Tomas Sokolowski, director of the Warhol museum, said the artist  
likely would have approved of the attempt by Campbell to update the 
soup label. The Tomato Soup label has not been altered since 1942. 
</P>
<P>
	``The one thing that Warhol understood was that change was  
necessary and his art changed immensely,'' Sokolowski said 
Wednesday. ``Who knows? May be this label will last for a hundred 
years.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Zakrajsek admits it may be risky for Campbell to alter its world  
famous label. The company believes the new label, however, will 
make it easier for consumers to find their favorite variety on 
store shelves. 
</P>
<P>
	Cans bearing the new look on some varieties of soup are already  
appearing on supermarket shelves. The banners identify categories 
such as Fun Favorites and 98 percent Fat Free. 
</P>
<P>
	The familiar traditional red-and-white soup labels that have  
lined supermarket shelves for more than a century will begin 
disappearing by mid-September. The average consumer, however, may 
not notice the seemingly subtle changes to the world famous cans. 
</P>
<P>
	The new label resembles changes Campbell made in 1994, but back  
then the company excluded its three biggest sellers from the new 
look: Tomato, Chicken Noodle and Cream of mushroom. This time, the 
change will include the entire classic red-and-white soup line. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's still Campbell Soup,'' Zakrajsek said.  
</P>
<P>
	Over the years, Campbell has tried various marketing strategies.  
Once it put its ``M'm M'm Good'' advertising slogan on the back 
burner to use a less catchy campaign theme, ``Never Underestimate 
the Power of Soup.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Campbell ranks sixth among U.S. food companies and controls 80  
percent of the U.S. market for condensed soups. Campbell also sells 
food under its Prego, V-8 juices, Godiva chocolate, Pace and 
Pepperidge Farms brands. 




  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990825.0118 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-25 08:11:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bomb Explodes Near Taliban HQ </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) -- A powerful truck bomb exploded near  
the home of the leader of Afghanistan's ruling Taliban movement, 
killing seven people, including three bodyguards, Taliban officials 
said today. 
</P>
<P>
	The explosion, shortly after 10 p.m. Tuesday in southern  
Kandahar, slightly damaged Mullah Mohammed Omar's compound, but he 
had left earlier in the evening and was unharmed, officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	The blast shattered windows and doors and sent frightened  
residents scurrying for cover. 
</P>
<P>
	The truck was parked three houses away from Omar's home, said  
Taliban spokesman Abdul Hai Muttmain, who was contacted on 
satellite telephone in Kandahar. 
</P>
<P>
	Omar -- who has two wives, several children and a missing eye he  
lost while fighting invading Russian soldiers in the 1980s -- leads 
the Taliban with an iron hand. He belongs to Afghanistan's majority 
ethnic group, the Pathans, and follows one of the strictest forms 
of Islamic law in the world. 
</P>
<P>
	Omar's home in Kandahar is a walled compound, the front door  
flanked by two green minaret-styled pillars. 
</P>
<P>
	There was no way to independently confirm Omar's whereabouts. He  
had not been seen publicly since the blast, but he is reclusive and 
rarely makes public appearances. 
</P>
<P>
	No one took responsibility for the explosion.  
</P>
<P>
	The Taliban religious army, which rules 90 percent of  
Afghanistan, is fighting an opposition alliance that has been 
restricted to northern Afghanistan. 
</P>
<P>
	Tuesday's truck bomb was the first attack on the Taliban in  
their stronghold of Kandahar, hundreds of miles from the fighting. 
</P>
<P>
	Muttmain said the Taliban, who have been under pressure from the  
United States to hand over accused terrorist Osama bin Laden, 
suspect the United States was involved in the bombing. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, the United States fired Tomahawk cruise missiles on  
eastern Afghanistan, where Washington believed bin Laden was 
running training camps for his terrorist network. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States has accused bin Laden of masterminding the  
devastating bombings of two U.S. embassies in East Africa on Aug. 
7, 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	The Taliban have refused to hand over bin Laden, saying he is a  
guest in Afghanistan, which does not have an extradition treaty 
with the United States. The Taliban also are demanding proof of his 
involvement in terrorist activity. 
</P>
<P>
	That a truck bomb was able to breach Taliban's defenses was not  
a concern, said Muttmain. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our security is good ... but we have enemies, and anywhere  
these things can happen,'' he said. It wasn't clear whether 
additional security was being arranged. 
</P>
<P>
	Leaders of an Islamic militant group in neighboring Pakistan,  
Harakat-ul-Mujahedeen, also blamed the bombing on Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	``The bombing was the worst kind of terrorism and the United  
States was responsible,'' the independent News Network 
International quoted Harakat leader Fazl-e-Rehman Khalil as saying. 
</P>
<P>
	Another militant group in Pakistan, Lashkar-e-Tayyaba, condemned  
the bombing, saying ``such incidents are not going to suppress or 
curb Islamic movements.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990825.0119 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-25 08:00:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Why Did Fed Raise Interest Rates? </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The Federal Reserve raised interest rates by a  
quarter percentage point for the second time in two months in a bid 
to slow the economy and contain inflation. 
</P>
<P>
	Here are some questions and answers about the Fed's action on  
Tuesday and what impact it might have on the economy and consumers: 
</P>
<P>
	Q: What did the Fed do?  
</P>
<P>
	A: The policy-making arm of the nation's central bank, led by  
Fed Chairman Alan Greenspan, raised the suggested ``federal funds'' 
rate that banks charge each other for overnight loans from 5 
percent to 5.25 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Fed officials also raised the ``discount rate'' it charges on  
direct loans to banks from 4.5 percent to 4.75 percent, the first 
increase in that rate since Feb. 1, 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	The boost in rates, which was widely expected, followed a  
quarter percentage point increase in the fed funds rate on June 30. 
</P>
<P>
	Q: How much and how soon will higher interest rates affect  
consumers? 
</P>
<P>
	A: The impact of a Fed rate hike is usually immediate, but not  
that drastic since they come in small quarter-point increments. 
</P>
<P>
	Banks, paying more to borrow from the Fed and other banks, will  
quickly make up for their increased expenses by charging businesses 
and consumers more to borrow. 
</P>
<P>
	The interest charged on many types of consumer borrowing --  
including variable-rate mortgages, auto loans and credit card debt 
-- are tied to the prime rate or directly to the federal funds rate. 
</P>
<P>
	The prime rate was raised to 8.25 percent from 8 percent,  
effective today, by major banks nationwide. The prime is the base 
upon which banks compute loans to business customers. The best 
customers may pay less than the prime rate. Riskier ventures will 
pay a higher rate. 
</P>
<P>
	Savers may benefit from higher rates because banks and other  
financial institutions will pay more interest on deposits in 
various types of accounts. 
</P>
<P>
	Q: Weren't interest rates already rising?  
</P>
<P>
	A: Yes. Mortgage rates climbed above 8 percent earlier this  
summer, a two-year high, in part because of expectations that the 
Fed would tighten credit further. 
</P>
<P>
	So far, however, higher mortgage rates haven't dampened home  
sales or housing construction that much. In fact, many consumers 
may be house hunting now out of concerns that mortgage rates will 
push even higher. 
</P>
<P>
	Home sales are a key economic force, driving demand for building  
supplies, appliances and home furnishings. 
</P>
<P>
	Q: Why the sudden push to raise interest rates?  
</P>
<P>
	The two rate hikes, the first in more than two years, are  
designed to ripple through the economy, slowing the pace of 
borrowing and spending among banks, businesses and consumers. 
</P>
<P>
	While everyone likes a strong economy, there is a potential  
downside: 
</P>
<P>
	If consumer confidence is too high, it may become hard for  
factories and service providers to keep up with demand. And if jobs 
are plentiful, workers bargain for better wages. Companies faced by 
product shortages or lost sales may boost prices so they can hire 
more workers and pay higher wages. 
</P>
<P>
	Q: Is that's what's happening now?  
</P>
<P>
	A: So far, inflation has remained surprisingly tame, with  
consumer prices rising just 0.3 percent in July and at a 2.4 
percent rate for the year. 
</P>
<P>
	But inflationary pressures persist with unemployment near a  
three-decade low and the economy growing at a brisk 4 percent pace 
for the year. Hoping to keep those pressures from boiling over, the 
Fed boosted rates in June and again on Tuesday as a precaution. 
</P>
<P>
	Q: How will higher rates slow the economy?  
</P>
<P>
	A: Increased borrowing costs may discourage some businesses from  
investing in expansion, buying new equipment or hiring workers. 
Consumers, worried about higher lending rates and a weaker job 
market, may slow their spending on clothes and travel or postpone 
major purchases like cars, homes and furniture. 
</P>
<P>
	Q: What if higher interest rates smother the economy, causing a  
recession? 
</P>
<P>
	A: Fed policy is a work in progress. Last fall, the central bank  
cut rates three times to reinvigorate the economy, bolstering 
confidence among lenders and borrowers fearful of a global 
financial crisis. If the economy slows too much, the Fed could 
switch course and start cutting rates again. 
</P>
<P>
	Q: What's next?  
</P>
<P>
	A: In announcing Tuesday's action, the Fed maintained a neutral  
stance on future interest rate decisions, expressing confidence in 
the economic outlook. 
</P>
<P>
	In a statement, the Fed said that its actions on Tuesday and  
June 30 should ``markedly diminish the risk of rising inflation 
going forward.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
