<HEADLINE> MetLife Said Near Deal With Insurer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Metropolitan Life Insurance Co. reportedly is  
close to announcing a deal to acquire troubled General American 
Life Insurance Co., in a deal that could be worth $1.2 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	MetLife's board already has approved a preliminary plan for the  
deal, Dow Jones News reported Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Larry Larance, a spokesman for St. Louis-based General American  
said he could not comment on the report. But he said General 
American's board of directors was meeting Wednesday night to 
consider offers and proposals and that an announcement could come 
as early as Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	He declined to say who was interested, how many offers had been  
made or possible financial terms. He also declined to say if 
MetLife was among the suitors. 
</P>
<P>
	A half-dozen companies have expressed an interest in buying  
General American since the company announced it was seeking a 
partner several weeks ago, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's no secret we have been negotiating with several  
companies,'' Larance added. 
</P>
<P>
	Attempts to reach MetLife officials after business hours were  
unsuccessful. 
</P>
<P>
	The sale could include General American's majority stakes in  
publicly traded Reinsurance Group of America, a provider of 
reinsurance, and Conning Corp., an asset manager, Dow Jones 
reported. 
</P>
<P>
	General American earlier this month turned to regulators to help  
it pay back $6.8 billion in customers' deposits. 
</P>
<P>
	Since then, it has been under administrative supervision of  
Missouri insurance regulators. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal would require the approval of regulators in both New  
York and Missouri. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
