<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Alternative Stock Exchanges Are In </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Forget the image of the pinstriped Wall Street  
broker hustling across the crowded floor of the New York Stock 
Exchange. Replace it with an image of rows of quietly humming 
computers in the basement offices of Island ECN Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	Welcome to the future of stock trading.  
</P>
<P>
	Island operates one of about a dozen so-called electronic  
communications networks, or ECNs, vying to replace the NYSE and the 
Nasdaq Stock Market as the primary U.S. arena for buying and 
selling stock. 
</P>
<P>
	ECNs are revolutionizing the way stocks are traded in America by  
allowing investors to process their trades electronically with 
minimal interference from middlemen, such as Nasdaq market makers 
or Big Board brokers and specialists, whose commissions drive up 
investors' trading fees. 
</P>
<P>
	Professional investors have used alternative exchanges for years  
to bypass the traditional markets' costly and often cumbersome 
trading methods. But the recent explosion in Internet investing has 
led ECNs to broaden their scope in search of the growing number of 
individual investors who trade online. 
</P>
<P>
	One way ECNs are competing for the small investor market is by  
allowing them to trade in the after-hours sessions formerly 
reserved for professionals. Already, small investors who trade 
through brokerage firms hooked up to Island can trade outside the 
regular market hours of 9:30 a.m. to 4 p.m. And Instinet, which 
operates the oldest and most widely used ECN, recently teamed with 
online brokerage firm ETrade Group to allow ETrade's retail clients 
access to Instinet's after-hours market. 
</P>
<P>
	The impact is already being seen on Wall Street; the NYSE, the  
Nasdaq and the regional Chicago Stock Exchange have all announced 
plans to introduce after-hours trading sessions. 
</P>
<P>
	``The masses out there obviously want this, and you can see it  
by the popularity of the ECNs,'' said Tony Kafeiti, online 
supervisor at Castle Online, a Freeport, N.Y., discount brokerage 
firm that processes most of its customers' trades on ECNs. 
</P>
<P>
	Kafeiti said ECNs are popular because they allow small investors  
to take a hands-on approach to trading, and because the networks 
don't discriminate against small investors in favor of large 
professional traders, an accusation frequently made against the 
established exchanges. 
</P>
<P>
	``They've leveled the playing field,'' Kafeiti said.  
</P>
<P>
	Investors who trade using ECNs do so by sending their buy and  
sell orders to an online brokerage firm over the Internet. The 
brokerage firm then completes the trade almost immediately by 
processing it on an ECN. The entire process can be completed in 
seconds and cost around $20 -- far quicker and cheaper than using a 
traditional full service broker who trades on the NYSE or the 
Nasdaq. 
</P>
<P>
	That said, questions have emerged as to how ECNs will regulate  
trading activity on the electronic frontier. And critics of ECNs 
argue that because the networks operate independently of one 
another they have fragmented the market to such a degree that 
investors can never really be sure they're getting the best price 
for their stock. 
</P>
<P>
	Junius Peake, a former vice chairman of the board of governors  
of the National Association of Securities Dealers, which governs 
the Nasdaq Stock Market, argues that investors who trade via ECNs 
are limited to whatever prices are being offered on the specific 
ECN on which their trade is completed. In other words, a better 
price may exist on another ECN or on a traditional exchange, but 
the investor has no access to it. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's the difference between listing your house with a single  
realtor or using a multiple listing,'' Peake said. 
</P>
<P>
	Nevertheless, since emerging as legitimate competition in the  
last three years, the networks have siphoned away about 30 percent 
of the trading volume in Nasdaq listed stocks, and experts expect 
that figure to rise. Moreover, their growing visibility has put 
pressure on the established exchanges to either change their ways 
or risk being left in the dust. 
</P>
<P>
	Several ECNs, including Island and Archipelago Holdings, are  
mulling plans to become full-fledged exchanges, similar in legal 
stature to the NYSE and the Nasdaq. And in a sign of their growing 
credibility, virtually every big name Wall Street investment bank 
has either invested in an ECN or is in the process of building one. 
</P>
<P>
	In an effort to stave off the competition, both the Big Board  
and the Nasdaq recently moved forward with plans to sell stakes in 
their markets through initial public offerings. Both exchanges are 
expected to use the stock created through an IPO to either buy or 
team-up with an ECN. 
</P>
<P>
	ECNs are also having a psychological affect on Wall Street. Many  
longtime market observers believe the proliferation of alternative 
exchanges has marked a turning point in what amounts to a true 
democratization of the stock market. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're giving individual investors the tools and the timing  
that were formerly accessible only to professionals,'' said Alan 
Ackerman, senior vice president and market strategist at Fahnestock 
&AMP; Co., a New York brokerage firm. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990825.0126 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-25 13:20:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lords Miffed Over Essay Contest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- In 75 words or less, why would you like to be in  
the House of Lords? 
</P>
<P>
	That's the question for hereditary members of the Lords before  
an election later this year to select the lucky few who will keep 
their seats. 
</P>
<P>
	To some, it smacks of a cereal-box competition. ``I should  
remain a lord because ...'' read Wednesday's headline in The Times. 
</P>
<P>
	``The whole thing is ludicrous,'' says Lord Mancroft, a  
Conservative peer. ``What do I include -- my inside leg 
measurement?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Brief essays did not win Lord Mancroft his seat in the Lords,  
the upper house of Parliament. He's there because his grandfather, 
Arthur Michael Samuel Mancroft, was given a hereditary peerage in 
1937 after long service in the House of Commons. 
</P>
<P>
	Prime Minister Tony Blair, who leads the Labor Party, is  
determined to eliminate all the 633 bluebloods from the House of 
Lords. 
</P>
<P>
	There are hardly any Labor supporters among the sundry dukes,  
marquesses, earls, countesses, viscounts, barons and baronesses. 
The 471 Conservatives in the Lords include 299 hereditary peers, 
compared to 176 Labor members, of whom just 18 inherited their 
titles. 
</P>
<P>
	As an interim step, the government will allow 92 hereditary  
peers, elected by their colleagues, to keep their seats for a 
while. 
</P>
<P>
	Candidates will not be allowed to print posters, bombard their  
fellow lords with leaflets or otherwise campaign to keep their 
seats. They may submit only their 75 words by Oct. 21, to be 
published in the Lords Library. 
</P>
<P>
	News of the 75-word limit naturally inspired some mirth.  
Columnist Giles Coren, writing in The Times, offered a model essay: 
</P>
<P>
	``Am proactive self-starter with good working knowledge of  
estate management, horsemanship, dithering, dribbling and claret 
drinking ... Have experience in the intricacies of the tax system -- 
specifically in relation to inheritance tax loopholes -- and 
seller's knowledge of the art market.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For Earl Ferrers, 13th in a line going back to 1711, even 75  
words was a bit much. 
</P>
<P>
	``People ought to know the peers for whom they wish to vote  
without people having to tout themselves around their colleagues to 
show how eminently electable they are,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Indeed, some of their noble lords are exceedingly reticent. The  
diary column of The Guardian newspaper recently has been 
highlighting some of the 168 lords who have yet to speak in the 
chamber. 
</P>
<P>
	They include the Duke of Leinster, silent for 27 years; the Earl  
of Normanton, who took his seat 32 years ago, and two peers who 
have been in the house for 45 years -- the Earl of Coventry and the 
Marquess of Abergavenny. 
</P>
<P>
	Lord Onslow, 7th in a line going back to 1801, accepted the  
75-word limit as a challenge. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is a great deal to be said for brevity,'' he said.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990825.0127 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-25 14:50:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> CR Renegade Is Yonkers Favorite </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	YONKERS, N.Y. (AP) -- CR Renegade, who has rebounded from a  
ninth-place finish in the Hamletonian with two straight victories, 
is the favorite in Saturday's $273,891 Yonkers Trot. 
</P>
<P>
	Self Possessed, who set a record in the Hambletonian, is  
skipping the Yonkers Trot, the second leg of the triple crown for 
3-year-olds, in order to compete in the American National on 
Saturday in Illinois. 
</P>
<P>
	CR Renegade is an 8-5 favorite at Yonkers Raceway while  
Raffaello Ambrosio, who finished fourth in the Hambo, is the second 
choice at 2-1. 
</P>
<P>
	Americanese and JW Dutch Treat follow at 6-1.  
</P>
<P>
	CR Renegade, which drew the six spot in the eight-horse field,  
won the Zweig Memorial and the Yonkers Trot elimination after a 
disappointing display in the Hambletonian. 
</P>
<P>
	``Forget about the Hambo,'' said Rod Allen, the driver-trainer  
of CR Renegade. ``That was just a bad trip. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm happy with the draw because we are inside the key horse.  
That gives us the option of getting off quickly or staying behind 
and make a strong finish.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rafaello Ambrosio, driven by Jack Moiseyev and winner of the  
second elimination, is outside Renegade in post position seven. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's too far out,'' trainer Ron Gurfein said. ``However,  
there's nothing I can do about it. CR Renegade will probably go 
first over and we'll find out how good a trotter we have.'' 
</P>
<P>
	CR Renegade has seven victories, three seconds and a third this  
year, with earnings of $415,814. 
</P>
<P>
	The final leg of the triple crown, the Little Brown Jug, is  
Sept. 23 in Delaware, Ohio. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
