<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Drops, Tokyo Stocks Fall / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- The dollar dropped against the yen today after  
traders realized that rumors about intervention from Japan's 
central bank were unfounded. Fears about an overly strong yen sent 
Tokyo share prices falling. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar was trading at 111.32 yen by late afternoon, down  
0.90 yen from late Tuesday but above its late New York level of 
110.80 yen overnight. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average shed 240.25 points,  
or 1.33 percent, to close at 17,855.16. On Tuesday, the average 
closed down 138.14 points, or 0.76 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar gyrated as rumors spread on the foreign exchange  
market that the Bank of Japan was buying up the greenback to stem 
its decline. During the day, it ranged from 110.40 yen to 112.40 
yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar moved as high as 112.40 yen soon after Haruhiko  
Kuroda, Japan's vice finance minister for international affairs, 
said the ministry is ready to take action against rapid moves in 
foreign exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	But traders soon realized that the Bank of Japan hadn't  
intervened. The U.S. currency fell back below 111.00 yen, as 
traders who had bought the U.S. currency turned around and dumped 
their holdings, dealers said. 
</P>
<P>
	``If the BOJ had really intervened, the dollar wouldn't have  
fallen back down so easily,'' said Ryohei Muramatsu, treasury 
manager at Commerzbank. 
</P>
<P>
	Dealers said the dollar was not expected to reverse course  
against the yen because of the view that the Japanese economy was 
starting to recover. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was traded at 116.84 yen, down  
from 117.28 yen late Tuesday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	On the stock market, the yen's rise added to overall gloom as  
market players stayed on the sidelines, worried about the direction 
of the yen. 
</P>
<P>
	A strong yen hurts exporters because it tends to make Japanese  
goods more expensive overseas and lowers the value of their dollar 
earnings. 
</P>
<P>
	Volume on the first section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange was  
estimated at 649.99 million shares, down from 940.74 million shares 
Tuesday. Retreating issues outnumbered advancers 714 to 480, while 
129 issues were unchanged. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section was down 12.27 points, or 0.81 percent, to finish at 
1,494.80. The TOPIX closed down 11.65 points, or 0.77 percent, the 
day before. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark No. 214 10-year Japanese government  
bond rose to 2.0000 percent from Tuesday's finish of 1.9950 
percent, pushing its price down to 98.33 yen from 98.37 yen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
