<HEADLINE> 'Witch' Town Site Gets 500,000 Hits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BURKITTSVILLE, Md. (AP) -- The Internet Website devoted to this  
small town of just over 200 people has drawn half a million visits 
in one day. 
</P>
<P>
	Residents of the town in western Maryland prepared the site to  
respond to the flood of tourist and media inquiries that followed 
the release of ``The Blair Witch Project,'' a pseudo-documentary 
horror film that has earned millions of dollars at the box office 
this summer. 
</P>
<P>
	On the Website, residents are providing facts about the town,  
which has just 75 old brick and Victorian homes, one post office 
and one church. 
</P>
<P>
	The page includes the answers to frequently asked questions  
about the town's connection to the movie. Though the Website, 
hosted by a Severna Park-based company called ToadNet, is 
attracting visitors, the Web page says residents are not making 
money from the limelight. 
</P>
<P>
	``The town of Burkittsville does not have a public restroom, any  
stores, restaurants, or even a payphone. Besides the occasional 
lemonade stand, we are not profiting in any way,'' residents have 
written on the page. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
