<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dvorak Retains Decathlon Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEVILLE, Spain (AP) -- The sweltering southern Spanish summer was  
too much even for Tomas Dvorak. 
</P>
<P>
	Dvorak retained the decathlon world title Wednesday night, but  
fell well short of his world record even though he had been only 10 
points off the pace after three events Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``Two days in this stadium was just too much,'' Dvorak said. ``I  
an happy with the gold but I was hoping to get more points,'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Czech ended the grueling, two-day event with 8,744 points,  
far ahead of Britain's Dean Macey, who earned the silver medal in 
his first major decathlon with 8,556 points. Chris Huffins of the 
United States took the bronze with 8,547. 
</P>
<P>
	Dvorak, 27, should have thrived in the conditions. He won the  
world title at Athens, Greece, two years ago, when the temperature 
was in the 90s. 
</P>
<P>
	When he set the world record of 8,994 points at Prague July 3-4,  
the temperature also was in the 90s. 
</P>
<P>
	``In Prague, it was 10 degrees lower than here and a lot less  
humid,'' Dvorak said. 
</P>
<P>
	Maybe it just felt that way.  
</P>
<P>
	The official readings here, in fact, also were in the 90s, but  
the humidity climbed over 50 percent during the two days of the 
decathlon. 
</P>
<P>
	``The record and the 9,000 points were beyond me here. It will  
have to wait. I just couldn't do it,'' said Dvorak, who led after 
the first day but kept slipping off the world record pace. 
</P>
<P>
	``I wanted to score at least one point more than in Athens; the  
record was far off my mind. 
</P>
<P>
	``My best was the long jump, but then I made a big mistake in  
the pole vault.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dvorak soared 26 feet, 2 1/4 inches in the long jump, a personal  
best. But he cleared only 15-1 in the pole vault, well below his 
best of 16-0 3/4. 
</P>
<P>
	Macey, 21, the world junior silver medalist, hopes one day to be  
the successor of the great British decathlete Daley Thompson. 
</P>
<P>
	He ended the first day only 36 points behind Dvorak, and by the  
end of the event had set six personal bests. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't know whether to be sick or cry or pass out,'' Macey  
said after the final event, the 1,500 meters. ``I just want to go 
to the pub now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Huffins missed the silver by 1.4 seconds in the 1,500.  
</P>
<P>
	``I can't complain one iota. I ran as hard as I could and I set  
my personal second-day best,'' said Huffins, the Pan American Games 
champion. 
</P>
<P>
	``I fully expected to win a medal although I had a subpar first  
day. 
</P>
<P>
	``I never found my rhythm in the discus and hit four hurdles,  
but I set my personal best in the javelin,'' said Huffins, who 
threw 211-2. 
</P>
<P>
	He had no complaints about the weather.  
</P>
<P>
	``In North Carolina, it's a lot hotter and more humid,'' he  
said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
