<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Crude and Gas Futures Plummet  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Crude oil and gasoline futures nose-dived Wednesday on the New  
York Mercantile Exchange after weekly inventory figures showed 
unexpectedly weak gasoline consumption as the peak season winds 
down. 
</P>
<P>
	On other markets, pork bellies fell sharply, while grain and  
soybean futures advanced. 
</P>
<P>
	After pushing over the $22-a-barrel mark recently, the price of  
crude oil for October delivery tumbled more than 4 percent. 
September gasoline was down 3.4 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Crude and its products were hurt after the American Petroleum  
Institute reported gasoline inventories fell a meager 197,000 
barrels. Market participants were betting on a decline of nearly 3 
million barrels. 
</P>
<P>
	Meantime, inventories of heating oil and other distillates rose  
a sharp 3 million barrels, putting supplies in a comfortable 
position going into that peak period. 
</P>
<P>
	Oil futures prices have been on a tear since late winter --  
spurred most recently by Hurricane Bret and an anticipated heavy 
impact on the industry which turned out to be less than expected. 
</P>
<P>
	``Given the huge runup in prices since February, this is causing  
some profit-taking or causing people to rethink the overall 
supply-and-demand picture,'' said William Byers, an analyst for 
Bear, Stearns &AMP; Co. in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors also are trying to anticipate the outcome of a meeting  
in Venezuela this week among three big producers -- Venezuela, Saudi 
Arabia and Mexico. The meeting has pressured prices amid fears oil 
producers may no longer cooperate at keeping supplies off the 
market as they enjoy the highest prices per barrel in nearly two 
years. 
</P>
<P>
	October crude fell 89 cents to $20.58 a barrel; September  
heating oil fell 2.25 cents to 54.75 cents a gallon; September 
unleaded gas was down 2.21 cents to 63.01 cents a gallon; September 
natural gas fell 29 cents to $3.030 per 1,000 cubic feet. 
</P>
<P>
	In London, North Sea Brent Blend crude oil for delivery in  
October plummeted 77 cents to $19.38 a barrel at the International 
Petroleum Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	Pork belly futures prices tumbled 2 percent on the Chicago  
Mercantile Exchange as investors took profits following an extended 
price rise. The decline came after a weekly warehouse report showed 
supplies of frozen meat had fallen far less than expected. 
</P>
<P>
	February pork bellies fell 1.50 cents to 59.30 cents per pound.  
</P>
<P>
	Grain and soybean futures advanced on the strength of a late-day  
rally that came after the private firm Freese/Notis forecast an 
early freeze in the Midwest this fall. 
</P>
<P>
	Some investors voiced skepticism about the long-range forecast,  
however, saying the gains reflected instead an inevitable end to 
the recent price drop responding to rains improved the picture for 
this year's crops. 
</P>
<P>
	``You've really pressed this market pretty hard, and the soybean  
crop is really largely unknown,'' said Eric Stacy, an analyst for 
the Price Futures Group in Chicago. ``The estimates we're getting 
are spotty at best.'' 
</P>
<P>
	December wheat rose 2 cents to $2.86 1/2 per bushel; December corn  
rose 3 1/4 to $2.19 3/4 per bushel; December oats rose 1 1/2 cents to $1.15 1/4 
per bushel; and November soybeans rose 8 1/2 cents to $4.75 1/2 per 
bushel. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
