<HEADLINE> Bush Leads GOP Rivals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Texas Gov. George W. Bush is running even  
with Vice President Al Gore in California, a state the Democrats 
must win, and has built a commanding lead over his rivals for the 
GOP nomination, a new poll indicates. 
</P>
<P>
	Actor Warren Beatty barely registered a blip in the California  
Field Poll as a potential contender for the Democratic nomination. 
He fared somewhat better as a possible third-party candidate, 
drawing 8 percent in the survey released Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Among Republicans who said they were likely to vote in  
California's winner-take-all March 7 primary, Bush got support from 
49 percent. That's more than the combined total of eight other 
Republican candidates, with 16 percent of those surveyed saying 
they were undecided. 
</P>
<P>
	In a survey matchup of the two parties' front-runners, Bush had  
48 percent to Gore's 46 percent, a statistical dead heat that is 
unchanged from March. 
</P>
<P>
	``Compared to the rest of the country, California is more likely  
to lean Democratic, a trend seen throughout the 1990s,'' said Mark 
DiCamillo, director of the Field Poll. ``But the Bush-Gore matchup 
has been very even throughout the entire year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gore advisers are concerned that the California race remains so  
close, but hope Gore will gain ground when the Republican's 
conservative stands on gun control, abortion and other major issues 
become better known in the state. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore led former New Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley by a nearly 3-1  
margin among likely California Democratic Party voters -- 51-18 -- a 
margin steady since March. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush is widening his lead over his GOP rivals in California from  
five months ago when he topped Elizabeth Dole by 18 points, 37-19. 
</P>
<P>
	Among Republicans, Steve Forbes, Mrs. Dole and Sen. John McCain  
of Arizona each drew 8 percent in the new poll. Former Vice 
President Dan Quayle, conservative activist Gary Bauer and 
commentator Pat Buchanan were at 3 percent, Sen. Orrin Hatch of 
Utah at 2 percent and conservative radio host Alan Keyes under 1 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Beatty, who has been considering the idea of running as a  
Democrat against Gore and Bradley, drew only 1 percent from likely 
Democratic voters in California. 
</P>
<P>
	But he drew 8 percent when presented to California Democrats as  
a potential third-party candidate -- with Bush and Gore still in a 
dead heat far ahead. Minnesota Gov. Jesse Ventura drew 15 percent 
as a possible third-party candidate, taking support about equally 
from Bush and Gore. 
</P>
<P>
	The poll's error margin for its 501 likely voters was plus or  
minus 5 percentage points, larger for subgroups such as likely 
Democratic voters or likely Republican voters. It was taken Aug. 
16-22. 
</P>
<P>
	Other possible candidates in a three-way general election were  
in single digits, including Ross Perot, Donald Trump, former 
Connecticut Gov. Lowell Weicker and Buchanan, should he bolt the 
GOP. 
</P>
<P>
	Although Bradley trailed Gore by a large margin in the  
Democratic race, he fared better going against Bush. In that 
scenario, Bush led Bradley 49-42, a far closer margin than Bush's 
19-point edge over Bradley five months ago. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
