<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Okla. Bomb Survivors Seen Suffering </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) -- Martin Cash has flashbacks about the day he  
lost his left eye in the Oklahoma City bombing. He says he 
sometimes has survivor's guilt and can somehow still smell the 
smoke. 
</P>
<P>
	Cash has post-traumatic stress disorder, and he retired from the  
Veterans Administration a year after the attack on April 19, 1995, 
that killed 168 people and injured nearly 700 others. 
</P>
<P>
	According to a study in today's Journal of the American Medical  
Association, almost half the survivors of the deadliest bombing on 
U.S. soil suffer from some sort of psychiatric illness, from 
chronic depression to alcohol and drug use disorders. 
</P>
<P>
	The study -- intended to improve mental health care following a  
disaster -- showed that 34 percent of the bombing survivors surveyed 
had post-traumatic stress disorder. Its symptoms include 
flashbacks, angry outbursts and sleep and concentration problems. 
</P>
<P>
	The study was based on interviews with 182 survivors conducted  
an average of six months after the blast. 
</P>
<P>
	In all, 45 percent developed some type of psychiatric disorder.  
And the researchers said almost everyone else in the study showed 
some symptoms of PTSD but did not have the disorder. 
</P>
<P>
	``Nobody was untouched by this disaster, but different people  
were touched differently,'' said Dr. Carol North of Washington 
University in St. Louis, one of the report's authors. ``Human 
distress is understandable after horrendous events such as this. We 
should not necessarily equate that with mental illness.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. North said those with more serious injuries were more prone  
to develop a disorder, as were those who had a family member 
seriously injured or killed. Most at risk of developing a disorder 
were survivors who refused to think about the event and had 
feelings of isolation and a loss of interest in their surroundings. 
</P>
<P>
	Recognizing such symptoms immediately after a disaster could  
help identify those who need the most help, the researchers said. 
</P>
<P>
	Gwen Allen, director of Project Heartland, which was created  
with a federal grant to provide counseling for those affected by 
the bombing, said that getting help as quickly as possible was 
critical. 
</P>
<P>
	``Those who got the work early on, who got into counseling, have  
done better. The key is that early intervention,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Bombing survivors like Cash have described nightmares and  
flashbacks triggered by loud noises. 
</P>
<P>
	Susan Urbach, who was in the Journal Record building across the  
street from the Alfred P. Murrah Federal Building, said she remains 
easily startled, but quit having nightmares about a year after the 
bombing. 
</P>
<P>
	``One night I dreamed stuff was falling on me. I literally felt  
it,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Charlie Younger, who was in a meeting on the fourth floor when  
the bomb went off, said he hasn't been able to watch movies with 
violence in them since that day and finds it difficult to trust 
people. 
</P>
<P>
	He also doesn't like tall buildings.  
</P>
<P>
	``I'm nervous all the time, especially if I can't look out a  
window,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Younger said he and other bombing victims will always carry  
those mental and emotional scars. 
</P>
<P>
	``You just learn to deal with them,'' he said.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
