<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-25 10:19:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Traditional Country Makes Comeback </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- Traditional country music -- weeping  
steel guitars, twangy voices and lyrics with emotional depth that 
can get downright depressing -- is making a bit of a comeback. 
</P>
<P>
	Several examples indicate at least part of Nashville is  
returning to its roots: 
</P>
<P>
	-- George Jones recently was nominated for a Country Music  
Association award for his single ``Choices,'' a mournful ballad 
that would fit on his classic albums from the 1970s. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Hot new country singer Brad Paisley declared from the stage at  
a Nashville performance: ``I'll never record a song that I can't 
sing on the stage of the Grand Ole Opry'' -- home of traditional 
country music since 1925. 
</P>
<P>
	-- New albums by Paisley, David Ball, Matt King, Jerry Kilgore  
and Chalee Tennison all use traditional country music themes and 
sounds. 
</P>
<P>
	In a year when VH-1 vamp Shania Twain continues to rule country  
music airwaves and Garth Brooks is using an alter ego to release a 
rock album, there's new country music that owes more to Tammy 
Wynette than the Eagles. 
</P>
<P>
	Lyrically, it isn't ``baby food,'' either, King says.  
</P>
<P>
	And Tennison agrees: ``I'm not trying to put anybody down, but I  
can't sing fairy tale stuff.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, for her debut album Tennison picked wrenching songs  
that relate to her recent divorce. The titles include ``I Let Him 
Get Away With It,'' ``I Can Feel You Drifting'' and ``There's a War 
in Me.'' On ``Just Because She Lives There,'' a neglected wife 
struggles with temptation. 
</P>
<P>
	``Just because she lives there/don't mean she loves there  
anymore,'' Tennison sings, her voice drenched in Texas twang and 
Wynette-style guilty heartache. ``And if she turns to another/she 
knows she'll have to answer to the Lord.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Such dark fare is worlds away from the sunny, pop-leaning  
records that Twain and other 1990s country singers have ridden to 
stardom. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am a woman,'' Tennison says. ``I am 30 years old. I do have  
children. I'm single. I've been divorced. 
</P>
<P>
	``The good news is your average listener out there, the average  
person turning on the radio, washing the dishes at home, or driving 
to work, is who I am. They can look at me, and feel like I'm 
reachable and I'm touchable.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Country music could use more of that kind of connection. While  
there have been individual success stories, the industry as a whole 
has stagnated. 
</P>
<P>
	Sales of country music have flattened since peaking in 1995 at  
about $2 billion. After an uptick of 2.7 percent last year, sales 
were down about 3 percent for the first half of 1999. 
</P>
<P>
	Country music's market share of sales has declined to 14.1  
percent, according to the Recording Industry Association of 
America's 1998 Consumer Profile. That's still second -- rock is 
first at 25.7 percent -- but country's share has declined each year 
since peaking at 18.7 percent in 1993. 
</P>
<P>
	That's not to say many country artists aren't doing extremely  
well. Twain, Brooks, Faith Hill, Tim McGraw and George Strait 
continue to sell millions. LeAnn Rimes had a good run as a teen 
idol and may yet get back on track, and the Dixie Chicks have 
become major stars. 
</P>
<P>
	But the middling artists have suffered, and there appears to be  
a limit on how many can cross over to pop. It's a time much like 
the early 1980s, when the wave of popularity and pop crossover hits 
caused by the movie ``Urban Cowboy'' dissipated. 
</P>
<P>
	Then, in 1986, country traditionalist Randy Travis came along  
with hits like ``On The Other Hand,'' sold millions and took 
country back to its roots. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1999, no traditional country artist has broken through to  
Travis-level success. But record executives like Scott Hendricks, 
who signed Kilgore to Virgin Nashville, are gambling on it 
happening. 
</P>
<P>
	``God bless country pop, but you've got to have some meat and  
potatoes once in a while, in my opinion,'' Hendricks says. ``I've 
done the pop stuff, too. I produced Restless Heart, which is as pop 
as it gets. But there's got to be a balance, some straight-ahead 
country music as well. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are fans out there who are hungry for it, and if you  
give them something real, many of them will partake in it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	King, who pointedly titled his second album ``Hard Country,''  
said he would be arrogant to imagine he was going to influence 
country music to become more traditional. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm just doing what I do best and trying to capitalize on a  
great opportunity,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Old-line star Jones says it just feels so good to hear  
traditional country music again. ``I hope it's coming back, if not 
all the way, at least in some form or fashion,'' he says. ``You've 
still got so many, many, many people out there that love the 
traditional music.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Paisley is the most successful new artist doing traditional  
country. He has a solid hit with the wistful ``Who Needs Pictures'' 
and has made a point of publicly declaring his allegiance to 
traditional country. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is a groundswell,'' he says. ``I don't dislike up-tempo,  
positive pop-sounding country records. But I do dislike the fact 
that it has taken such a turn that that seems to be mainstream.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ball, whose excellent third album ``Play'' is a perfect  
soundtrack for two-steppin', likewise shows no animosity to 
pop-leaning artists like Twain. So far, ``Play'' isn't selling. 
</P>
<P>
	``I GET what Shania Twain is doing, and understand why people  
like her records,'' Ball says. ``They're put together really well. 
It just doesn't have much to do with the country music I like to 
do. 
</P>
<P>
	``I love a good pop record. Unfortunately for me, if that's what  
they want, I have no interest in trying to do it. But I just keep 
doing what I love, and maybe the next time the trend comes around 
I'll be waiting.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
