<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 6 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Wednesday, Aug. 25, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Better Building Vowed in Turkey  
</P>
<P>
	ISTANBUL, Turkey (AP) -- Shoddy construction is blamed for the  
thousands of deaths in last week's deadly earthquake in Turkey, and 
the country's leader has vowed to create stricter building rules. 
Eight days after the powerful 7.4-magnitude quake reduced much of 
western Turkey to rubble, 200,000 survivors remain camped out in 
parks and on vacant lots. For a second night, they were drenched 
with heavy rains. A new tremor 200 miles away sent residents of the 
capital, Ankara, running into the streets in panic. The 
4.7-magnitude quake was centered near Haymana, 40 miles south of 
Ankara. A 4.2-magnitude aftershock followed. 

</P>
<P>
	Study: Okla. Survivors Suffering  
</P>
<P>
	OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) -- According to a study in today's Journal of  
the American Medical Association, almost half the survivors of the 
deadliest bombing on U.S. soil suffer from some sort of psychiatric 
illness, from chronic depression to alcohol and drug use disorders. 
The study -- intended to improve mental health care following a 
disaster -- showed that 34 percent of the Oklahoma City bombing 
survivors surveyed had post-traumatic stress disorder. Its symptoms 
include flashbacks, angry outbursts and sleep and concentration 
problems. The study was based on interviews with 182 survivors of 
the 1995 bombing conducted an average of six months after the 
blast. 

</P>
<P>
	Russian Forces Drive Out Militants  
</P>
<P>
	MAKHACHKALA, Russia (AP) -- Russian troops have regained control  
of all six mountain villages captured by Islamic militants in 
southern Russia more than two weeks ago, and were attempting to 
drive scattered groups of rebels from the region entirely, the 
military said today. The operation against the militants in 
Dagestan ``is in its final stage,'' said Defense Minister Igor 
Sergeyev, on a trip with President Boris Yeltsin to the Central 
Asian nation of Kyrgyzstan. The Russians have carried out daily 
bombing raids and artillery attacks, hammering rebels who seized 
the villages when they invaded the Caucasus Mountains region on 
Aug. 7. 

</P>
<P>
	FBI Admits Tear Gas Use in Siege  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Taking back previous disavowals, the FBI now  
admits that federal agents fired one or more incendiary tear gas 
canisters during the 1993 standoff with Branch Davidian cult 
members in Texas, a federal law enforcement official says. The 
agency, however, still maintains it did not start the fire that 
consumed the Davidians' compound with leader David Koresh and more 
than 80 followers inside. The April 19, 1993, inferno ended a 
51-day siege by federal agents trying to serve a warrant for 
Koresh's arrest on firearms and explosive charges. 

</P>
<P>
	Bret Soaks Texas Cotton Fields  
</P>
<P>
	CORPUS CHRISTI, Texas (AP) -- Cotton growers in south Texas will  
have slim pickings in the aftermath of Hurricane Bret. ``There's 
quite a few depressed farmers here now,'' said Bill Ordner, a 
cotton farmer who was among those who fled the storm. He returned 
to his 1,500-acre cotton field southwest of Corpus Christi 
yesterday to find crops ruined. ``It made us sick,'' he said. 
Ordner estimated his losses at $700,000. Bret rolled ashore Sunday 
with drenching rains and 125-mph winds. The storm caused relatively 
few problems considering its size and strength, missing urban areas 
and quickly deteriorating into a tropical storm. 

</P>
<P>
	Fly Halts Calif. Projects  
</P>
<P>
	COLTON, Calif. (AP) -- Some people in this Southern California  
community wish the problem would just buzz off: An endangered 
species of fly is holding up construction projects worth hundreds 
of millions. Communities around the country have squared off 
against environmentalists over owls, foxes, fish and trees. But 
here, the fly has a number of foes: county officials, developers, 
bond holders and residents. The U.S. government has all but halted 
development across the sand dunes in the desert east of Los Angeles 
to protect the tiny Delhi Sands flower-loving fly -- the only fly 
ever to make the Endangered Species List. 

</P>
<P>
	Japanese Stocks Close Lower  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Fears about an overly strong yen sent Tokyo share  
prices falling today. The Nikkei shed 240.25 points to close at 
17,855.16. 

</P>
<P>
	Johnson Sets Sights on 400M Record  
</P>
<P>
	SEVILLE, Spain (AP) -- There was a serious question about Michael  
Johnson's health early this year, but there isn't now: the American 
400-meter runner thinks he can break the world record at the World 
Championships. ``I know I'm in shape to run faster than 43.29,'' 
Johnson said last night after blistering through the first 300 
meters of his semifinal heat and advancing to Thursday night's 
final. American Butch Reynolds set the record in 1988, and Johnson 
has been chasing it in frustration in recent years. He has come 
close three times, with clockings of 43.39, 43.44 and 43.49. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by BRADLEY BROOKS  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
