<DOCNO> APW19990825.0158 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-25 14:20:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bush Pushes Free Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHARLESTON, S.C. (AP) -- Texas Gov. George W. Bush pitched open  
trade Wednesday to a part of the country where many feel stung by 
it, declaring, ``We'll be prosperous if this nation does not 
retreat within its borders.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bush opened a three-day Southern swing with a series of events  
in South Carolina, where his rivals for the Republican presidential 
nomination are working hard for an early February primary. Next 
come campaign stops and fund-raisers in North Carolina and Georgia. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush has been a strong advocate of the North American Free Trade  
Agreement pioneered by his father when he was president and put 
into effect in 1994 by President Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	Texas exports to Mexico have jumped by more than 16 percent in  
two years on the strength of NAFTA. But the results have been 
uneven by industry and region, with critics citing a particular 
toll on textile mills and other industries of the Carolinas. 
</P>
<P>
	``The fearful build walls,'' Bush told the Charleston Rotary  
Club in a wide-ranging stump speech that included his usual defense 
of liberalized trade. 
</P>
<P>
	At a news conference after his speech, Bush, for once, faced  
only drug-free questions. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked about an emotional regional issue, he said it was up to  
people in South Carolina to decide whether the Confederate flag 
should continue to fly over the Statehouse. The NAACP has called 
for a tourist boycott of South Carolina because the flag still 
flies and some like-minded groups have canceled convention plans in 
the state. 
</P>
<P>
	On trade, Bush acknowledged harm done to the textile industry  
and said, without being specific, that he supports ``anti-dumping'' 
laws to prevent some economic sectors from being obliterated. But 
in the main, he said, the United States must compete in the world. 
</P>
<P>
	``I say that free trade is healthy for our economy,'' he told  
reporters. ``We want Mexico to succeed, not fail. After all, they 
are our friends.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In North Carolina, announcements of major plant closures have  
been made three times just this year, eliminating jobs. 
</P>
<P>
	Supporters say NAFTA has been a success, citing increased  
exports and improved relations with neighbors. Opponents say the 
deal has drained jobs from the United States by encouraging 
companies to relocate to Mexico, hire low-paid workers and ship the 
manufactured products back. 
</P>
<P>
	Republican candidate Pat Buchanan calls for a stop to NAFTA when  
he campaigns in South Carolina, warning against the 
``deindustrialization of America.'' Most other candidates in both 
parties either support the deal or have not made it an issue. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990825.0159 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-25 22:20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Family Turning To Mint for Money / Farm Scene  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KEMPTON, N.D. (AP) -- After struggling for years to turn a profit  
with traditional North Dakota crops such as wheat and sunflowers, 
Bob and Karen Landman are making money with mint. 
</P>
<P>
	Not ``a mint,'' but mint. The Landmans have the state's only  
known mint farm, producing spearmint oil that is used to make 
toothpaste, chewing gum and mouthwash. 
</P>
<P>
	``When I started this, I thought it'd be a nice little  
supplement on the farm,'' he said during a break from harvest last 
week. ``But now we rely on it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Landmans' first four crops lost money, but their  
sweet-smelling operation in northeastern North Dakota was in the 
black last year, Landman said. 
</P>
<P>
	They started experimenting with mint in the early 1990s after  
touring a mint farm during a camping trip in Montana. They 
eventually invested in a distillery and mint harvesting equipment, 
but the early years were difficult. 
</P>
<P>
	``That first summer when I was buying this equipment, I had a  
hard time sleeping a lot of nights,'' Bob Landman said. ``Now I 
work so hard I have no trouble sleeping at night.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Landmans have about 300 acres of spearmint, which will  
produce more than 12,000 pounds of oil. They quit growing 
peppermint because the plants didn't do well during North Dakota's 
brutal winters, but they still have some home-cooked peppermint 
paddies in the freezer. 
</P>
<P>
	Their operation also includes 2,600 acres of wheat, durum,  
sunflowers and beans. Mint is harvested in July and August, before 
the other crops. 
</P>
<P>
	Landman, a fourth-generation farmer, said he would have trouble  
staying on the farm if he produced the same crops as his father and 
grandfather. He or his wife would be working a second job off the 
farm without the money from the mint, he said as he hauled the 
harvested crop through a rugged field with a beat-up pickup truck. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would have had to do something, because I would have gone  
under,'' Landman said. 
</P>
<P>
	The green mint plants are swathed, chopped and then hauled to  
the still, where steam is injected into the leaves to extract the 
oil. The oil is then separated and put into drums before being 
shipped. 
</P>
<P>
	Harvest normally lasts about three weeks, but it can go longer  
if weather doesn't cooperate. It's a grueling process, regardless 
of the duration. 
</P>
<P>
	Landman tries to get at least six hours of sleep during mint  
harvest, and his dirt-stained pants are evidence of an arduous day. 
</P>
<P>
	His wife brings out meals and works until dark running the mint  
still. 
</P>
<P>
	The Landmans' children, Sam, 10, and Daniel, 5, also help out  
during harvest. Daniel is just tall enough to guide trucks as they 
back up to pull mint-filled trailers up to the still. 
</P>
<P>
	The Landmans have two-year contracts with companies in Michigan  
and Indiana that pay about $12 to $14 per pound of spearmint oil. 
Mint prices have been lower this year because of an oversupply 
caused by struggling Asian economies. 
</P>
<P>
	But the Landmans say the mint market still beats wheat prices.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's the only thing making money,'' Bob Landman said.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990825.0160 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-25 19:00:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> New ABC Game Show Has Record Winner </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- ABC's hit new game show on Wednesday crowned its  
first half-millionaire, a Virginia lawyer who passed up a chance to 
double his winnings because he didn't know heavy metal music. 
</P>
<P>
	Michael Shutterly, 46, walked away with $500,000 from the show,  
``Who Wants To Be a Millionaire.'' ABC believes that is the highest 
cash award ever given to a game show contestant in television 
history. 
</P>
<P>
	``It just hasn't quite registered yet,'' said Shutterly, a  
father of three from Richmond, Va. ``It will take a couple of days 
until it settles in.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He has some experience counting game show winnings. Shutterly  
earned $49,000 a decade ago as a four-time champion on 
``Jeopardy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the tradition of the new prime-time game show, Shutterly  
answered a series of questions to build up his winnings, earning 
$500,000 because he correctly identified Pope John Paul I as Albino 
Luciani. 
</P>
<P>
	He was offered one last question and a chance to win a million.  
But if he got it wrong, Shutterly's winnings would be sliced to 
$250,000. 
</P>
<P>
	For the final query, Shutterly had to identify the initial hard  
rock Grammy Award winner when the music awards show established the 
category in 1989. The winner, Jethro Tull, was controversial 
because it doesn't really play hard rock. 
</P>
<P>
	Presented with four choices, Shutterly said he felt certain of  
only one thing: that the winner wasn't Jethro Tull. 
</P>
<P>
	Wisely, he chose to pass on the question and leave with  
$500,000. 
</P>
<P>
	``Who Wants To Be a Millionaire'' has been a surprise summer hit  
for ABC during its run of 13 shows in 14 nights. Its audience has 
been increasing throughout the run, and Tuesday night's count of 
just under 16 million viewers was its highest yet. 
</P>
<P>
	Hungry for a success, ABC has already promised producers that  
the game show will be back. 
</P>
<P>
	An international version of the game show has been aired in four  
other countries since last year. None of the overseas versions have 
ever awarded as much as $500,000, ABC said. 
</P>
<P>
	Shutterly said he has only one immediate plan for his winnings,  
and it shows he may have a future as a commercial pitchman, too. He 
echoed the boast of sports stars in commercials after they've won 
the Super Bowl. 
</P>
<P>
	``The kids want to go to Disney World,'' he said.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
