<HEADLINE> Hokies To Join Big East in 2001-02 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) -- Virginia Tech, a member of the Big East  
football league since its inception in 1991, will become a full 
member of the conference beginning in the 2001-02 academic year, 
the league announced Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Hokies will become the 14th member of the league.  
</P>
<P>
	Virginia Tech was offered full membership in the league in June,  
but athletic director Jim Weaver said last month he wanted to delay 
the move until 2001 to reduce the school's withdrawal fee from the 
Atlantic 10 basketball league by $300,000, and to see if Miami, 
another marquee team, was leaving for the Atlantic Coast 
Conference. 
</P>
<P>
	The Hokies eventual full membership is contingent on the  
composition of the league remaining unchanged, Smith said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Hokies haven't been an all-sports member of a conference  
since leaving the Southern Conference in 1965, but have used their 
affiliation with the Big East to help push their football team into 
the national spotlight. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1995, Virginia Tech beat Texas 28-10 in the Sugar Bowl and  
the following year played in the Orange Bowl, losing 41-21 to 
Nebraska. 
</P>
<P>
	The Hokies have been to bowls six straight seasons.  
</P>
<P>
	Tech earns about $100,000 a year under the Atlantic 10's  
revenue-sharing plan, which includes money from TV contracts and 
tournaments. Weaver has said Tech would earn at least $500,000 to 
$750,000 a year from the Big East pot, and possibly more. 
</P>
</TEXT>
