<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 10 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Wednesday, Aug. 25, 1999    	

</P>
<P>
	Report: Israel, Palestinians Close  
</P>
<P>
	JERUSALEM (AP) -- Palestinian negotiator Saeb Erekat delayed a  
trip to Washington today amid reports that the Israelis and 
Palestinians are close to a compromise on reviving a U.S.-brokered 
peace accord. A Palestinian official, speaking on condition of 
anonymity, said agreement had been reached today on a timetable for 
Israel's withdrawal from the West Bank outlined in the accords 
brokered by President Clinton at Wye River, Md., last October. 

</P>
<P>
	Moroccan Airliner Hijacked  
</P>
<P>
	BARCELONA, Spain (AP) -- A Moroccan airliner with 88 people  
aboard was hijacked late tonight while en route to Tunisia, 
officials said. The plane landed in Barcelona and hijackers were 
demanding to fly to Germany. The Royal Air Maroc 737-400 was 
carrying 79 passengers and a crew of nine, said Spanish Interior 
Ministry spokeswoman Luisa Pena. 

</P>
<P>
	Plaintiffs Offer GM Reduced Deal  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Six people severely burned when their  
Chevrolet Malibu exploded in a crash have offered to accept less 
than a tenth of the $4.9 billion a jury awarded them if General 
Motors agrees to recall similar vehicles, their attorney said 
today. Patricia Anderson, her four children and a family friend are 
willing to settle for about $400 million from GM for injuries 
sustained in the 1993 accident, attorney Brian Panish said. GM 
rejected the settlement offer in a written statement. 

</P>
<P>
	FBI Admits Using Tear Gas at Waco  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The FBI, reversing a 6-year-old course,  
admitted tonight its agents may have fired some potentially 
inflammatory tear gas canisters on the final day of the 1993 
standoff with the Branch Davidian cult near Waco, Texas. Cult 
leader David Koresh and many of his followers died during the fire 
that broke out during the FBI's final assault April 19, 1993. 

</P>
<P>
	UN Asked to Create All-Serb Havens  
</P>
<P>
	PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- With NATO-led peacekeepers unable to  
stop reprisal attacks, Serb leaders asked the United Nations today 
to create all-Serb havens within Kosovo, a proposal immediately 
rejected by ethnic Albanians. In the deeply divided town of 
Orahovac, appeals from the United States and others failed to 
persuade ethnic Albanians to abandon their makeshift roadblocks and 
allow Russian peacekeepers to enter the town. 

</P>
<P>
	Russian Forces Drive Out Militants  
</P>
<P>
	MAKHACHKALA, Russia (AP) -- After more than two weeks of  
bombarding invading Islamic militants, Russia's military claimed 
victory today, saying they have largely driven the rebels out of 
the southern republic of Dagestan. Most of the rebel forces fled 
across mountain passes to the breakaway territory of Chechnya, from 
which they had infiltrated Dagestan and seized about half a dozen 
villages Aug. 7. 

</P>
<P>
	Navy Bookkeeping Found To Be Lax  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Navy bookkeeping is so lax that the service  
lost track of $54 million paid by Kuwait for three F-18 jet 
fighters and billed Greece and Japan for seaborne services it 
actually provided to Canada, congressional auditors said today. The 
report by the General Accounting Office said that the Navy's 
bookkeeping in the government's foreign military sales program 
included inaccurate information, ``making it difficult for Navy 
managers to accurately account for and report on the ... program.'' 

</P>
<P>
	UK Lords Miffed Over Essay Contest  
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Hereditary members of the Lords who want to keep  
their seats need to answer one question in 75 words or less before 
an election this fall: why would you like to be in the House of 
Lords? The election is an interim step that will allow the 
hereditary peers to choose 92 of their number to keep their seats 
for a while. Prime Minister Tony Blair is determined to eliminate 
all the 755 hereditary peers from the House of Lords. 

</P>
<P>
	Tokyo Stocks Rise in Early Trading  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese stocks rose moderately following another  
record close on Wall Street. The Nikkei gained 46.08 points to 
17,901.24 in early trading on Thursday. In New York on Wednesday, 
the Dow industrials finished at a record high 11,326.04 points, up 
42.74. 

</P>
<P>
	Sosa Hits 52nd Homer To Take Lead  
</P>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Sammy Sosa hit his 52nd homer tonight, breaking a  
tie with Mark McGwire for the major league lead. Sosa sent a 2-1 
pitch from San Francisco's Kirk Rueter far over the left-field 
fence in the sixth inning of the second game of a doubleheader. 
Sosa's 52nd homer came in the Cubs' 125th game and kept him well 
ahead of his pace last year. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by LINDA KIM  




  	   	
