<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jordanian Soccer Match Ends in Riot </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AMMAN, Jordan (AP) -- A riot at the end of a soccer game,  
dispersed when police fired tear gas at fighting players and fans, 
left scores of people injured Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Doctors and Arab Games officials said least 12 people were  
hospitalized, including two of three players injured in the melee 
after the match between teams from Palestinian and Libyan 
territories. The street outside the stadium was littered with 
broken glass from windshields of cars rioters smashed. 
</P>
<P>
	The trouble started after the Palestinians tied the second-round  
game 2-2 at the end. Angry Libyan fans pulled out the chairs at the 
stadium and attacked Palestinian supporters, who retaliated, 
government officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	The witnesses said the fans hurled bottles with frozen water and  
soda bottles looted from snack stands, and fought with wooden 
sticks and iron parts of the uprooted chairs. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, there was trouble in the changing room after the  
players left the field. Libyan players burst into the Palestinian 
area and exchanged blows, a television crew member said on 
condition of anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	He said the Libyans were armed with iron chains.  
</P>
<P>
	Two of the players were hospitalized, one with chest and  
shoulder injuries and another with a torn thigh muscle, said Dr. 
Mouafak al-Jamal at the Specialist Hospital where there injured 
were being treated. 
</P>
<P>
	He said the other injured people suffered cuts in the head.  
</P>
<P>
	``I stitched them up and sent them home,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	A senior government official, speaking on condition of  
anonymity, said a Libyan player was also seen hurling a tear gas 
canister at the Palestinian locker room before police moved in. 
</P>
<P>
	Riot police intervened, and fired tear gas inside the room to  
disperse the players. They also fired tear gas canisters in the 
tunnel connecting the field to the changing room. 
</P>
<P>
	``The police tried to help us, but they were beaten up, too, by  
the Libyans,'' said Saeed Jandiye, a Palestinian player. 
</P>
<P>
	After dispersing the players, police moved near the gates of the  
stadium, where most of the rioting was taking place. They fired 
tear gas again and fought pitched battles with the fans. 
</P>
<P>
	Several police were among those injured, the officials said.  
</P>
<P>
	Tempers had been flaring since the start of the match, when the  
Palestinians scored a goal in the 15th second. The Libyan players 
were further angered because they apparently thought that the 
referee unjustly allowed the game to spill into injury time, giving 
the Palestinians an opportunity to tie. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
