<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.S., Israel Disagree on Teen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JERUSALEM (AP) -- Prosecutors in Israel and the United States  
disagree vehemently about an American teen's plea bargain on a 
murder charge, a situation that has revived tensions between the 
allies. 
</P>
<P>
	Israel's Attorney General on Wednesday rejected a Maryland  
prosecutor's criticism that Samuel Sheinbein's likely 24-year 
sentence for the 1997 murder of Alfred Tello Jr. is too lenient. 
</P>
<P>
	``We treated this as a vicious murder by accepting a plea that  
is in the very upper levels of cases for minors,'' Elyakim 
Rubinstein told a press conference packed with Israeli reporters. 
</P>
<P>
	Sheinbein was 17 at the time of the murder. Under Israeli law  
juveniles cannot be tried as adults. 
</P>
<P>
	Other Israelis worried that the revived flap could adversely  
affect relations between Israel and its closest ally. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Americans don't understand how a strapping, healthy --  
violent, even -- 17-year old can be treated as a minor, and frankly, 
neither can I,'' Amnon Rubinstein, an Israeli legislator who is not 
related to the attorney general, told Israel TV. ``A 17-year-old 
murderer is not a minor. He deserves life.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gil Tamari, Israel TV's Washington correspondent, held up the  
front page of The Washington Post on the evening newscast, with the 
headline ``Sheinbein to Plead Guilty in Israel,'' and warned: 
``This case is causing grave damage to Israel's image in the United 
States.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Amnon Rubinstein led a successful effort this year to modify the  
law that Sheinbein used to seek asylum here -- albeit too late to 
extradite the teen. The 1978 law was designed to protect Jews from 
being prosecuted by anti-Semites. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S.-born Sheinbein fled to Israel days after the  
dismembered and charred body of Tello was discovered near 
Sheinbein's home in Maryland. Citing his Israeli-born father's 
citizenship, he sought refuge under a broad anti-extradition law. 
Otherwise, he had only visited Israel a few times as a child and 
had little connection with the country. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. authorities expressed outrage at Sheinbein's manipulation  
of the system, and some U.S. lawmakers threatened to cut aid to 
Israel if Sheinbein was not returned. 
</P>
<P>
	The Israeli government was sympathetic and Attorney General  
Rubinstein fought all the way to the Supreme Court to extradite 
Sheinbein. But the court upheld Sheinbein's citizenship earlier 
this year and set the stage for the trial to take place in Israel. 
</P>
<P>
	Sheinbein entered a not guilty plea, and the attorney general's  
staff -- seeking to avoid a lengthy, costly trial that would likely 
further exacerbate U.S.-Israel relations -- began negotiating a plea 
bargain. 
</P>
<P>
	As a courtesy, Israeli officials faxed the plea bargain to  
Montgomery County State Attorney Douglas Gansler's office on 
Monday. Under Israeli law -- considerably more liberal than in the 
United States -- Sheinbein is eligible for parole after 16 years, 
likely to include the two years he has already spent in jail. He is 
also eligible for weekend furloughs after six years. 
</P>
<P>
	Sheinbein is scheduled to reverse his not guilty plea at a Sept.  
2 court hearing. 
</P>
<P>
	At a press conference Tuesday, Gansler expressed his outrage  
with the deal. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're not pleased with the result, because it's still a very  
short sentence in terms of what he would have gotten here,'' 
Gansler said. 
</P>
<P>
	Attorney General Rubinstein was furious with Gansler for  
violating a request to keep the deal secret until Sept. 2. The 
judge is free to reject the plea bargain, and could be influenced 
by media reporting of the case. 
</P>
<P>
	``We didn't feel it was proper, we felt it was a breach of  
professional faith,'' the attorney general said. 
</P>
<P>
	But the attorney general, who said Israel would pay for a member  
of Tello's family to attend the hearing, was quick to declare that 
revived tensions over the extradition case had not damaged 
diplomatic relations between the countries. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hope this will not have any effect whatsoever because it  
shouldn't,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Others were not so sure.  
</P>
<P>
	``It may very well harm relations between the two legal  
systems,'' Emanuel Gross, a Haifa University criminal law expert, 
told Israel army radio. ``This is about an American citizen who has 
no connection with the state of Israel, and who received shelter 
and protection just because ... he held a sliver of Israeli 
citizenship.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Government ministers expressed their discomfort with the  
emerging ruckus. 
</P>
<P>
	``I believe that it is forbidden for us to become a shelter''  
for Jewish criminals, Michael Melchior, the minister who liaises 
with the Jewish Diaspora, told Israel radio. ``It is anti-Jewish.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
