<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Five Questions With John Lewis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- John Lewis, famous for his 40-plus years of  
playing piano and composing for the Modern Jazz Quartet, still 
improvises when he plays live and makes recordings. 
</P>
<P>
	``For me, improvisation is one of the most exciting parts of  
making music,'' Lewis said during an interview in his Manhattan 
apartment. ``You're not confined. If you have enough imagination, 
you don't have to repeat.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the 17th century, Lewis said, Bach and Handel composed  
variations on themes so they wouldn't repeat. And musicians 
improvised a lot. ``You have to try to be as perfect as you can 
when you're improvising -- without the advantage of an eraser,'' he 
said. ``And it's like composing -- it should be a complete and 
satisfying experience.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lewis was born in LaGrange, Ill., in 1920, and grew up in  
Albuquerque, N.M. He began piano lessons at 6. Before he was 12, he 
had earned Boy Scout merit badges in music, played for a Holy 
Roller church for 50 cents and played Saturday nights at a 
nightclub for $1. 
</P>
<P>
	He studied at the University of New Mexico and got a master's  
degree from the Manhattan School of Music in 1953. 
</P>
<P>
	Lewis and nine other American jazz pianists, billed as 100  
Golden Fingers, toured Japan this summer, giving 14 concerts in 18 
days. For the finale, they all played ``Take the A Train,'' quickly 
trading places on two pianos. 
</P>
<P>
	The Modern Jazz Quartet began recording in 1952 with Lewis,  
vibraphonist Milt Jackson, bassist Percy Heath and drummer Kenny 
Clarke. When Clarke moved to Paris in 1955, Connie Kay replaced him 
and the quartet continued until Kay's death in 1994. 
</P>
<P>
	Lewis took time out from his busy schedule to answer questions  
about his long career. 
</P>
<P>
	1. Do you miss the Manhattan Jazz Quartet?  
</P>
<P>
	Lewis: Yes. It would be hard not to miss a major part of my  
life. Milt, Percy and I keep in contact. They're still playing. 
Percy's youngest brother, Albert, played drums with us for a while 
but he lives in California, which makes rehearsing difficult. So 
far we haven't had any reunions. 
</P>
<P>
	2. What is your favorite context for playing piano?  
</P>
<P>
	Lewis: My favorite is solo. It's very difficult to do and takes  
a lot of work to make it come off. For a listener, a band is very 
attractive. There's a lot of things to look at; it's actually a 
show. The most impressed I ever was with a band was the Duke 
Ellington Band playing in Albuquerque in 1939 and 1941. They were 
impressive before they ever played a note. When they played, it was 
overwhelming. 
</P>
<P>
	3. Your new CD is solo piano, isn't it?  
</P>
<P>
	Lewis: Yes. It's `Evolution,' the first of three CDs for  
Atlantic Records. Two pieces from it will be in the next CD, which 
will be a trio album, and two pieces from the first two will be in 
the third CD, played by an instrumental group including horns. At 
least one tune will be on all three. That's an opportunity for me 
and other people who are interested to see how a piece of music can 
evolve. 
</P>
<P>
	4. Did you compose anything on ``Evolution''?  
</P>
<P>
	Lewis: Yes. `At the Horse Show' I wrote for this album. `For  
Ellington' I wrote for the MJQ as the title song for an album. Milt 
wrote one for that album; the rest were Ellington pieces. I made it 
feel like a piece of church music. It starts off like a simple 
hymn. I tried to make it turn to a gospel feeling and go back to 
the hymn to close. I was inspired by Ellington's devotion to his 
sacred concerts near the end of his life. `Afternoon in Paris' and 
`Two Degrees East, Three Degrees West' I wrote before the quartet, 
in 1948. 
</P>
<P>
	5. How has your piano playing changed over the years?  
</P>
<P>
	Lewis: I worked in Dizzy Gillespie's big band from 1946 into  
1948 and again in 1950. I accompanied singers at the beginning of 
our quartet. We were trying to build up literature; everybody had 
to do other things. I was fortunate to accompany Ella Fitzgerald 
for six months. I made records and toured Japan with Helen Merrill. 
And I played in theaters for Sarah Vaughan when I was working for 
Dizzy. My piano playing may seem like it has changed but it hasn't. 
Maybe some things have become refined and I can control them 
better. But it hasn't really changed. I do what I do and that's it. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
