<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hurricane Heads Toward U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NASSAU, Bahamas (AP) -- Hurricane Dennis was headed for this  
island chain early Thursday with 75 mph winds after being upgraded 
from a tropical storm. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. National Hurricane Center in Miami urged people on the  
southeast coast of the United States, primarily North and South 
Carolina, to closely monitor Dennis. 
</P>
<P>
	Anticipating possible heavy rains, the South Florida Water  
Management District on Wednesday started to drain canals to stave 
off flooding. 
</P>
<P>
	``The uncertainty is killing us,'' said district spokeswoman Ann  
Overton. 
</P>
<P>
	Bahamians took a nonchalant attitude.  
</P>
<P>
	``I think some degree of complacency has developed in the  
Bahamas because we have had the good fortune of escaping a direct 
hit of a hurricane for a number of years,'' said Godwin Blyden of 
the Bahamas National Disaster Organization. 
</P>
<P>
	At 2 a.m. EDT, Dennis was centered near latitude 23.8 north,  
longitude 73.1 west, 290 miles east-southeast of Nassau, the 
Bahamian capital. 
</P>
<P>
	The storm was moving northwest near 5 mph and expected to  
strengthen. It was upgraded to a hurricane late Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's looking like it's going to be in the central Bahamas by  
Thursday,'' said meteorologist Trisha Wallace at the National 
Hurricane Center in Miami. 
</P>
<P>
	Before it was upgraded to hurricane status, Dennis was one of  
three tropical storms in the area. Emily sprang up Tuesday at near 
hurricane strength, surprising forecasters who hadn't even thought 
it was a depression. Wednesday morning, they warned people in the 
Lesser Antilles Islands in the southeastern Caribbean to monitor 
the storm. 
</P>
<P>
	But Emily weakened quickly. Wednesday night it had top winds of  
45 mph and was centered near 13.4 north latitude, 55.7 west 
longitude, 255 miles east of Barbados. It was moving northwest at 
about 7 mph with little change expected. 
</P>
<P>
	Emily may tangle with Tropical Storm Cindy, which was near  
hurricane strength with winds of 70 mph but far out in the Atlantic 
with no threat to land. Meteorologists explained that if the storms 
do combine, the resulting system would probably not suddenly become 
twice as strong. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
