<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Choosing Options for Long-Term Care </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- Americans are living longer and healthier than  
ever before. Yet many will find themselves needing long-term care 
at some point in their life, cautions an insurance expert at the 
College for Financial Planning. 
</P>
<P>
	That's why it's important to plan ahead in order to choose the  
best option or options to pay for any long term care needs. 
</P>
<P>
	``An American Health Care Association study several years ago  
found that one in three people who reach the age of 65 will spend 
at least three months in a nursing home, and one in four will spend 
a full year or longer in a nursing home,'' says Michael Snowdon, an 
academic associate at the College. 
</P>
<P>
	With nursing home costs running $40,000 to $60,000 a year, even  
a short stay can be expensive. And the percentage of people needing 
home health care is even higher, Snowdon notes. 
</P>
<P>
	So how do you pay for these long-term care costs? Snowdon says  
there are several options, and as people reach their late 50s and 
early 60s they need to think seriously about what is the best 
option for them. They also need to be aware of some of the 
misconceptions people have about paying for long-term care. 
</P>
<P>
	One of the biggest misconceptions is that Medicare, or the  
Medicare supplemental insurance known as Medigap, will pay for 
long-term care. Medicare will pay for skilled nursing and home care 
only in limited circumstances; Medigap policies don't substantially 
expand that coverage. 
</P>
<P>
	Medicaid will pay for long-term nursing home stays, and  
sometimes home health care, but a person basically has to be 
impoverished before qualifying for coverage. Furthermore, Snowdon 
says, experience has shown that Medicaid patients tend not to 
receive the same level of care compared to what they would receive 
on a private-pay basis. 
</P>
<P>
	The most favorable option for paying for long-term care usually  
is long-term care insurance, either private or through group 
coverage at work, according to Snowdon. 
</P>
<P>
	``However, long-term care insurance isn't necessarily the best  
answer for everyone,'' Snowdon says. ``You have to look at its cost 
effectiveness.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For example, he says a study by the United Seniors Health  
Cooperative recommends that long-term care insurance can be a good 
buy for households where there are more than $75,000 in assets per 
person, income of $30,000 or more per person, and they can afford 
premium increases of 20 percent to 30 percent in the future. People 
who have less than these assets and income may find the insurance 
coverage too expensive and may be better off relying on other 
options. 
</P>
<P>
	Snowdon adds that households with substantial assets may be able  
to fund their own long-term care needs, though insurance would 
minimize the impact on those assets. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the value of long-term care insurance in many  
circumstances, people who could afford to pay for it often refuse 
to buy it, Snowdon says. This doesn't make sense, he adds. ``A 
homeowner would never risk going without homeowner's insurance. Yet 
your potential exposure to long-term care is significantly higher 
than the risk to your home.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Snowdon notes several other alternatives people may want to  
consider if long-term care insurance isn't in the picture. One 
option is to own life insurance with a rider that pays out a 
portion of the face value of the policy -- typically up to 2 percent 
a month -- for long-term care needs. 
</P>
<P>
	This may be useful if you have a brief need, Snowdon says, but  
if you need care for a long time you're ``cannibalizing'' your life 
insurance policy because you're eating away what's left of the 
policy's proceeds. 
</P>
<P>
	Furthermore, Snowdon points out that you will need to have a lot  
of life insurance to fund an annual nursing home bill of $40,000 or 
$50,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Another option, he says, is to use a reverse mortgage. This is  
when the mortgage company pays you money based on the equity you've 
built up in your home. The money isn't paid back until you die or 
sell your home. This can be helpful in situations where someone is 
cash-poor but house-rich, though Medicaid may be the better option 
since you may not be required to give up your home. 
</P>
<P>
	Retirees also may want to consider setting aside an annuity  
specifically to cover long-term care. If you never need it, the 
money can be used for other purposes. 
</P>
<P>
	The important point is to consider ahead of time what option or  
options are best for you, Snowdon says. For example, if you have 
the money and you're in good health, you might insure part of the 
risk through long-term care coverage and pay for the remainder out 
of personal savings or an annuity. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990825.0187 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-25 10:24:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Clinton Vacation: Read, Rest, Sun </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EDGARTOWN, Mass. (AP) -- No fund-raisers, no parties, no dinner  
out. The president read. The first lady nursed a summer cold. They 
joined their daughter on the beach. 
</P>
<P>
	Tuesday was a quiet, relaxed vacation day for Bill, Hillary and  
Chelsea Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	The White House press office brushed aside attempts to stir  
controversy. 
</P>
<P>
	Back in Washington, a spokesman for the White House counsel's  
office told a newspaper that, as was said during his 1992 campaign, 
the president had never used cocaine. Not once. 
</P>
<P>
	At the vacation press center on the Massachusetts island of  
Martha's Vineyard, White House press secretary Joe Lockhart said 
the denial of cocaine use was ``both authorized and accurate.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lockhart had told reporters on Monday that the president has  
expressed no interest in news stories discussing whether Texas Gov. 
George W. Bush, the front-runner for the Republican presidential 
nomination, ever used cocaine. 
</P>
<P>
	Then there was the cigar. The White House spokesman said it  
wasn't lit. 
</P>
<P>
	Enterprising photographers snapped the president Monday on the  
second hole of the Farm Neck golf club here chomping on a large 
stogie. A story said he had lit it and was puffing on it. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've never seen the president light a cigar,'' Lockhart said  
when asked about it. ``I've seen him, obviously, chew on the end of 
it. I don't think he had a lit cigar. I've seen the picture. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's no smoking gun, as the case may be.''  
</P>
<P>
	After five straight nights of fund-raisers and social  
engagements, the Clintons spent the night at their borrowed Oyster 
Pond vacation home. Lockhart described the first lady's nagging 
summer cold as ``nothing serious'' and said that when he saw the 
Clintons, they were on the beach. 
</P>
<P>
	Lockhart said the Clintons wanted to unwind and relax before  
heading to New York state this weekend for a busy round of money 
raising for Democrats generally and for the first lady's 
near-certain run for a New York Senate seat in particular. 
</P>
<P>
	They'll try to enjoy themselves as well as they begin their  
second vacation week in the Hamptons on Long Island. 
</P>
<P>
	``I expect he'll have some time to relax there and enjoy the  
wonderful, natural surroundings,'' Lockhart said. ``The ocean, the 
beach and potentially some fine golf courses.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990825.0188 </DOCNO>
