<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lemon Drop Kid Eyes Saratoga Win </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SARATOGA SPRINGS, N.Y. (AP) -- Scotty Schulhofer has a simple  
plan for Belmont Stakes winner Lemon Drop Kid. 
</P>
<P>
	``Win the Travers, win the Gold Cup and go on to the Breeders'  
Cup,'' the Hall of Fame trainer said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Lemon Drop Kid is expected to oppose seven other 3-year-olds in  
$1 million Travers on Saturday at Saratoga. 
</P>
<P>
	The colt, owned by Jeanne and Laddie Vance, then will be pointed  
to the Jockey Club Gold Cup on Oct. 9 at Belmont Park and the 
Breeders' Cup Classic on Nov. 6 at Gulfstream Park. 
</P>
<P>
	Two of Lemon Drop Kid's rivals in the 1 1/4-mile Travers will be  
the Elliott Walden-trained Menifee and Ecton Park. 
</P>
<P>
	Menifee, second in both the Kentucky Derby and Preakness,  
finished eighth in the Belmont. In his only start since, he won the 
1 1/8-mile Haskell Invitational Handicap on Aug. 8 at Monmouth Park. 
</P>
<P>
	In three starts since finishing 12th in the Kentucky Derby,  
Ecton Park won an allowance race at Churchill Downs, finished 
second in the 1 1/8-mile Ohio Derby at Thistledown and won the 1 1/8-mile 
Jim Dandy on Aug. 8 at Saratoga. 
</P>
<P>
	``Menifee is the horse to beat,'' Schulhofer said. ``If it comes  
up sloppy, he has his other horse.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lemon Drop Kid finished second, 5 1/4 lengths behind Ecton Park, on  
a sloppy track in the Jim Dandy. 
</P>
<P>
	Schulhofer feels it was the track that did in Lemon Drop Kid.  
</P>
<P>
	``That was it,'' he said. ``The horse ran a good race.''  
</P>
<P>
	The Jim Dandy was first start for Lemon Drop Kid since his  
victory in the 1 1/2-mile Belmont on June 5, and the sixth of the year 
for the colt, a May foal. 
</P>
<P>
	After winning two of six starts, with two seconds and a third,  
as a 2-year-old, Lemon Drop Kid, bought for $200,000 as a yearling, 
opened his 3-year-old campaign by winning an allowance race on Feb. 
27. He next finished fifth in the 1 1/8-mile Blue Grass won by Menifee 
on April 10 at Keeneland, then was ninth in the 1 1/4-mile Kentucky 
Derby on May 1. 
</P>
<P>
	After skipping the 1 3-16-mile Preakness on May 15, Lemon Drop  
Kid finished third in the 1 1/8-mile Peter Pan won by Travers 
probability Best of Luck on a muddy track May 23 at Belmont Park. 
He then won Belmont Stakes in which Derby-Preakness winner 
Charismatic was injured while finishing third 
</P>
<P>
	Lemon Drop Kid was then rested until the Jim Dandy.  
</P>
<P>
	Schulhofer said he has had no second thoughts about not pushing  
Lemon Drop Kid harder. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's done nothing but go forward,'' Schulhofer said. ``I've  
got good owners who let me do what I think is best, and it's worked 
out real well.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Others expected to be entered in the Travers on Thursday were  
Badger Gold, Cat Thief, Unbridled Jet and Vision and Verse. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
