<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Little League Notebook </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WILLIAMSPORT, Pa. (AP) -- There isn't much pressure on a Little  
League manager in the United States. But in Japan, it's a different 
story. 
</P>
<P>
	Manager Tsutomu Kameyama, who also played for the Hanshin  
Tigers, knows all about it. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is not a lot of pressure on the Little League players --  
besides the pressure they put on themselves,'' Kameyama said 
through an interpreter, Bill Lundy. ``All of the pressure is on the 
manager. I bring it all on myself.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kameyama, now a sports consultant, went 10-1 on the way to the  
series, including a 14-4 win over Korea in the Far East 
championship. His team is 2-1 and may have to wait until Wednesday 
to learn whether it will reach Thursday's international 
championship, probably against Puerto Rico. 
</P>
<P>
	``I will work one, two, three years, whatever it takes'' to take  
the team to a championship, he said. 
</P>
<P>
                            	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	TAKING CANDY FROM A BOISE: Edward Hughmanic, general manager of  
the United Water business in Toms River, N.J., can look forward to 
a taste treat from the Northwest -- potato candy. 
</P>
<P>
	Toms River's 4-0 win over Boise on Monday means that United  
Water of Boise's Bill Linham has to pay up with five boxes of 
potato shaped Idaho Spud Candy. Had Toms River lost, Linham would 
have gotten a taste of the boardwalk with five boxes of salt water 
taffy, according to the Asbury Park Press. 
</P>
<P>
                            	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	TOMS RIVER REDUX: Toms River manager Mike Gaynor said the thing  
that makes the 1999 team better than 1998 championship squad is 
depth. 
</P>
<P>
	``It seems like this team has a few more heroes every evening --  
Zack Del Vento, Chris Fontenelli,'' he said. ``That team knew how 
to win a game when it needed to pull one out, and this team knows 
how to win a game when it needs to pull one out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He was asked if everyone on his team pitched.  
</P>
<P>
	``Everyone except Cunningham -- he's terrible,'' he said,  
needling catcher Chris Cunningham, who was also at a post-game news 
conference Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The unlikely heroes include R.J. Jones, who had a pinch-hit  
single and scored in the win over Boise, Idaho on Tuesday night. 
And everyone gets a chance to be a hero with Little League's 
must-play rule. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'll get 12 players in there on Thursday night, and hopefully  
I'll have a chance to get 12 players in there on Saturday,'' Gaynor 
said. 
</P>
<P>
                            	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	NOTES: U.S. country star Kenny Rogers will perform his song  
``The Greatest,'' about a little boy's baseball dreams, before 
Saturday's championship game. Rogers, an avid softball player, is 
paying his own way to Williamsport. ... Little League volunteer 
Fred Blankenhorn spent his 59th birthday Tuesday showing the 
Japanese team around. As one of the Little League ``uncles,'' 
Blankenhorn's job is to help players with whatever they might need 
while in Williamsport. ... Carlos Davila, the son of a member of 
Puerto Rico's Senate, played left field and was 0-for-2 for Yabucoa 
on Tuesday in a 3-1 win over Japan. ... Brownsburg, Ind.'s Steve 
Veza, who nearly robbed Kyle Tidwell of a game-winning grand slam 
in a loss Monday to Phenix City, Ala., said he missed the ball by 3 
or 4 inches. He told Star-News.Com, the Indianapolis newspapers' 
web site, that he might have caught the ball if the fence hadn't 
stopped him on the way up. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
