<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-25 10:30:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Americans Will Miss Mir </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) -- They endured a fire and crash,  
breakdowns and blackouts, sweltering heat and noxious fumes. 
</P>
<P>
	One came back noticeably thinner, another looking skeletal,  
thanks to rations on the space station Mir. A third struggled with 
depression. 
</P>
<P>
	Once back on Earth, more than one vowed never to return. Three  
promptly quit the astronaut corps. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet as Mir finally begins to wind down, its last long-duration  
crew due to leave Saturday and a fiery plunge planned for early 
next year, the seven Americans who lived on the venerable Russian 
station to help NASA prepare for a new space station can't help but 
feel a little nostalgic. 
</P>
<P>
	Sure, they'll miss Mir, or at least miss knowing Mir's there.  
But it's high time, they say, for a new house in the sky: the 
NASA-led international space station. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's sort of like if you've lived in a house and you've really  
enjoyed living in the house and maybe your kids have been born 
there,'' says NASA astronaut Shannon Lucid. ``But then there comes 
a point in time when you need those extra bedrooms and you need to 
move.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lucid lived on Mir for six months in 1996 and, in doing so, set  
a space endurance record not only for Americans but also for women 
worldwide. 
</P>
<P>
	A biochemist in her 50s with grown children, Lucid was the only  
American woman on Mir. Her craving for M&AMP;M's and potato chips and 
her delayed homecoming -- she spent more than six extra weeks in 
orbit because of problems with her shuttle ride home -- endeared her 
to everyone. 
</P>
<P>
	``Any time that you leave some place, obviously you're more than  
anxious to get home. But you do feel a certain sadness,'' Lucid 
says. ``I sort of feel the same way about the thought of Mir 
re-entering the Earth's atmosphere and burning up. Mir has been a 
very historic part of space travel, and I think you'll feel a sense 
of loss when Mir comes down.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. David Wolf also will be sorry to see Mir go, even though he  
says it's time the Russians focus their scarce resources on the 
international space station, a work in progress 250 miles in the 
sky. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's like maybe a place you used to live. You may never go  
back, but you always know you could,'' says Wolf, who stayed on Mir 
from the end of September 1997 to January 1998. ``The grape juice 
spill I got all over the wall -- I'd be able to see the stains. A 
few things that I fixed up there, I'd be able to go see how they 
held out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The first American on Mir, Dr. Norman Thagard, came across as a  
whiner after he arrived in March 1995. But the truth is, he sat on 
Mir almost two months with virtually nothing to do, waiting for his 
experiments to arrive on the Spektre module. Originally scheduled 
to attach to Mir before Thagard's arrival, Spektre was not launched 
until that June. 
</P>
<P>
	NASA had underestimated the psychological hardships of training  
for a year in Russia, conversing in Russian, then living with 
Russians on THEIR space station. 
</P>
<P>
	Thagard returned from almost four months aloft looking anemic  
and haggard. He'd lost muscle. By year's end, he'd resigned. 
</P>
<P>
	John Blaha, the only test pilot and nonscientist of the bunch,  
also suffered on Mir. He replace Lucid and spent the first month of 
his four-month mission in a depression -- he badly missed his wife 
of 30 years, back home in Houston. 
</P>
<P>
	He says he finally told himself: ``This is crazy, John. You need  
to get happy that you're here again'' in space. ``I realized that I 
was clinging to Earth so to speak. I psychologically cut the cords 
with all those things that were on the planet that I couldn't have. 
... Once I did, I really enjoyed the Mir space station. I was happy 
to get up in the morning and go to work.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Next came Dr. Jerry Linenger, who battled two-foot flames from a  
burst oxygen generator in February 1997, then English-American 
Michael Foale, who four months later found himself trying to save 
the ruptured station following a near-catastrophic collision with a 
cargo ship. 
</P>
<P>
	Within months of returning to Earth, Blaha and Linenger followed  
Thagard out the door. 
</P>
<P>
	Wolf relieved Foale in September 1997 after considerable debate  
over whether Mir was safe. A female astronaut should have followed 
Foale, but was bumped for being too small for a Russian 
space-walking suit, necessary for outdoor repairs. Wolf spent most 
of his time doing maintenance and repairs on the insufferably hot 
space station. He returned 20 pounds lighter. 
</P>
<P>
	Australian-American Andrew Thomas closed out the shuttle-Mir  
collaboration in June 1998. In all, the seven astronauts spent a 
total of 907 days on Mir. 
</P>
<P>
	Although some of the seven American volunteers had it tougher  
than others, ``it was certainly not easy for any one of them,'' 
says NASA's Jim Van Laak. 
</P>
<P>
	``They did not anticipate before the mission ... how hard they  
had to work or how deep they had to go within themselves to be 
successful. But they all did and all grew as a result of it.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990825.0202 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-25 10:17:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> New Career As Writer and Producer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Polly Draper makes a short gagging sound -- a  
quiet cough that barely reverberates over the hum of traffic beyond 
the walls of a dressing room in the Music Box Theater. 
</P>
<P>
	She is demonstrating a symptom of Tourette's Syndrome, the  
neurological disorder that most people associate with violent 
shaking and outbursts of obscenity. 
</P>
<P>
	``Only 10 to 15 percent of the people who have Tourette's have  
that,'' says Draper. ``But it's the kind most depicted in the 
movies and on television.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Not in her new film, though. The actress has become something of  
an authority on the disease. Tourette's figures prominently in 
``The Tic Code,'' the movie she wrote and which she co-produced 
with her husband, jazz musician Michael Wolff, who has a mild form 
of the illness. 
</P>
<P>
	For the 43-year-old Draper, still remembered for her role as  
Ellyn, the insecure career woman on television's 
``thirtysomething,'' the movie is the first fruit of a new career 
as a writer-producer. The film will be released later this year or 
early next year. It already has won praise at various film 
festivals from Vancouver to Berlin. 
</P>
<P>
	Not that she has given up acting. Draper, who trained at the  
Yale School of Drama, spent her summer working on Broadway. She 
replaced Natasha Richardson in ``Closer,'' Patrick Marber's smart, 
occasionally savage look at love and sex in London during the last 
decade before the millennium. 
</P>
<P>
	Marber altered the leading role for Draper, turning an  
Englishwoman, played by the London-born Richardson, into an 
American. 
</P>
<P>
	``Patrick kept saying he wanted someone who was openhearted,''  
Draper says. ``That's the word he kept using as a description of 
the character: `She's very openhearted.' So all the experiences 
that come her way are received in that light. She's not a 
manipulator. I like to think I'm like that, too -- that I'm just out 
there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Draper is also persistent. ``The Tic Code'' took five years to  
get to the screen. The actress started writing the script before 
she had her first child, Matt, now 4, and she was pregnant with her 
second son while the actual filming took place. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Tic Code'' concerns a mother and her 10-year-old son, a  
gifted young pianist who has Tourette's. The boy forges a 
friendship with a jazz musician who also has the disease. The 
musician, played by Gregory Hines, gets involved with the mother, 
too. 
</P>
<P>
	``People have told me that it is the most amazing mother-and-son  
relationship they have seen,'' Draper says. ``That's one of the 
reasons why I wanted to write it. At that stage in my career, I was 
starting to audition for mother parts, and I thought they were so 
phonily written.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Draper knew she could do better, even though she had never  
written a full-length script. Yet she did her share of tinkering. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've been in a lot of bad TV movies and in self-defense just  
had to change some lines,'' she says. ``I thought, `You know, I 
could do my own one of these instead of helping other people so 
much.' And that's when I started writing it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As a child Draper thought of becoming a writer.  
</P>
<P>
	``I used to ride my bike home from school and think up different  
stories I was going to write down,'' she recalls. ``The transfer to 
becoming an actress wasn't much of a stretch because I still was 
using my imagination. But the good thing about writing is you get 
to play every single part in your head.'' 
</P>
<P>
	An impetus for the script was her husband's illness. The two met  
in 1989 on Arsenio Hall's television show where Wolff was the 
bandleader. Wolff also contributed the jazz score to the movie. 
</P>
<P>
	``I wanted Tourette's to be a metaphor for a certain emotional  
freedom, the way jazz is a metaphor for musical freedom because it 
is such a free-form kind of music,'' says Draper. 
</P>
<P>
	``To someone who doesn't know, a person with Tourette's can seem  
nutty -- like there is something wrong with them,'' the actress 
says. ``With Michael, it almost looks like he is singing to music 
all the time. So I think that people never really questioned it 
because he is a musician. He tells me I was the only one who was 
rude enough to ask.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The Tic Code'' cost $2.7 million, pocket change for Hollywood  
studios but a fortune if you are raising it yourself. 
</P>
<P>
	The project faced roadblocks. Script readers at the big studios  
loved it; the marketing people ran the other way -- a disease story, 
a little kid story (usually box-office death), an interracial 
romance, and starring the woman who wrote it, too. 
</P>
<P>
	``The financing was raised haphazardly at best,'' Draper says  
with a sigh. ``We got $1 million when Gregory came aboard, but it 
was a struggle.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Now, dividing her time between Los Angeles and New York, she is  
on to her next writing project -- a play, which Draper describes as 
much more avant-garde than her movie. 
</P>
<P>
	``A character who has died comes back to life to talk to the  
audience,'' she says. ``He is basically soliciting their good will 
for a person he is trying to get into heaven. It's called `Getting 
into Heaven.' We shall see what happens.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
