<HEADLINE> Redskins' Bowie Breaks Ankle Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ASHBURN, Va. (AP) -- Washington Redskins fullback Larry Bowie,  
attempting to come back from a broken ankle, broke it again 
Wednesday after jumping over a defender during practice. 
</P>
<P>
	Bowie, the team's best backfield blocker, landed awkwardly on  
the saturated artificial turf at Redskin Park and was dejected as 
he was driven away on an equipment cart. Heavy rain had forced the 
team to move the practice from the regular grass fields. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was in a lot of pain,'' trainer Bubba Tyer said. ``He knew  
it wasn't a sprained ankle.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tyer said the fracture was in the lower left fibula, the same  
part of the leg that was broken in the second quarter against 
Dallas in the fifth game last season. Bowie underwent surgery and 
did not play the rest of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	According to Tyer, this injury was not as severe and would not  
require surgery. The leg will be placed in a cast for about five 
weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	Tyer said Bowie would then have to spend up to five weeks in  
rehabilitation, although a better prognosis for his return wouldn't 
be known until a full examination Thursday morning. 
</P>
<P>
	Bowie made the Redskins as an undrafted rookie from Georgia in  
1996 and became the starter in 1997. After he was injured last 
year, the team moved Stephen Davis to fullback for the rest of the 
season. 
</P>
<P>
	Bowie worked hard in the offseason to rehabilitate the ankle,  
but continued to feel discomfort during training camp. 
</P>
<P>
	His injury makes the offseason acquisition of Larry Centers even  
more crucial. Centers was expected to play more than Bowie anyway, 
but primarily as a receiving back. Bowie, who weighs 25 pounds more 
than Centers, was expected to lead the way through the holes on 
running plays and help protect the passer. 
</P>
<P>
	The only other fullback on the current roster is second-year  
player Mike Sellers, who played tight end last season. The Redskins 
were using Sellers at his old position in some workouts this week 
because tight ends Stephen Alexander and Kevin Pesak also are hurt. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
