<HEADLINE> Jim Bakker's Son Has Own Ministry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Jay Bakker looks more like a punk rocker than a  
preacher, and that's exactly the point. 
</P>
<P>
	The tattooed and pierced son of fallen evangelists Jim and Tammy  
Fay Bakker lives in Atlanta and runs his own ministry, Revolution. 
He preaches a message of self-worth and unconditional love to 
punks, Goths and gays. 
</P>
<P>
	``I dropped out of high school. I can barely write. I'm white  
trash,'' he said in the latest issue of Rolling Stone. 
</P>
<P>
	``But God has given me a gift -- to relate to people and to see  
the common sense of the Bible. The church needs to stop figuring 
out ways that they can fight Marilyn Manson and start accepting all 
types of people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bakker, 23, was just a kid when his father was charged with  
defrauding followers and went to prison, the family dynasty 
crumbled and his parents split up. He was left in the rubble with 
drug and alcohol problems. 
</P>
<P>
	``The punk groups really attracted me because they had this  
attitude like, `We'll accept you and everyone else can go to 
hell,''' he said. 
  	   	
</P>
