<HEADLINE> MetLife Said Near Deal With Insurer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. LOUIS (AP) -- Metropolitan Life Insurance Co. appears to have  
won the bidding war to buy the troubled General American Life 
Insurance Co. in a deal worth $1.2 billion, according to several 
news reports. 
</P>
<P>
	Larry Larance, a spokesman for St. Louis-based General American  
said the announcement of a new owner could come as early as today. 
The board of directors met Wednesday night to consider offers and 
proposals, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	MetLife's board already has approved a preliminary plan for the  
deal, Dow Jones News reported Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	MetLife would operate General American as a stand-alone brand  
and leave its headquarters in St. Louis, the St. Louis 
Post-Dispatch reported today. 
</P>
<P>
	MetLife, based in New York, is the nation's second-largest  
insurance company, with $357 billion in assets. It dwarfs General 
American's roughly $30 billion in assets. 
</P>
<P>
	Attempts to reach MetLife officials after business hours  
Wednesday were unsuccessful. 
</P>
<P>
	Larance said he could not comment on the Dow Jones report, but  
said a half-dozen companies have expressed an interest in buying 
General American since the company announced it was seeking a 
partner. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's no secret we have been negotiating with several  
companies,'' Larance added. 
</P>
<P>
	Larance declined to say who was interested, how many offers had  
been made or possible financial terms. He also declined to say if 
MetLife was among the suitors. 
</P>
<P>
	General American is seeking a buyer to take over the $6.8  
billion in ``funding agreements'' that sent it searching for a 
rescuer. General American couldn't quickly come up with the cash 
when 37 big institutional investors, mainly money-market funds, 
staged a run on $5 billion in General American contracts early this 
month. 
</P>
<P>
	Any deal would require the approval of regulators in both New  
York and Missouri. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
