<HEADLINE> Former Fugitive Sentenced to 7 Yrs. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GLOUCESTER, Va. (AP) -- A 16-year-old boy who allegedly faked his  
death to avoid going to jail for robbery has been sentenced to 
seven years in prison. 
</P>
<P>
	The sentence Wednesday was more than twice the three-year  
maximum Sage Weakland would have spent in a youthful offender 
program under a plea agreement reached after his conviction. 
</P>
<P>
	But he disappeared in July 1997 during a boating accident the  
night before his sentencing. 
</P>
<P>
	The boy's family maintained that he died, but the FBI arrested  
him July 14 in Las Vegas. Agents were acting on a tip from a friend 
who said Weakland's father helped the teen-ager get away. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm sorry for what I did,'' Weakland, now 18, told the judge.  
</P>
<P>
	The night before he was to be sentenced for a housebreak,  
Weakland and his father, Eugene, went fishing. Their boat slammed 
into an anchored ship, and father and son went overboard. 
</P>
<P>
	Eugene Weakland was rescued, but Sage was not found after  
authorities spent weeks looking for him with the aid of 
helicopters, divers and sonar equipment. 
</P>
<P>
	The father, who was not in court Wednesday, is under  
investigation and has already been charged with reckless boating. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
