<DOCNO> APW19990825.0217 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-25 08:31:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Little League Manager Sacrifices Job </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WILLIAMSPORT, Pa. (AP) -- Tony Rasmus had a choice to make: Stay  
on in his job as football coach at a small private school or help 
his two sons fulfill their Little League dreams. 
</P>
<P>
	It was a no-brainer.  
</P>
<P>
	``I made the decision to resign early on, for the good of the  
kids,'' said Rasmus, a former minor leaguer in the Anaheim Angels 
system and manager of the Phenix City, Ala., team that is three 
victories away from a Little League World Series championship. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a sacrifice but all this is worth it,'' Rasmus said  
before his team defeated Boise, Idaho 12-0 to advance to the U.S. 
championships. ``Shoot, I wasn't making a million dollars in the 
job anyway.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Still, signs pointed to Rasmus leaving his beloved Little League  
team behind. He had just been giving the responsibilities of 
coaching running backs and linebackers at the Glenwood School and 
closed on a loan for a house that would have enabled him to move 
the family out of their mobile home. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have four kids living in a trailer in a 10-foot-by-10-foot  
room,'' he said. ``At the time, my wife didn't think it was the 
smartest thing to do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But the thrill of watching 12-year-old Colby and 11-year-old  
Cory take the field in Williamsport is priceless, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Looking back, it was a super-good decision. I wouldn't have  
traded this for anything,'' Rasmus said. 
</P>
<P>
	After the team won its district championship last month, Rasmus  
knew he had something special. So he went into the athletic 
director's office on July 12 and told them he was considering 
leaving and taking another job close by. 
</P>
<P>
	``It sounded better than to say, `I quit my job for Little  
League,''' he said. ``They would have laughed me right out of the 
place.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It wasn't until a week -- and two no-hitters -- later that Rasmus  
signed his resignation letter with his squad going to the Alabama 
state championships. 
</P>
<P>
	At Williamsport, Phenix City has had its ups and downs. They  
lost their opening game 6-0 to defending champion Toms River, then 
rallied from a four-run deficit to take a 5-4 win over Brownsburg, 
Ind., on Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The pressure didn't seem to be affecting Rasmus' players before  
Tuesday night's game. A Phenix City win sets up a rematch with Toms 
River in the U.S. championship game Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	As metal bats pinged in the background and crowds cheered during  
an afternoon game, Colby signed autographs for two female fans, 
while other teammates ran onto the grassy hilly beyond the outfield 
fence to talk with family members. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was pretty sure he was going to stay with us,'' the  
soft-spoken Colby said between glances at the field to watch an 
ongoing game. ``He knows a lot more about baseball than most people 
do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rasmus said he has no hard feelings with the situation at  
Glenwood since he left on his own accord. The school already had 
recently lost two football coaches, and Rasmus wanted to make sure 
it had a full-time coach from the start of training camp. 
</P>
<P>
	There will be other jobs, he said.  
</P>
<P>
	``It just didn't seem fair to my (Little League) team,'' Rasmus  
said. ``It wasn't fair to say, `OK, guys, congratulations on this, 
but I've got to leave you now.''' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990825.0218 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-25 08:31:52 </DATE_TIME>
