<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Eaton Lays Off Thousands of Workers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TORONTO (AP) -- Troubled retailer T. Eaton Co., now going through  
liquidation, said Tuesday it has laid off or given termination 
notices to thousands of employees. 
</P>
<P>
	``Those employees whose services will be required during the  
liquidation have been advised to continue to report to work through 
the notice period,'' the company said in a release. ``Those 
employees whose services will not be required have had their 
employment terminated effective immediately.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The once-dominant department store chain, with 64 stores, has  
close to 13,000 full- and part-time employees. It was not clear how 
many workers were immediately laid off. 
</P>
<P>
	The company also announced the resignation of Brent Ballantyne  
as chief executive and president. He will stay on as a director and 
chairman. 
</P>
<P>
	``With the appointment of the interim receiver and the  
engagement of the liquidators, I did not think I could add any 
further value and it seemed appropriate to offer my resignation as 
president and chief executive officer,'' Ballantyne said in the 
release. 
</P>
<P>
	``I intend to continue on as chairman in order to lead the  
company through to the presentation of a proposal to its 
creditors.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Also Tuesday, trading on the company's stock was halted on the  
Toronto Stock Exchange due to ``failure to meet continued listing 
requirements.'' Eaton's shares plunged more than 43 percent Monday 
to close at 27 cents a share. The shares were valued at over $10 
each when the chain went public in mid-1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Eaton's said after an insolvency hearing Monday that a selloff  
of its inventory will start at mid-week in all its stores. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our management team is also continuing to explore all  
alternatives in order to preserve as much value for its 
stakeholders as possible,'' Ballantyne said after an Ontario 
Superior Court judge appointed a receiver and approved the 
liquidation. 
</P>
<P>
	With the chain $220 million in debt, Richter Partners of  
Montreal was appointed interim receiver while Gordon Brothers 
Retail Partners of Boston will liquidate the company's goods. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is designed to protect the greater body of creditors and  
employees,'' Eaton's lawyer Gordon Marantz of Osler, Hoskin &AMP; 
Harcourt told Justice James Farley. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
