<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-25 01:30:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> McCain Declares He's Anti-Abortion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Republican presidential candidate John McCain  
has not satisfied some conservative critics despite declaring his 
support for overturning the Supreme Court ruling that legalized 
abortion. 
</P>
<P>
	``I share our common goal of reducing the staggering number of  
abortions currently performed in this country and overturning the 
Roe vs. Wade decision,'' McCain said in a letter, released Tuesday, 
to National Right to Life Committee president Wanda Franz. ``I 
truly hope this clarifies any ambiguity on my position.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Arizona senator angered some social conservatives with  
recent remarks that appeared to soften his stance against abortion. 
His advisers said McCain was misunderstood. 
</P>
<P>
	In separate interviews, the senator had:  
</P>
<P>
	--Told the San Francisco Chronicle: ``I'd love to see a point  
where it is irrelevant, and could be repealed because abortion is 
no longer necessary. But certainly in the short term, or even the 
long term, I would not support repeal of Roe vs. Wade, which would 
then force X number of women in America to (undergo) illegal and 
dangerous operations.'' 
</P>
<P>
	--Told CNN that although he ultimately favored repeal of the 1973  
Supreme Court decision legalizing abortion, ``We all know, and it's 
obvious, that if we repeal Roe vs. Wade tomorrow, thousands of 
young American women would be performing illegal and dangerous 
operations.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Juleanna Glover Weiss, spokeswoman for GOP presidential rival  
Steve Forbes, said McCain was ``stuttering and stammering'' on the 
abortion issue. 
</P>
<P>
	Even after receiving McCain's letter, the National Right to Life  
Committee questioned whether he was backpedaling from his longtime 
anti-abortion views. 
</P>
<P>
	``Last week, he said he would not support overturning Roe vs.  
Wade in the short term or the long term,'' said the committee's 
political director, Carol Tobias. ``This week, he is saying he 
supports overturning Roe vs. Wade but he is not saying when. Does 
he mean in 200 years? In 50 years?'' 
</P>
<P>
	McCain spokesman Howard Opinsky replied that McCain ``has a  
17-year voting record of supporting efforts to overturn Roe vs. 
Wade and simultaneously reducing the abortion rate in America. He 
does that currently. He did that previously and will continue to do 
that as president.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Referring to the controversial quotes, Opinsky said McCain had  
responded to questions about Roe vs. Wade ``in a vacuum.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``While we work to overturn Roe vs. Wade, we must promote  
policies that reduce the number of abortions,'' McCain wrote. 
</P>
<P>
	McCain's letter detailed a long anti-abortion record, including  
his sponsorship of the effort to overturn President Clinton's veto 
of a bill banning late-term procedures called ``partial birth'' 
abortions. He also has opposed public financing of abortions, 
except in cases of rape, incest or a threat to the mother's life. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
