<DOCNO> APW19990825.0224 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-25 03:20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Talk Show Trial Races Toward Finish </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PONTIAC, Mich, (AP) -- With quick questions and well-practiced  
answers, the retrial of the man who killed a gay acquaintance after 
a taping of ``The Jenny Jones Show'' neared a finish. 
</P>
<P>
	Most of the witnesses in the retrial of Jonathan Schmitz had  
taken the stand twice before -- in Schmitz's 1996 trial, where he 
was convicted of second-degree murder in the death of Scott 
Amedure, and in the civil trial against the producers of the show. 
</P>
<P>
	Closing arguments were scheduled to begin today, with the jury  
asked to decide whether Schmitz committed second-degree murder or 
manslaughter when he shot an unarmed Amedure twice in the chest. 
</P>
<P>
	The shooting came three days after Amedure had revealed a crush  
on Schmitz during the show taping. 
</P>
<P>
	Schmitz, 29, was sentenced to 25 to 50 years in prison three  
years ago, but an appeals court overturned the verdict because of 
an error in jury selection. 
</P>
<P>
	Unlike the first trial, Schmitz's defense has not been able to  
bring up his mental history as a factor in the killing. Attorney 
Jerome Sabbota has also refrained from blaming the show, as 
Schmitz's lawyers did in his first trial. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, Sabbota sought to show that Amedure sparked his own  
death by pursuing Schmitz. 
</P>
<P>
	Sabbota said Amedure lied to Schmitz about the show, entitled  
``Same-Sex Secret Crushes,'' and introduced testimony that Schmitz, 
who says he is heterosexual, went to the show believing he would be 
reunited with an ex-girlfriend. 
</P>
<P>
	Sabbota argued that Schmitz should be convicted of manslaughter,  
which has a maximum sentence of 15 years in prison. The maximum 
sentence for second-degree murder is life. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990825.0225 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-25 12:30:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Volvo To Install LatAm Headquarters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAO PAULO, Brazil (AP) -- Aiming at a threefold increase in its  
Latin American market share, automaker Volvo will move its regional 
headquarters from Sweden to Brazil, a top company official said 
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Latin America market for prestige imported cars is one of  
the world's fastest growing, and in this sense Brazil is the 
region's most important country,'' said Luis Carlos Pimenta, 
general manager for Volvo's sales operations in Brazil. 
</P>
<P>
	Pimenta said that Volvo competes with Mercedes Benz, BMW and  
Audi in Latin America for sales of cars costing more than $30,000. 
</P>
<P>
	All of Volvo's sales from Mexico on down will be coordinated  
from the company's new Latin American headquarters, scheduled to 
open by the end of October in Sao Paulo. 
</P>
<P>
	Pimenta said the company will launch a $8 million marketing  
program to increase Volvo's prestige car market share in Brazil 
from its current 7 percent to 20 percent by the end of 2001. Of the 
8,500 such vehicles sold in this country in 1998, close to 600 were 
Volvos. 
</P>
<P>
	A similar market share increase should take place elsewhere in  
Latin America, Pimenta said by phone. 
</P>
<P>
	He said while Volvo does not discard the idea of eventually  
building its cars in Brazil, no such plans were being drawn up. 
</P>
<P>
	He said the Latin American headquarters would operate  
independently of Ford, which acquired a controlling share of the 
Swedish automakers in January of this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Volvo has a truck and bus production unit near the southern city  
of Curitiba. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990825.0226 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-25 10:16:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Emmys: Even Presenters Are Winners </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Let's say you're a star who failed to score  
an Emmy nomination. Or maybe, if you did, you're a long shot to win 
next month. 
</P>
<P>
	But you could at least serve as a presenter, for goodness sake,  
proving you have the stature to hold an Emmy statue even if you 
can't take it home with you. 
</P>
<P>
	You are Mr. or Ms. Television, and the show will not go on  
without you -- unless Don Mischer decides it will. 
</P>
<P>
	Mischer, producer of the Sept. 12 awards for the Academy of  
Television Arts &AMP; Sciences, knows how much industry members long to 
be associated with the high-profile ceremony. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have had cables sent to me by people who've said, 'I've got  
the dress, I just need the invitation.' I've had big bouquets of 
flowers sent by artists who want to do something on the show. ... 
Some will get the heads of big agencies to call you.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``There are many people who deserve to be on the Emmy Awards who  
we simply don't have room for,'' said Mischer. ``In the end, our 
job is to do what's best for the show.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A scant three weeks before the ceremony, he and his crew are  
balancing the big and small elements that can turn the three-hour 
broadcast on Fox (down from last year's four-hour, 50th anniversary 
blockbuster) into a thriller or a yawner. 
</P>
<P>
	There's the all-important display of stars, of course. Jenna  
Elfman (``Dharma &AMP; Greg'') and David Hyde Pierce (``Frasier'') were 
tapped this week as co-hosts. Presenters announced so far include 
Dennis Franz, Calista Flockhart, Sarah Michelle Gellar, David 
Spade, Dylan McDermott and Jon Stewart. 
</P>
<P>
	Decisions are being made about the show's theme (Mischer favors  
a millennium-tinged look to TV's future), comic relief and the clip 
packages for nominated series and performers. The mob drama ``The 
Sopranos,'' the leading nominee with 16 bids, and best-comedy 
contender ``Sex and the City'' will get especially careful 
attention. 
</P>
<P>
	The two HBO series, true to their carefree cable pedigree, brim  
with explicit language and story lines. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're trying to find scenes that don't have more than five or  
six bleeps,'' said Mischer. ``This show will probably have more 
bleeps than any other.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A veteran of five Emmy ceremonies, Mischer knows the potential  
pitfalls, some of which simply can't be avoided. 
</P>
<P>
	When a presenter's remarks fall flat or the stilted, scripted  
banter between two stars is painful to behold, the celebrities may 
have only themselves to blame. 
</P>
<P>
	``When you rehearse, that stuff emerges and you fix it on the  
spot. But fewer and fewer stars want to rehearse. Those who have a 
good sense of self-preservation will want to come to rehearsal, but 
a lot of stars say, 'Hey, just let me show up and do it.' '' 
</P>
<P>
	It is, after all, a nonpaying gig. But Emmy does have some  
lovely gifts for her guests: ``Treasure chests'' filled with 
several thousand dollars worth of products will be bestowed on 
presenters and nominees. 
</P>
<P>
	Dry mouth? Pop an Altoids or a bottle of Piper-Heidsieck  
Champagne. Got a sugar jones? There's Godiva chocolate. Stars also 
can divert themselves with their new camera, hide behind free 
sunglasses or lose themselves in a reverie about their two free 
nights at a posh Beverly Hills hotel. 
</P>
<P>
	Mere mortals can get their own taste of glamour, but for a  
price. An ``Emmy experience'' weekend, including two balcony seats 
at the Shrine Auditorium, was being sold to the public through the 
Los Angeles Sports &AMP; Entertainment Commission. 
</P>
<P>
	The $499 package includes a ``red carpet'' arrival at the  
ceremony, parties and, for a change of pace, a Los Angeles 
Dodgers-New York Mets game. Including outsiders is a boost for the 
ceremony, according to Mischer. 
</P>
<P>
	``We want to try to get real television fans into the hall. It  
adds a real spark of energy that you don't have when you're playing 
in front of an exclusively industry audience,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	All his work notwithstanding, Mischer still counts on  
serendipity. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's the things you can't plan and you can't produce that  
makes these shows interesting. My friend Gil Cates, who produces 
the Oscars, has said when you do these kinds of shows the award 
gods are either with you or ignore you.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Camryn Manheim's exuberant ``This is for all the fat girls!'' --  
which she shouted as she accepted her best supporting actress 
trophy -- was last year's golden Emmy moment, Mischer said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's really about when people win, how they feel, how they  
express themselves. These are the things that make the show.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere in television ....  
</P>
<P>
	NAPOLEON'S NAVY: In 1798, Napoleon sailed to Egypt to conquer it  
as a steppingstone to Britain's colonies in India. ``Napoleon's 
Lost Fleet,'' a Discovery Channel special debuting 9 p.m. EDT 
Sunday, Aug. 29, details the Frenchman's battle with Admiral 
Nelson's fleet and the search for the wreckage. In Aboukir Bay, 
divers and explorers probe the remains of L'Orient, Napoleon's 
flagship, and reveal its treasures. 
</P>
<P>
	Lynn Elber can be reached at lelber''at''ap.org  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
