<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Court Affirms $50 Million Verdict </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. (AP) -- A Florida appeals court on  
Wednesday rejected attempts by CSX Transportation to throw out a 
$50 million award to the widow of a Miami police officer killed in 
a train derailment. 
</P>
<P>
	The 4th District Court of Appeal said a lower court was right to  
approve the $50 million in punitive damages against CSX, a railroad 
company. 
</P>
<P>
	A jury ruled the company disregarded passenger safety when it  
cut its maintenance work force in half, saving itself hundreds of 
millions of dollars. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are disappointed ... and we are reviewing our appellate  
options,'' CSX spokesman Adam Hollingsworth said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Police officer Paul Palank was one of eight passengers who died  
when the Amtrak Silver Star slammed into a parked freight train in 
July 1991 near Camden, S.C. 
</P>
<P>
	Palank was traveling by train because he feared flying.  
</P>
<P>
	Investigators said the derailment was the fault of a corroded  
pin that caused a malfunction in a switch. 
</P>
<P>
	During a trial on the wrongful death lawsuit, there was  
testimony that CSX lied about how often it did maintenance checks 
on the tracks, and that it put passenger safety at risk by cutting 
back on its inspection staff to boost profits. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
