<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Russia's Avtovaz Expects GM Accord </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- Russia's biggest car maker, Avtovaz, said  
Wednesday that a long-awaited agreement for a joint car plant with 
General Motors Corp. is likely to be signed next month. 
</P>
<P>
	GM executives indicated, however, that details remained to be  
worked out despite two years of talks on the project. 
</P>
<P>
	``We hope to finalize the agreement in September, but it's too  
early to talk about further details,'' said GM spokesman Dmitry 
Choulga. 
</P>
<P>
	Avtovaz chief Vladimir Kadannikov told reporters at an annual  
international car show here that production at the plant could 
begin a year after the deal is signed. 
</P>
<P>
	Avtovaz has serious financial problems and has been looking for  
foreign partners to help it pay off $113 million in back taxes. 
</P>
<P>
	Kadannikov refused to say how much investment he expected from  
GM. Russian media have said GM would invest up to $200 million. 
</P>
<P>
	The plant, in the central Russian city of Togliatti, initially  
would produce up to 120,000 cars a year, including 30,000 Opel 
Astra models, Kadannikov said. The output eventually would rise to 
200,000 cars a year, he said. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
