<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bored Clinton Press Turns to Hoop </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EDGARTOWN, Mass. (AP) -- President Clinton spent another quiet  
day Wednesday close to his Martha's Vineyard beach house, but work 
was starting to intrude on his vacation. 
</P>
<P>
	The president spoke Tuesday night with Sen. Dianne Feinstein,  
D-Calif., who had just returned from China. On Wednesday he talked 
with his chief of staff, John Podesta, and national security 
adviser, Sandy Berger, who is briefing Clinton daily in 
anticipation of the president's meeting with Chinese President 
Jiang Zemin next month. 
</P>
<P>
	White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said it was unlikely that  
Clinton would remain close to the house during the last two days of 
his stay on Martha's Vineyard. The president planned to play golf 
Thursday and dine at the home of Mattel Corp. executive William 
Rollinick and his wife, Nancy. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Waiting for the vacationing Clinton to do something Wednesday  
was no picnic for the White House press corps. It was a basketball 
game. 
</P>
<P>
	As Clinton and his family lolled on a stretch of beach belonging  
to Boston businessman Richard Freidman, boredom reigned among the 
reporters and photographers who were waiting at the Edgartown 
School gymnasium in case the president made news. 
</P>
<P>
	Then someone found a basketball, and before long Lockhart and  
two of his aides were caught up in a brief but aggressive game 
against three members of the press corps. 
</P>
<P>
	The sound of squeaking sneakers and the thumping ball competed  
with the soft tap-a-tap-tap of reporters working on their laptop 
computers at long tables that took up most of the gym floor. 
</P>
<P>
	With a big advantage in 6-foot-7-inch Washington Times  
correspondent Bill Sammon, the press corps won 10-6. 
</P>
<P>
	``They were bigger than us,'' said Lockhart.  
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	There was a hint early on that levity would be the order of the  
day Wednesday when Lockhart caved to the will of the television 
reporters and donned a blazer to do an on-camera briefing. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've got a button-down shirt on, a nice jacket ... Oh! And my  
glasses,'' Lockhart said. He put on an oversized pair of purple 
rims, complete with fuzzy eyebrows and a hooked nose. ``OK, 
questions? Ready for television.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lockhart had balked at appearing before the cameras Tuesday  
while he was wearing shorts. His legs were ``not ready for prime 
time,'' he said. 




  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
