<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> White House Renews Tax Cut Attack </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Renewing its attack on the Republican tax cut  
plan, the White House contended Wednesday the proposal would result 
in nearly $100 billion in cuts to essential federal programs over 
the next five years, with Medicare and farm programs among the 
hardest hit. 
</P>
<P>
	The White House budget office report said that through the year  
2004, the GOP's 10-year, $792 billion tax cut proposal would 
trigger Medicare cuts of $41 billion and entirely eliminate 
veterans education, farm safety net and child support enforcement 
programs. 
</P>
<P>
	President Clinton, writing to House Speaker Dennis Hastert,  
R-Ill., and Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., from his 
vacation home in Martha's Vineyard, cited the budget office's 
figures and said it would be ``irresponsible'' for him to sign the 
GOP legislation. 
</P>
<P>
	House and Senate GOP leaders pushed the bill through Congress  
before lawmakers left for their August vacation. But they have yet 
to send it to the White House, where it faces a certain veto, so 
that Republican lawmakers can make their case to constituents 
before Congress returns in September. 
</P>
<P>
	Hastert's press spokesman, Pete Jeffries, stressed the  
Republican argument that the tax cut would consume only one-fourth 
of the estimated $3 trillion in Social Security and general budget 
surplus over the next decade, with the rest going to saving Social 
Security and Medicare, reducing the debt and paying for needed 
education and defense programs. 
</P>
<P>
	``We as Republicans believe that needs to be returned to  
Americans in the form of tax relief,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	But the White House and most Democrats argue that the GOP plan  
would use up all of the non-Social Security surplus and require 
major cuts in fundamental government programs. The administration 
says it could support a cut of about $250 billion, but only after 
the future of Social Security and Medicare is secured and money is 
set aside for social and defense programs. 
</P>
<P>
	``If your tax cut became law, it would leave America permanently  
in debt,'' Clinton wrote. 
</P>
<P>
	White House Office of Management and Budget Director Jack Lew  
said Wednesday's report, which outlines automatic cuts required by 
law if spending ceilings set in previous budget acts are not met, 
came up with ``distressing information and I hope it factors into 
their (the Republicans') thinking.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The OMB report concluded the GOP plan would require cuts of  
$99.3 billion through 2004 to mandatory, or fixed, government 
programs, with $41.4 billion coming from Medicare, and $19.3 
billion from the Commodity Credit Corporation and other crop 
insurance programs for farmers. 
</P>
<P>
	Child support enforcement would lose $10.3 billion and social  
services block grants would lose $4.4 billion, essentially 
eliminating those programs, and immigration support would drop by 
$4 billion. Veterans education and training benefits would lose 
$3.2 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hope Congress will treat this report as something of a  
wakeup call,'' Lew said. 
</P>
<P>
	The report does not take up discretionary, or non-mandatory  
spending, but Democrats say this too would have to be cut 
drastically to keep the budget in balance under a massive tax cut. 
</P>
<P>
	White House press secretary Joe Lockhart said Republicans, in  
talking to constituents back home, have discovered little public 
appetite for a tax cut involving severe reductions in spending for 
education, the FBI, the FAA and veterans programs. 
</P>
<P>
	But Hastert and Lott, wrote to Clinton last week that the  
estimated budget surplus is more than enough to cut taxes, save 
Social Security and Medicare and ensure adequate levels of 
government spending. 
</P>
<P>
	``Mr. President, there is no honest reason to veto this  
commonsense tax legislation,'' Hastert and Lott wrote. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
