<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Minneapolis Institute of Arts Toured </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- With only a few minutes to get away from the  
office, Scott Heinrich decided to take a quick tour of 17th century 
Europe. 
</P>
<P>
	Seated in a quiet niche at the Minneapolis Institute of Arts,  
Heinrich touched a computer display and listened as a narrator 
described politics in Italy at the time of the painters Poussin and 
Rembrandt, whose work hung just a few feet away. 
</P>
<P>
	The museum's new interactive kiosks help him understand art and  
its social context. 
</P>
<P>
	``Here you can come in just a couple of minutes, clear your head  
and go back to work,'' Heinrich said. 
</P>
<P>
	Heinrich and thousands of other museumgoers have embraced the  
kind of unintimidating familiarity that the MIA was striving for in 
the 10-year, $150 million expansion project it completed last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Exhibit space was boosted by 65 percent, allowing the museum to  
bring many of its works out of storage and add new ones. This 
summer, the new space is filling up with new art and new audiences. 
</P>
<P>
	The museum recently took delivery of the largest single  
corporate gift in its history: Norwest Bank Minnesota's 20th 
century collection of some 475 pieces of furniture, tableware and 
decorative objects. The collection, which includes a Mies van der 
Rohe chair and a Frank Lloyd Wright urn, is valued at more than $5 
million. 
</P>
<P>
	The MIA's renewal was guided by a single philosophy: Get the  
best art and get everyone to enjoy it. 
</P>
<P>
	To that end, the museum eliminated its entrance fee and rewrote  
labels and panels in less technical language. The flow was 
redesigned to make viewing easier, with displays in chronological 
or thematic order. More respect was given to non-Western art. 
</P>
<P>
	The changes also were cosmetic, with restoration of the main  
entrance to the 1915 neoclassical facade. And a new family center 
comes complete with stroller parking. 
</P>
<P>
	``The goal was to make the museum a more comfortable, more  
approachable place to view art,'' museum spokesman John Easley 
says. 
</P>
<P>
	Both experts and visitors say the MIA achieved that.  
</P>
<P>
	Museum experts now rank the MIA among America's top seven or  
eight ``encyclopedic,'' or non-specialized, museums. 
</P>
<P>
	``The museum seems more open,'' Jim Bennett, a longtime visitor,  
said during a recent trip to see the new Asian galleries. 
</P>
<P>
	Gazing at a 17th century Chinese marble screen, LeBron Zolbe, an  
Oklahoma City muralist and first-time visitor, said the flow of 
galleries steered her to artwork she might not have set out to see. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know of another museum that has done a better job,''  
said Peter Marzio, who is overseeing his own major expansion as 
director of the Museum of Fine Arts in Houston. 
</P>
<P>
	MIA's patronage has more than doubled since 1988 to an all-time  
peak of nearly 30,000 members and 500,000 visitors. Financial 
support has never been larger, with donations of $5.5 million in 
1998-99. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead of lumping together artifacts from Africa, Oceania and  
the Americas as the ``primitive'' poor cousins of European art, the 
galleries highlight each continent separately. Egyptian mummies and 
Zambian masks share new space on the second floor; on the third 
floor, elk skins and contemporary paintings show that American 
Indian art is as alive today as it was centuries ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Indeed, the MIA is at the forefront nationally for treating  
African or American Indian art as respectfully as paintings by 
Cezanne or Pollock, Marzio says. 
</P>
<P>
	The European and American collection is also presented with a  
twist -- the great masters' paintings are integrated with sculpture 
and decorative arts, so that the whole story of a community at a 
particular time can be narrated. 
</P>
<P>
	``Through these exhibits, we hook a lot of people,'' Easley  
says. ``Once we get people here for the first time, they want to 
come back.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
