NASDAQ Composite Index:       2805.60 + 53.23
Gold(final) -    $253.00    troy oz., NY Comex spot month Wed.

</P>
<P>
	Big-Ticket Items Big in Demand  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Orders for big-ticket manufactured goods  
vaulted ahead in July, spurred by demand for computers, machine 
tools, electronics and transportation equipment. The Commerce 
Department reported that orders for durable goods -- items expected 
to last at least three years -- rose 3.3 percent last month to a 
seasonally adjusted $204 billion. The 3.3 percent increase was the 
biggest gain since December 1998, when durable good orders rose 3.4 
percent. The report reflects a still-booming economy, powered by 
strong consumer spending and low unemployment, economists said. 

</P>
<P>
	Airline Workers Held in Drug Probe  
</P>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- Dozens of American Airlines employees and contract  
workers were arrested today in a federal investigation into a drug 
ring that authorities said used the airline's planes to smuggle 
drugs into the United States. Undercover agents from the Bureau of 
Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms also approached suspects about 
shipping guns and military-style explosives in the sting. At least 
48 people have been arrested. The suspects indicted were mainly 
ramp workers and baggage handlers, agents said. Shares in AMR 
Corp., American Airlines' parent company, rose 2 3/4 at 64 3/4. 

</P>
<P>
	ATM Network Heads Reassure Clients  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The heads of the country's ATM networks today  
urged consumers not to withdraw unusually large amounts of cash, 
while assuring them that their cards will work normally through the 
year-end date change. The nation's bankers, meanwhile, are 
distributing a folksy sample sermon for clergy to help them debunk 
fears of a Year 2000 catastrophe. The American Bankers Association 
is distributing to bankers a four-page homily to share with their 
local clergy. 

</P>
<P>
	White House Renews Tax Cut Attack  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Renewing its attack on the Republican tax cut  
plan, the White House contended today the proposal would result in 
nearly $100 billion in cuts to essential federal programs over the 
next five years, with Medicare and farm programs among the hardest 
hit. The White House budget office report said that through the 
year 2004, the GOP's 10-year, $792 billion tax cut proposal would 
trigger Medicare cuts of $41 billion and entirely eliminate 
veterans education, farm safety net and child support enforcement 
programs. 

</P>
<P>
	House To Hold Laundering Hearings  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The House Banking Committee will hold hearings  
next month on an alleged money-laundering scheme at the Bank of New 
York that federal investigators say involves the Russian mob. U.S. 
authorities are investigating the bank, where $4.2 billion passed 
through a single account in more than 10,000 transactions between 
October and March, The New York Times reported last week. It has 
been described as potentially one of the biggest money-laundering 
schemes ever uncovered in the United States. 

</P>
<P>
	Campbell Soup Revamping Labels  
</P>
<P>
	CAMDEN, N.J. (AP) -- Campbell Soup Co. is tampering with an  
American icon: the red-and-white soup label. The company says it's 
the most significant change in its history and will include 70 
varieties in its condensed soup line. The new label has a 
photograph of a bowl of soup at the center, a recipe on the back 
and a colored banner to distinguish the soup category. Since 1898, 
Campbell has only made 14 minor changes to the red-and-white label. 
The last change was made for select varieties in 1994 to mark the 
company's 125th anniversary. Campbell stock closed up 13/16 at 45 
5/16. 

</P>
<P>
	Justice Attorneys Seek Overtime Pay  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Lawyers who work for the Justice Department  
are pressing a class-action lawsuit that accuses the 
law-enforcement agency of illegally failing to provide overtime 
pay. The lawsuit says the department made ``a conscious decision'' 
to ignore a federal law that requires overtime pay for employees 
who work more than 40 hours a week. As many as 12,000 current or 
former Justice Department lawyers might seek damages of more than 
$500 million. 

</P>
<P>
	Disney Buys Into Online Toy Retailer  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The Walt Disney Co. has bought a majority  
interest in toysmart.com, an online educational toy seller. 
Disney's Buena Vista internet group will have an estimated 60 
percent stake in toysmart.com. Analysts say the deal includes $20 
million in cash for toysmart.com and $25 million worth of free 
marketing with Disney. The ads would appear on the Go Network, 
which includes ESPN.com and ABCNews.com and on other outlets, such 
as the Disney Channel. Stock in Walt Disney Co. rose 1/16 to 29 7/8. 

</P>
<P>
	New Web Page Design Language Planned  
</P>
<P>
	CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) -- An Internet standards body has proposed  
a new programming language for designing Web sites that would make 
it easier for Web pages to be displayed on handheld information 
devices. The World Wide Web Consortium proposed the use of XHTML, 
or Extensible Hypertext Markup Language, to help make Web pages 
readable on handheld computers, cell phones and other outlets 
besides desktop browsers. 

</P>
<P>
	German Cabinet Approves Budget Cuts  
</P>
<P>
	BERLIN (AP) -- Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder's Cabinet approved  
hotly debated budget cuts Wednesday that are designed to spur the 
German economy, fight joblessness and bolster the euro. Schroeder's 
effort to trim the nation's social safety net has sparked 
resistance among fellow Social Democrats. If passed by parliament, 
it would trim $16 billion from next year's budget. Its most 
controversial proposals include a clause raising pension payments 
only at the rate of annual inflation in 2000 and 2001. 

</P>
<P>
	Volvo To Install LatAm Headquarters  
</P>
<P>
	SAO PAULO, Brazil (AP) -- Aiming at a threefold increase in its  
Latin American market share, automaker Volvo will move its regional 
headquarters from Sweden to Brazil. ``The Latin America market for 
prestige imported cars is one of the world's fastest growing, and 
in this sense Brazil is the region's most important country,'' a 
Volvo official said. Volvo competes with Mercedes Benz, BMW and 
Audi in Latin America for sales of cars costing more than $30,000. 

</P>
