<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Russian Forces Drive Out Militants </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MAKHACHKALA, Russia (AP) -- Russian troops have regained control  
of all six mountain villages captured by Islamic militants in 
southern Russia more than two weeks ago, and were attempting to 
drive scattered groups of rebels from the region entirely, the 
military said today. 
</P>
<P>
	Military officials said most of the rebels have fled from  
Dagestan to neighboring Chechnya, the breakaway republic from which 
they came. The rebels are seeking to establish an independent 
Islamic state in southern Russia. 
</P>
<P>
	The operation against them ``is in its final stage,'' said  
Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev, on a trip with President Boris 
Yeltsin to the Central Asian nation of Kyrgyzstan. 
</P>
<P>
	Rebel leader Shamil Basayev appeared on Chechen television and  
claimed that the withdrawal from Dagestan was planned and would be 
followed by guerrilla attacks throughout the region. 
</P>
<P>
	``The first stage of our operation has been successfully  
completed and now we are getting ready for the second stage,'' 
Basayev said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russians have carried out daily bombing raids and artillery  
attacks, hammering rebels who seized the villages when they invaded 
the Caucasus Mountain region Aug. 7. 
</P>
<P>
	The outgunned militants said in the past few days that they  
might withdraw or redeploy forces rather than remain in the 
villages and battle the much larger Russian contingent. 
</P>
<P>
	The Defense Ministry said small groups of militants were still  
hiding in the mountains. Wounded Russian troops at a hospital in 
Makhachkala said rebel snipers were still active in many of the 
villages. The soldiers, who refused to give their names, said they 
were attacked in Tando, one of the most hotly contested villages. 
</P>
<P>
	According to the Defense Ministry, the militants had been  
completely driven from four villages by Tuesday night, while 
government troops had gained control over two other settlements and 
were sweeping through them today to clear out any remaining rebels. 
</P>
<P>
	Residents who fled the conflict weren't allowed to return home  
because the rebels heavily mined the villages before leaving, the 
Defense Ministry said. 
</P>
<P>
	Mine-clearing specialists, accompanied by trained dogs, searched  
for hidden explosives. Two Russian trucks and an armored personnel 
carrier were destroyed by the mines, but no one was hurt. 
</P>
<P>
	Government forces were preparing to launch a new operation to  
encircle and eliminate the remaining militants. 
</P>
<P>
	Russian military commander Col. Gen. Viktor Kazantsev on Tuesday  
said the rebels had 2,000 fighters and about half of them have been 
killed in the conflict. Rebel leaders have put their casualty 
figure at 32. 
</P>
<P>
	Kazantsev said 59 government soldiers and police officers were  
killed. 
</P>
<P>
	The fighting has been the worst in Russia since government  
troops withdrew from Chechnya nearly three years ago, giving 
Chechnya de facto independence as part of a peace deal. 
</P>
<P>
	Unlike in the 1994-96 secession war in Chechnya, the Islamic  
militants in Dagestan don't have wide support from the population. 
The republic's secular politicians and moderate religious leaders 
also oppose the militants. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990825.0235 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-25 10:30:39 </DATE_TIME>
