<DOCNO> APW19990825.0240 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-25 15:40:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> LPGA Oldsmobile Event Up for Grabs  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EAST LANSING, Mich. (AP) -- Karrie Webb, Meg Mallon, Dottie  
Pepper, Rosie Jones, Kelli Kuehne, Kelly Robbins. Take your pick. 
</P>
<P>
	All have gathered at Walnut Hills Country Club, and any one of  
them could leave town $105,000 richer on Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Defending champion Lisa Walters, who has undergone two  
operations this season, is unable to defend her Oldsmobile Classic 
title. But just about everybody who is anybody on the LPGA Tour is 
on hand, including four of the season's top 10 money-winners. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a solid field,'' said Rosie Jones, who beat Upper  
Peninsula favorite Becky Iverson and veteran Jan Stephenson in a 
playoff last week in the Firstar LPGA Classic at Beavercreek, Ohio. 
``It's a good golf course, too, probably one of the top 10 courses 
we play.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Webb, the top money-winner with more than $1.2 million, has to  
be the favorite when first-round action begins Thursday. She 
already has six victories this season, including the du Maurier 
Classic on Aug. 1 -- the circuit's fourth and final major of the 
season. 
</P>
<P>
	The rolling, tree-lined course has been set up at 6,191 yards  
and will play at par 72 for the women. Two days of rain in the area 
made Walnut Hills play a tad longer in the practice rounds. 
</P>
<P>
	If those conditions hold, it would favor long hitters like Webb  
and Robbins, the pride of Mount Pleasant, Mich. 
</P>
<P>
	``The course plays a lot longer,'' Kuehne said after a round in  
Wednesday's pro-am event. ``Where you fly it is where the ball 
goes, by and large. It's not rolling much in the fairways.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A wet, energy-sapping golf course is perhaps the last thing  
Jones needs. The playoff victory last week left her drained. 
</P>
<P>
	``After nine holes, it looked a little stormy and I was tired,''  
said Jones, who needed four extra holes to win it. ``When you win, 
you have some adrenaline sabotage. So, I went home and took a nap 
and went to a movie.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Stephenson, the 47-year-old Australian, hasn't won an LPGA event  
since 1987. That made last week's near-miss all the more 
frustrating. 
</P>
<P>
	``I feel like I can win any week now,'' Stephenson said. ``My  
coach, Mike McGetrick, keeps telling me I can win. He said if I 
would just keep some patience, I'd be fine. 
</P>
<P>
	``Every time I get off to a bad start, I get frustrated.''  
</P>
<P>
	Walnut Hills could be just the place to shed those blues. It is  
a course on which veterans have done well. Past winners in this 
field this week include Barb Mucha, Jane Geddes, Beth Daniel, Dale 
Eggeling, Michelle McGann and Pat Hurst. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm playing the best I have in a long time,'' Stephenson said.  
``We'll see what happens.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
