<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Harvard, Boston Settle Dispute </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Harvard University and Boston have reached a $40  
million agreement to settle a fight over the university's secret 
purchase of 14 properties in the city's Allston neighborhood. 
</P>
<P>
	The two announced Tuesday that Harvard will make $40 million in  
voluntary payments-in-lieu-of-taxes over the next two decades -- $12 
million more than a previous agreement between the school and the 
city. Harvard will also build 288 new units of graduate student 
housing on its Allston campus. 
</P>
<P>
	``The whole thing is a big deal and it's a signal of a very  
cooperative and progressive relationship between Harvard and the 
city that's been going on two years now,'' said Joe Wrinn, Harvard 
spokesman. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1997, it was learned Harvard secretly bought 52 acres in  
Allston for $88 million between 1988 and 1994. 
</P>
<P>
	Harvard used a private broker and didn't tell sellers, city  
officials or residents who was behind the purchases. Officials said 
they feared the owners would have raised the prices if they knew 
the buyer was the world's wealthiest university. 
</P>
<P>
	After the sale became known, Harvard donated land that will be  
the home of a new Allston branch of the Boston Public Library. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
