<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-Child Stars Squandered Riches </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Former child star Paul Petersen thought ``The  
Donna Reed Show'' gravy train would never end. He played Jeff Stone 
on the popular 1960s television show until he was 21, and there was 
quite a fortune in the bank. 
</P>
<P>
	``Lassie'' star Jon Provost was 3 when he started his television  
career. He ``basically retired'' with a nest egg when he was 18. 
And Brandon Cruz had a bundle of cash after ``The Courtship of 
Eddie's Father'' left the air. 
</P>
<P>
	That was then, this is now. These TV icons, riding high during  
the formative years of the baby boomer generation, squandered their 
riches, and now they are out there selling their tales. 
</P>
<P>
	Financial services giant SunAmerica Inc. is paying them to  
appear on talk shows to discuss how poor financial planning left 
them with little of their Hollywood fortunes. It is SunAmerica's 
way of promoting its retirement planning services. 
</P>
<P>
	Each of the former child stars has settled into  
non-entertainment careers. 
</P>
<P>
	Petersen, 53, founded the nonprofit A Minor Consideration, which  
serves as an advocate for the new generation of childhood stars and 
athletes. He talks about the ``terrible choices in my 20s: drugs, 
alcohol, bad people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said he bought 20 cars, five homes and 30 televisions.  
</P>
<P>
	``There was a pile of money, and the mistake I made is that I  
didn't save my savings. I thought this gravy train would 
continue,'' Petersen said. 
</P>
<P>
	He ponders: ``When I look back at buying a sports car at 17 and  
my first house in Beverly Hills, I think now, `Why didn't I buy it 
in Burbank?''' 
</P>
<P>
	Provost, 49, also has regrets.  
</P>
<P>
	He now works for an escrow title company in the Northern  
California community of Santa Rosa. His spending spree began when 
he dropped $6,000 (1960s dollars) for a Lotus sports car. 
</P>
<P>
	``I pretty much partied my money away,'' Provost said. ``During  
the 1960s and 1970s the motto was `live for today,' and we didn't 
really plan for the future. The money was there and I never really 
understood about money. 
</P>
<P>
	``I went out and bought cars. I was turned loose in a candy  
store, what can I say? It was instant gratification.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cruz, 37, remembers buying 12 surfboards, six wet suits and  
airline tickets in one day for an around-the-world surf adventure. 
He eventually lost a significant amount of his money in failed real 
estate deals. 
</P>
<P>
	These are the stories SunAmerica wants America to hear, and they  
are betting these familiar faces will appeal to the boomers. 
</P>
<P>
	SunAmerica won't say how much it is paying the former child  
stars. The firm made a $10,000 donation to A Minor Consideration, 
but Petersen said his fees for personal appearances are 
significant. 
</P>
<P>
	``Their target group is baby boomers and I'm a boomer myself,''  
said Provost, who isn't bashful about speaking in public. ``I enjoy 
being in front of people. It's in the blood I guess.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It's so easy to forget that the future is going to come,''  
Petersen said. ``If it takes a bunch of vintage celebrities to 
change the thinking, then that's what it will take.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Petersen said he recovered financially since blowing his  
fortune. 
</P>
<P>
	``Once I got my bearings, my life is fine. We're cool,'' he  
said. ``I've learned my lessons. But I'm concerned. I see my 
friends with pretty fancy ZIP codes who have no savings. If I can 
speak to them, then I feel I can speak to everybody.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Provost agrees they can have an impact.  
</P>
<P>
	``For people who grew up with Lassie and Timmy, they can relate  
to me because of the image I portrayed of being wholesome and 
honest. They'll know I've made mistakes and learned from them,'' 
Provost said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
