<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jumper Blames Shoe Co. for Injury </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- A college track star says a shoe that came apart  
just as he was about to high jump caused a foot injury and ruined 
his chances of making the Olympic team. He is suing. 
</P>
<P>
	Craig Lyon, captain of the track team at Augustana College,  
claims in his suit that a specialized sports shoe tore in half 
during his approach in the high jump last winter. He fell, injuring 
ligaments and bones in his left foot. He has been wearing a cast 
since the Feb. 26 track meet at Illinois Wesleyan. 
</P>
<P>
	He filed suit Tuesday in Cook County Circuit Court against ASICS  
Tiger Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	Lyon, winner of the NCAA Division III national championship his  
sophomore year, said the meet was the first time he wore the new 
Mega Hi-Jump shoes. 
</P>
<P>
	He had planned to participate in the Olympic trials next summer  
and is seeking more than $50,000 in damages. 
</P>
<P>
	ASICS representatives were not immediately available to comment  
on the lawsuit. 
</P>
<P>
	Lyons said doctors have told him that he has an 80 to 90 percent  
chance of being able to run again, but his future as a high jumper 
is questionable. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
