<HEADLINE> Telecoms Push European Shares Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- European stocks rose Wednesday, as top-performing  
telecommunications shares climbed across the Continent. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones Stoxx Index of 592 European companies ended 3.81  
points higher, or 1.2 percent, at 314.34, while the Dow Jones Euro 
Stoxx Index, which tracks 297 companies in countries joining the 
single currency, ended 5.24 points higher at 328.98. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones Euro Stoxx 50 Index closed up 75.42 points at  
3856.72, while the DJ Stoxx 50 Index ended 58.83 points better at 
2792.27. 
</P>
<P>
	Telecoms sector indexes were the day's best performers, fueled  
by talk of expansion, tie-up expectations and the lack of surprises 
on U.S. interest rates. 
</P>
<P>
	Tuesday's U.S. interest rate increase of one-quarter percentage  
point was expected, which relieved concerns about the immediate 
outlook for global interest rates. 
</P>
<P>
	In Frankfurt, the Xetra DAX index rose 1.4 percent to 5,400.32,  
aided by Deutsche Telekom's announcement it plans to expand 
internationally in mobile communications, online business and data 
communications and network access through mergers and acquisitions. 
</P>
<P>
	Mannesman, the telecommunications and engineering group, rose  
after it said it hopes to offer a five-year eurobond issue this 
week or the next to help refinance outstanding debt in acquired 
stakes of Omnitel and Infostrada. The news removed fears of a 
capital increase, a trader said. 
</P>
<P>
	London's FTSE 100 index rose 0.9 percent, to 6,369.5, with  
British Telecom gaining 5.9 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The Paris CAC 40 index ended up 2 percent to 4,629.23, with  
France Telecom rising strongly. The banking sector also rose. 
Banque Nationale de Paris, Societe Generale and the investment bank 
Paribas all gained. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares in French pay-television group Canal Plus climbed on  
speculation that Vivendi is planning to sell part of its 49 percent 
stake to German media group Bertelsmann. 
</P>
<P>
	Amsterdam's AEX rose 2 percent to 583.80, with publisher VNU up  
4.8 percent, after it posted a 16 percent rise in first-half income 
from consolidated operations. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
