<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Private Land Hidden in Park System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Privately owned land within the national parks  
is becoming increasingly valuable, raising concerns that 
development will threaten the federal park system, a conservation 
group said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The National Park Service as well as private groups have tried  
to increase purchase of such parcels -- known as ``inholdings'' -- 
but Congress has not provided nearly enough money to buy the 
thousands of acres that environmentalists say are in greatest 
peril. 
</P>
<P>
	``Within 84 million acres of the national park system, 7 million  
acres are privately owned,'' Paul Pritchard, president of the 
National Park Trust, said at a news conference. The group is one of 
a number of organizations that are trying to find ways to buy some 
of these lands and donate them to the park system. 
</P>
<P>
	Citing Park Service statistics, Pritchard said, ``On any given  
day 200,000 acres are under an immediate threat.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In its report the National Park Trust said that the threat to  
parks from the commercialization of ``inholding'' properties is 
growing significantly because the value of these lands in many 
cases has skyrocketed. 
</P>
<P>
	The report cited 110,000 acres of privately owned property in  
and next to 20 parks, valued at more than $70 million, as being at 
greatest risk of being sold for commercial purposes. The ``top 
targets'' list ranged from 9 acres within the Cape Cod National 
Seashore in Massachusetts, appraised at $2.8 million, to 86,426 
acres of the Catellus property at the Mojave National Preserve in 
California, valued at $7.1 million. 
</P>
<P>
	David Barna, spokesman for the National Park Service, said the  
agency was ``delighted that they're bringing attention to these 
pieces of property within the national parks that we'd like to 
acquire.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Agency officials said there are no restrictions on the use of  
privately owned land within the parks, although the owners must 
comply with local zoning requirements. ``The Park Service has no 
jurisdiction over it (and) ... no control over what they do with 
the land,'' said Elaine Sevy, an agency spokeswoman. 
</P>
<P>
	But Chuck Cushman, executive director of the American Land  
Rights Association, a property rights advocacy group, said concerns 
about inholdings are exaggerated. ``Most inholders do not want to 
sell their land and do not want to use the land for logging, 
condos, or other activities'' detrimental to the adjacent parks, he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	But Pritchard said ``the danger that this land could be sold for  
development, bulldozing, clear cutting or for other destructive 
purposes constitutes the single greatest threat to the system of 
national and state parks.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Congress has been reluctant to come up with money for buying  
land inside or next to federal park land. Pritchard's group said in 
1998 only $23 million was provided for national park land 
acquisition, a tenth of what the Park Service had sought. 
</P>
<P>
	This summer the House and Senate approved about half of the $295  
million the Interior Department had sought for its ``land legacy'' 
purchases, including funds earmarked to buy inholdings and land 
adjacent to federal parks. 
</P>
<P>
	One ambitious attempt to address the inholding problems has  
focused on the southern California desert. 
</P>
<P>
	A private group, the Wildlands Conservancy, recently began  
negotiations to buy 430,000 acres parceled out checkerboard-fashion 
in and around Joshua Tree National Park and the Mojave National 
Preserve in the desert. 
</P>
<P>
	The so-called Catellus property is up for sale. But the deal is  
still in preliminary stages and final approval will depend on $36 
million coming from the federal government. So far, the Senate has 
agreed to come up with only $15 million and the House none at all. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the more than 100,000 acres of inholdings cited by the  
National Park Trust as being in peril were 375 acres in the Pecos 
National Historic Park in New Mexico; 11 acres in the Keweenaw 
National Historic Park in Michigan; 40 acres in the Blue Ridge 
Parkway in North Carolina and Virginia; 315 acres in the Antietam 
National Battlefield in Maryland; and 17,321 acres in the 
Everglades National Park in Florida. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
