<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Judge Tosses Lawsuit Against Ford </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- Two days into the retrial of a $25 million  
lawsuit against the Ford Motor Co., a federal judge dismissed the 
case, agreeing with the automaker that the case lacked merit. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Judge Alexander Harvey II's ruling marked the  
second time David Binakonsky's family has been rebuffed in its 
attempt to hold Ford liable for an alleged design flaw in the 1988 
Econoline van. Fire caused by leaking fuel killed Binakonsky in 
1992 after his van plowed into a tree alongside a hilly road in 
Frederick County, the family argued. 
</P>
<P>
	Binakonsky was drunk at the time, the family acknowledged.  
</P>
<P>
	``We won without even having to call a witness because the  
plaintiff's case was so flimsy and preposterous,'' said company 
spokesman Jim Cain from Ford headquarters in Dearborn, Mich. 
</P>
<P>
	``It amazes me that the family believes they have a valid claim  
against Ford when clearly this driver was drunk, he had a history 
of drunk driving.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The family's attorney, Martin Freeman, said he will appeal.  
</P>
<P>
	``Our case is he did survive the impact and he would be alive  
today if it hadn't been for the defective fuel system,'' Freeman 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The family argued Ford is liable because the van didn't have a  
so-called ``check'' valve to prevent gasoline from reaching the 
engine compartment in an accident. The automaker also used plastic 
connectors and fuel lines even though they knew the devices were 
fire hazards, Freeman said. 
</P>
<P>
	The judge, however, didn't allow damaging Ford documents that  
proved some Ford employees had reservations about the plastic 
parts. The judge also ended the trial before the testimony of an 
automobile expert who could have proved harmful to Ford's case, 
Freeman said. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
