<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Evening Trading Begins With Trickle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Trading began with a trickle Wednesday in what  
amounted to the first real evening session ever held for individual 
investors on the East Coast and the first real afternoon session 
for those on the West Coast. 
</P>
<P>
	The new session from 6 p.m. to 8 p.m. Eastern time -- or 3 p.m.  
to 5 p.m. Pacific time -- is being offered Monday through Thursday 
for customers of Discover Brokerage and Dreyfus Brokerage Services 
on an electronic exchange named MarketXT. 
</P>
<P>
	A total of 142 orders were executed during Wednesday's two-hour  
session, with about $3.5 million worth of stock changing hands 
overall. However, there was insufficient volume to match up most 
buyers and sellers, with more than 1,000 orders going unfilled. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft grabbed top honors as the most active issue for the  
inaugural session -- although with just 5,500 shares changing hands, 
the term ``most active'' was a bit of a stretch. The software maker 
finished the MarketXT session at $95.56 1/4 a share, a gain of 25 
cents from the closing Nasdaq quote. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors have already demonstrated an appetite for making  
portfolio decisions at home, where they have more privacy and time 
to think. An estimated 20 percent to 25 percent of online trades 
are currently placed outside normal hours, and then executed when 
regular trading resumes in the morning. 
</P>
<P>
	While other brokerages and alternative markets have already  
announced plans to extend their trading hours in the coming months, 
only the discount broker Datek Online had officially launched an 
after-hours session before Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	MarketXT takes after-hours trading a step forward because the  
late session on Datek's Island ECN exchange only runs for an hour 
and fifteen minutes after the regular 4 p.m. close of the New York 
Stock Exchange and Nasdaq Stock Market. 
</P>
<P>
	Wednesday's launch by MarketXT, formerly named Eclipse Trading,  
comes amid a suddenly fierce scramble to roll out extended hours 
for individual investors as the stock market hits new highs. The 
Dow Jones industrial average set another record on Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Last week, ETrade Group said it will offer trading from 4 p.m.  
to 6:30 p.m. through Instinet, the busiest market when regular 
exchanges are closed, and the Chicago Stock Exchange disclosed 
plans to become the first traditional market to extend its hours. 
</P>
<P>
	A week earlier, America Online announced that it would provide a  
link to after-hours trading through Wit Capital later this year. 
</P>
<P>
	The impending competition has prompted NYSE and Nasdaq officials  
to announce that they'll introduce after-hours trading sometime 
next year. 
</P>
<P>
	For most individual investors, the new offerings mark the first  
time they're being given a chance to manage their portfolios or 
react to late-breaking news outside normal trading hours. 
</P>
<P>
	That privilege has been long-reserved for elite money managers  
handling large pools of money such as mutual funds. 
</P>
<P>
	And on the West Coast, where the daily close of regular trading  
comes at 1 p.m., extended hours mean that investors won't get shut 
out after lunch -- a long-standing gripe. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, the mainstreaming of after-hours trading has provoked  
some worries because it may expose investors to sharp price swings 
if there isn't sufficient demand to buy or sell a stock. 
</P>
<P>
	For that reason, many of the first after-hours services are  
requiring investors to specify the most they're willing to pay when 
buying or the least they're willing to take when selling. That 
means brokers carrying out the trades will be restricted in the 
deals they arrange. 
</P>
<P>
	Likewise, trading is being limited to major companies that are  
likely to generate sufficient volume for price stability. 
</P>
<P>
	Any changes in price that occur after hours won't affect the  
prices that appear in newspaper stock tables for that day's 
trading. Instead, after-hours price movements are reflected in the 
following day's opening quote. The after-hour prices also won't 
affect the closing quotes on market indexes and mutual funds, which 
are calculated at the 4 p.m. finish of NYSE and Nasdaq trading. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
