<HEADLINE> Belluzzo To Run Microsoft Web Unit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	REDMOND, Wash. (AP) -- Microsoft Corp. reportedly has chosen  
Richard Belluzzo, a computer industry veteran, to run its Internet 
operations. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft today would not confirm the reports.  
</P>
<P>
	Belluzzo, 45, resigned on Monday as chairman and chief executive  
officer of Silicon Graphics Inc., a position he held for less than 
two years. 
</P>
<P>
	The Wall Street Journal reported Tuesday that he's expected to  
start as head of Microsoft's Internet unit -- now called the 
Consumer and Commerce Group -- on Sept. 1. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have no comment for you at the moment,'' Microsoft spokesman  
Dan Leach said this morning. 
</P>
<P>
	Before he moved to Silicon Graphics, Belluzzo had a 22-year  
career at Hewlett-Packard, where he became the No. 2 executive. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft's strategy appears to be to transfer its strength in  
the personal computer business to the Internet commerce arena, 
experts say. 
</P>
<P>
	``The strategy now is to use its software strengths to create a  
transaction backbone for the Internet,'' Mark R. Anderson, 
president of the research firm Technology Alliance Partners, told 
The Times. ``And Microsoft is really pulling back from the media 
stuff.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft's recent Web investments focus mainly on  
communications, shopping, travel, scheduling and personal finance. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the company has pulled back from some of its media  
ventures, last week selling off its collection of city arts and 
entertainment guides, MSN Sidewalk, for about $240 million to 
Ticketmaster Online-Citysearch. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
