<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-25 10:19:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 'Scream' Writer Ditches Horror </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Reliving his traumas has become a lucrative  
business for Kevin Williamson, the horror screenwriter and 
``Dawson's Creek'' creator says much of his work is based on things 
that really happened to him. 
</P>
<P>
	It's definitely the case with his directorial debut, ``Teaching  
Mrs. Tingle.'' The fanciful tale of three high school students' 
revenge against a tyrannical teacher is based on a cruel schoolmarm 
who squashed Williamson's budding writing ambitions. 
</P>
<P>
	``She was so mean to me, she just hated me and I never knew  
why,'' Williamson says. ``She, like, really discouraged me from 
being a writer, to the point where she ripped up a short story in 
my face and almost sent me to the principal's office because she 
hated me so much. 
</P>
<P>
	``She basically just tried to crush the dream, you know? She  
basically said, `You'll never be a writer. Your voice should never 
be heard.''' 
</P>
<P>
	A similar academic drubbing a year or two later in a college  
writing class finished the job. 
</P>
<P>
	``They trashed me. And I said, `There's the answer. No writing.  
I can't write.' And I gave up on it until, like, nine years 
later,'' says the 34-year-old Williamson, who bounced back to 
become one of the hottest screenwriters in Hollywood, penning 
``Scream,'' ``I Know What You Did Last Summer,'' ``Scream 2,'' 
``The Faculty'' and ``Halloween: H20.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But it was a long haul back. He tried his hand at acting for a  
number of years before working on music videos, then was ready to 
give up on his Hollywood aspirations. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was severely unhappy because my life wasn't taking off, none  
of my dreams were coming true, nothing was happening for me,'' 
Williamson says. ``So I made a deal with myself that I would leave 
the business and move out of L.A. and try to find something else to 
do. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was going to go take a real estate course, but before I did  
that I said I'll write a script, and then just see. I always kept 
talking about it but I never did it, so I said, `If you just write 
it and then fail, then there's your answer, yet again.' And I wrote 
`Tingle.' That's what happened.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the emotional pain of his early journey toward success,  
Williamson wouldn't trade the experience for an easier one. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's sort of the irony of the whole piece. All those  
negative messages I got as a kid, those things like, `You're not 
good enough, you can't do this,' and `You can't do that,' are 
ultimately the things that fueled me and propelled me onward,'' he 
says. ``It just didn't happen in my time line.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He sold his first script, but it was never made into a movie, so  
it was a perfect choice for his directorial debut, and a decided 
departure from horror for a storyteller eager to avoid typecasting. 
</P>
<P>
	``I certainly didn't want to be defined as the Horror Guy the  
rest of my life,'' Williamson says. ``And I also wanted to say to 
the world that I can create an adult character. I'm not just about 
teen-agers.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Furthering that effort, Williamson is writing an all-adult film  
he'll direct next year and has moved on from the WB network's 
``Dawson's Creek,'' which will continue without him, to a new TV 
series, the upcoming fall drama ``Wasteland.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It deals with the lives of a group in their mid-20s struggling  
to make it in New York. ``Basically it's another autobiographical 
story, about me, my favorite subject,'' says Williamson, harking 
back to his days as a hard-up aspiring actor in the city. 
</P>
<P>
	The Steven Spielberg-adoring title character on ``Dawson's  
Creek'' is a thinly disguised teen version of Williamson, while 
``Scream'' was inspired by a frightening night he had while house 
sitting. 
</P>
<P>
	With a major career goal -- directing -- under his belt,  
Williamson is focusing on personal challenges, like trying to have 
a life. 
</P>
<P>
	``My whole goal this year was to slack off,'' he says. ``It's  
really hard, I'm having a hard time, because I can't stand it. I'm 
a workaholic. I'd rather work. I'd rather work than sit back and 
relax. I can't understand the concept really, so it's really hard. 
</P>
<P>
	``It wears me out to relax. Trying to relax takes so much  
work,'' he says, stopping suddenly at what he's saying. ``Sounds 
sick. I hear myself and say, `How pathetic is this guy?''' 
</P>
<P>
	Williamson, who grew up in rural North Carolina, is a  
fisherman's son who credits his yarn-spinning mother with fostering 
his natural storytelling bent. 
</P>
<P>
	``She can make washing clothes sound exciting, you know,'' he  
says. ``She just goes off in her Southern way, about anything, a 
trip to the store, a visit from a friend. And she has a flair for 
the dramatic.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And unlike some of the teens in his movies and TV show, he says  
his childhood was normal. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was never in one clique or circle, but I think I was kind of  
liked,'' he says. ``There weren't any big horror stories growing up 
and in high school.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Then where does his blistering talent for creating cinema terror  
come from? Williamson thinks it stems from his lively imagination, 
and one intense primal fear. 
</P>
<P>
	``What scares me? I'm scared of the dark,'' he says. ``When I  
was a little kid my mom and dad used to make me turn out all the 
lights because we didn't have any money. They said if you left the 
light on, it cost, like, a quarter per hour, so if I kept the 
lights on I'd get charged. 
</P>
<P>
	``So what I did was I made an agreement with myself that when I  
became an adult, I would leave all the lights on if I chose to. And 
so when you go into my house at any given moment, it's lit up. 
</P>
<P>
	``If I walk into a dark house, I go nuts.''  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
