<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Electric Chair Debated in Fla. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) -- The state Supreme Court has more than  
words to consider when deciding the fate of Florida's electric 
chair -- it has graphic color photos of the last victim. 
</P>
<P>
	A lawyer for Thomas Provenzano, the next man scheduled to die,  
held up two pictures Tuesday of Allen Lee ``Tiny'' Davis strapped 
in the chair minutes after being executed. 
</P>
<P>
	In one, the upper half of Davis' face is purplish and his  
features are scrunched together. A line of blood stretches down 
from beneath his leather mask. 
</P>
<P>
	Justice Harry Lee Anstead called the images of Davis  
``heinous,'' ``horrible'' and ``right out of some horror movie.'' 
He challenged the lawyer representing the state to defend them. 
</P>
<P>
	``Can you hold that picture up to the people of the state of  
Florida and say this is what we want to do when we are taking a 
person's life through due process?'' Anstead asked Richard Martell, 
chief of capital appeals for Attorney General Bob Butterworth. 
</P>
<P>
	Martell agreed the photographs were graphic but disagreed they  
were reason to retire the electric chair. While electrocution is 
unpleasant, he said, that doesn't make it unconstitutional. 
</P>
<P>
	``Any execution is going to involve certain things no matter how  
it's carried out,'' Martell said. ``It's going to involve fear, 
it's going to involve ... discomfort.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Later, Justice Leander Shaw asked Martell if death by guillotine  
would be considered constitutional. Martell replied that it would 
not. 
</P>
<P>
	``But that's pretty painless, isn't it?'' asked Chief Justice  
Major Harding, who voted to uphold the electric chair in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Davis was executed July 8 for the 1982 murders of a pregnant  
Jacksonville woman and her two young daughters. His nose started 
bleeding just before the current was sent through his body and the 
bloody mess saved Provenzano from going to the electric chair 24 
hours later. 
</P>
<P>
	Florida's high court ordered a halt to further executions until  
Sept. 14 and ordered a judge in Orlando to hold a hearing on 
operation of the chair. 
</P>
<P>
	Circuit Judge Clarence Johnson ruled three weeks ago that  
electrocution does not violate the constitutional ban on cruel or 
unusual punishment. Provenzano's lawyers appealed to the high 
court. 
</P>
<P>
	Provenzano, 50, is condemned for the 1984 murders of two  
bailiffs. A third bailiff was left paralyzed after Provenzano 
opened fire in an Orlando courtroom. 
</P>
<P>
	Three states besides Florida -- Alabama, Georgia and Nebraska --  
still use electrocution as the sole method of execution. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
